<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Teamsters-Auto Proposal Highlights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Highlights of a proposed new Teamsters union contract with  
companies that haul new cars and trucks to dealerships nationwide. 
The four-year contract, which affects about 12,800 drivers, 
mechanics and yard and office workers, must still be ratified by a 
vote of union members. 
</P>
<P>
	--A $1,500 bonus for workers this year in lieu of a raise, with  
50-cent increases in hourly wages during the three subsequent 
contract years. 
</P>
<P>
	--New retirement benefits available after 25 years of work,  
including pension increases and health insurance eligibility 
starting at age 55 instead of age 57. Also, all retirees over age 
65 would get new prescription drug benefits to supplement 
government Medicare coverage. 
</P>
<P>
	--More leeway for trucking companies to assign full-time  
mechanics flexible schedules in order to help cover weekend hours -- 
for example, four 10-hour days rather than five 8-hour days. 
</P>
<P>
	Left out of the agreement: company proposals to pay newly-hired  
drivers less than current contract wages, use part-time workers, 
and use Mexican drivers to deliver vehicles in the United States 
after the U.S.-Mexican border opens up Jan. 1 under the North 
American Free Trade Agreement. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
