<DOCNO> APW19990602.0010 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 21:10:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Steel Producers Seek More Tariffs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Domestic steel producers hurt by low-priced  
imports are pressing ahead with new requests for punitive tariffs 
despite recent reductions in shipments from Japan and other 
countries. 
</P>
<P>
	The industry filed its latest complaints Wednesday, asking the  
federal government to impose tariffs on a high-grade product called 
cold-rolled, flat carbon steel. 
</P>
<P>
	One steel executive said cases targeting steel rail and tin also  
are in the works as part of the industry's assault on imports, 
which reached record levels last year. U.S. producers blame the 
imports for thousands of layoffs nationwide. 
</P>
<P>
	``Many cases have been brought, and I believe more will be  
brought,'' said Curtis H. Barnette, chairman and chief executive of 
Bethlehem Steel Corp. ``It's accurate to say there are injurious 
imports in other product areas.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The cold-rolled complaints came despite reductions in imports by  
roughly 40 percent since November. U.S. producers say foreign 
countries continue to flaunt U.S. trade laws that prohibit unfair 
pricing practices. 
</P>
<P>
	``Countries that ignore our laws and international agreements  
should have learned by now we will use every means available to 
stop them,'' said Richard K. Riederer, president and chief 
executive of Weirton Steel Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	Bethlehem Steel, Weirton Steel and six other companies joined  
the United Steelworkers of America in accusing a dozen countries, 
including Japan and Russia, of unfair pricing practices. 
</P>
<P>
	The cases represent the third major round of trade complains in  
the wake of the Asian economic crisis, which reduced demand for 
steel abroad and led foreign producers to find an outlet in a 
healthy U.S. economy. 
</P>
<P>
	A Japanese steel executive, Hidenori Tazawa of NKK America Inc.,  
said the latest complaint ``has absolutely no economic or factual 
basis ... (and) only indicates the lengths to which U.S. steel 
mills are willing to go to stifle legitimate domestic and 
international competition.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The filings with the Commerce Department and the U.S.  
International Trade Commission seek steel tariffs to effectively 
raise prices of foreign shipments. The targeted countries are 
Argentina, Brazil, China, Indonesia, Japan, Russia, South Africa, 
Slovakia, Taiwan, Thailand, Turkey and Venezuela. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. industry accused the 12 countries of selling goods in  
the United States below production costs or home-market prices. 
Brazil, Indonesia, Thailand and Venezuela also were charged with 
subsidizing their producers to artificially lower prices. 
</P>
<P>
	The Commerce Department already has ruled that Japan illegally  
sold the industry's leading product, hot-rolled carbon steel, at 
unfair prices. The U.S. International Trade Commission is to 
determine next week whether the pricing practices warrant tariffs. 
Similar cases are pending against Russia and Brazil. 
</P>
<P>
	The latest product targeted, cold-rolled flat carbon steel, is  
pressed from hot-rolled sheets into a thinner, stronger material 
that commands a higher price. Typical applications include washing 
machines, refrigerators and some internal auto parts. 
</P>
<P>
	The other companies filing the cold-rolled complaints are Gulf  
States Steel, Ispat Inland Inc., LTV Steel Co. Inc, National Steel 
Corp., Steel Dynamics Inc. and U.S. Steel Group. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
