<DOCNO> APW19990602.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 13:40:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Charismatic Weathers Stormy Trip </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Charismatic proved a good traveler on a stormy  
trip Wednesday from Louisville to Belmont Park, where the colt will 
try to become a Triple Crown champion by winning the Belmont 
Stakes. 
</P>
<P>
	Also on the flight was Silverbulletday, who will be making her  
debut against males in quest of a 12th victory in 13 starts. 
</P>
<P>
	``We had bad weather and were delayed leaving Louisville -- high  
storms and crackling lightning,'' said D. Wayne Lukas, 
Charismatic's trainer, who was on the plane. ``All the horses 
traveled just great except Silverbulletday.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lukas looked at Bob Baffert, the filly's trainer, who arrived in  
New York on Tuesday night. He then laughed and said, ``She was 
reluctant to get on. She protested every step of the way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The strapping chestnut colt and the bay filly are a two-horse  
story in a 12-horse race. 
</P>
<P>
	Charismatic, who ran for a $62,500 claiming tag Feb. 11, will be  
trying to become the 12th horse to sweep the Kentucky Derby, 
Preakness and Belmont Stakes and the first since Affirmed in 1978. 
</P>
<P>
	Should he collect first-place money of $600,000 from a $1  
million purse and also earn a Visa-sponsored $5 million bonus to 
any horse winning all three races, Lukas would become the first 
trainer to top $200 million in earnings. The late Charlie 
Whittingham is second with about $110 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Charismatic is owned by Bob and Beverly Lewis, owners of the  
Baffert-trained Silver Charm. Silver Charm failed to win the Triple 
Crown when he finished second in the 1997 Belmont. 
</P>
<P>
	Baffert also failed to win the Triple Crown last year when Real  
Quiet, owned by Mike Pegram, Silverbulletday's owner, was beaten a 
nose by Victory Gallop. 
</P>
<P>
	Lewis has no problem with Baffert trying to spoil his colt's  
Triple Crown bid. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've said to all of you over the past two or three weeks,  
bring them on, bring them all on,'' he said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Of the 25 Belmonts in which the Triple Crown was at stake,  
Saturday's field is the second largest. Thirteen started in 1971 
when Canonero II finished fourth. The biggest field for a 
successful Triple Crown was eight when Seattle Slew won in 1977. 
</P>
<P>
	Silverbulletday will be only the 21st filly in 131 Belmonts. The  
winners were Ruthless in the first Belmont in 1867 and Tanya in 
1905. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to find out if she fits,'' Baffert said. ``I think  
she fits. A mile and a half -- I don't know.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She will be ridden by Jerry Bailey because Gary Stevens, her  
regular jockey, is riding in England. 
</P>
<P>
	``The filly will add a great deal of spice,'' Lukas said. ``Half  
the world is women. She'll have a built-in rooting second that 
don't ever read the (Racing) Form.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Silverbulletday is the 4-1 early third choice behind Charismatic  
(2-1) and Menifee (7-2). Charismatic was 31-1 in the Derby and 8-1 
in the Preakness. 
</P>
<P>
	Menifee, runner-up in the Derby and Preakness, is trained by  
Elliott Walden. Walden is also the trainer of Victory Gallop, who 
preceded his Belmont victory with seconds in the first two races. 
</P>
<P>
	Silverbulletday will start from the No. 3 post, with  
Charismatic, ridden by Chris Antley, going from No. 4. Menifee, 
ridden by Pat Day, will start from the No. 10 post. 
</P>
<P>
	Post-position is not that important in the Belmont. Because of  
the distance of the race and the track's sweeping turns, there is 
time to sort things out. 
</P>
<P>
	Other than Silverbulletday, Best of Luck (6-1), the Peter Pan  
winner, is the shortest-priced of five 3-year-olds making their 
debuts in Triple Crown competition. 
</P>
<P>
	The other four are Vision and Verse, Prime Directive and Pineaff  
-- 1-2-3 in the Illinois Derby -- and Teletable, whose four career 
starts all have been in maiden races. Teletable's only win came in 
his last start Feb. 15 at Gulfstream Park. 
</P>
<P>
	Back for another crack at Charismatic are the Nick Zito-trained  
pair of Stephen Got Even and Adonis, Lemon Drop Kid and Patience 
Game. 
</P>
<P>
	Stephen Got Even finished 14th in the 1 1/4-mile Derby after a  
rough trip, then improved to fourth in the 1 3-16-mile Preakness. 
Adonis, 17th in Derby, also after traffic problems, finished sixth 
in the Preakness. 
</P>
<P>
	Lemon Drop Kid finished ninth in the Derby, skipped the  
Preakness and finished third in the Peter Pan. Patience Game won 
the Derby Trial, skipped the Derby and finished fifth in the 
Preakness. 
</P>
<P>
	The Belmont held a traditional blind draw. Had Charismatic drawn  
No. 4 in the Derby or Preakness, Lukas would have been fourth in 
the selection order and could have chosen any remaining 
post-positions. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
