<DOCNO> APW19990602.0012 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 03:20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> The Breaks Eventually Even Out </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Two of the worst calls in the history of televised sports belong  
to baseball. Combined, they make the best possible argument for 
keeping instant replay as far from the game as possible. 
</P>
<P>
	There wouldn't even be a debate except that on Monday veteran  
umpire Frank Pulli did something unseen in the five decades since 
somebody first shrunk the national pastime to the size of a picture 
tube. He wandered over to a TV camera and asked to have a second 
look. 
</P>
<P>
	What Pulli did was watch a fifth-inning fly ball hit by  
Florida's Cliff Floyd -- over and over. It touched off a sequence as 
confusing as it was comical. 
</P>
<P>
	Floyd claimed his drive bounced off the facade behind the  
left-field scoreboard in Miami for a homer. Second-base ump Greg 
Gibson said it hit the scoreboard for a double. 
</P>
<P>
	The Marlins argued, the umpires conferred and Pulli, the crew  
chief, changed the ruling. Home run. Then the Cardinals protested, 
Pulli consulted a TV camera near the Marlins dugout, and switched 
the call again. Double. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, the umpire's boss struck back.  
</P>
<P>
	``Use of the video replay is not an acceptable practice. Part of  
the beauty of baseball is that it is imperfect,'' NL president Len 
Coleman said. ``Players make errors. Managers are constantly 
second-guessed. But the game is played and determined by two teams 
between the white lines.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Not always -- as the following two examples prove:  
</P>
<P>
	Hands-down winner of the worst call ever is umpire Don  
Denkinger. With St. Louis leading 1-0 in the ninth inning of Game 6 
of the 1985 World Series, Denkinger ruled Kansas City's Jorge Orta 
beat out a grounder to first -- though replays clearly showed 
otherwise. 
</P>
<P>
	The call helped Kansas City win that game to tie the Series 3-3.  
The Royals won Game 7 when Denkinger, working behind the plate, 
repeatedly got into it with Cards manager Whitey Herzog and pitcher 
Joaquin Andujar and wound up ejecting both. 
</P>
<P>
	The Game 6 call was so awful that after a while, Denkinger took  
a perverse pride in having made it. He didn't just own up to the 
mistake, he had a framed print displayed prominently in his home. 
By the time he retired last fall, Denkinger sounded wistful -- if 
somewhat deluded -- in saying few people even remembered it any 
more. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm still constantly reminded by some fans from St. Louis,''  
he said. ``But time has a great way of healing. Basically, it is 
pretty well forgotten.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The next worst call ever televised was made by umpire Rich  
Garcia in Game 1 of the 1996 AL championship. With the Orioles 
leading 4-3 in the bottom of the eighth, New York's Derek Jeter hit 
a fly ball to the right-field wall. Baltimore outfielder Tony 
Tarasco parked underneath the ball and prepared to make the catch. 
But a 12-year-old Yankee fan named Jeff Maier reached over the 
fence with his own baseball glove and deflected it into the stands. 
</P>
<P>
	Though replays would later prove him wrong, too, Garcia ruled no  
interference and declared Jeter's fly a game-tying home run. The 
Yankees won 5-4 in 11 innings, and went on to win the ALCS and 
World Series. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm starting to understand what it did,'' Jeff said. ``It  
struck me this morning when I woke up. Wow! I may have really 
helped the Yankees out.'' 
</P>
<P>
	What these two episodes prove beyond a doubt is that life isn't  
fair. 
</P>
<P>
	It's easy to make more neutral arguments against instant replay  
-- especially in baseball. NL president Coleman said it eloquently: 
Errors by everybody involved are part of the folklore of the game. 
On top of that, there is not a decisive camera angle on every play; 
the game is too long as it is; and its very foundation -- calling 
balls and strikes -- is built on one person making sound judgments. 
</P>
<P>
	But the real threat to the game is the notion that complaining  
loud or long enough, or looking at the replay enough times, is the 
way to guarantee justice. 
</P>
<P>
	Everybody who saw the Game 6 call -- including Denkinger -- knew  
it was wrong a few seconds after it happened. The Cardinals -- 
especially Herzog and Andujar -- couldn't get over it. It wound up 
costing them the World Series. 
</P>
<P>
	What they didn't learn is the lesson people who get bad calls  
outside the white lines repeat over and over: The breaks even out. 
Eventually. 
</P>
<P>
	And sometimes, they actually do. Forgotten in all the uproar  
over Maier's impetuous stab at the baseball was what happened just 
a few weeks earlier. Roberto Alomar, then playing for Baltimore, 
had spit on an ump and then made a mockery of baseball's 
ineffective justice system by clinching both a wild-card spot and 
the divisional series for the Orioles with clutch hits in games he 
shouldn't have been allowed to play. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Jim Litke is a sports columnist for The Associated Press. Write  
to him at: jlik@ap.org. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
