<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 4 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	9 Die in Ark. Plane Crash Landing  
</P>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- A coroner has confirmed that nine  
people were killed when an American Airlines jetliner skidded off a 
runway while landing during a storm last night. The deaths are the 
first on a major U.S. airline in nearly 1 1/2 years. The dead were not 
immediately identified, except for Flight 1420's pilot, Capt. 
Richard Buschmann, the airline's chief pilot in Chicago. The jet 
was headed to Arkansas from Dallas and crashed amid rough weather 
at the Little Rock airport just before midnight. More than 80 
others on board were treated for injuries at hospitals. There were 
also about 50 others who didn't require treatment. 

</P>
<P>
	US Seeks More Normal Trade With China  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton plans to extend normal trade  
relations with China for another year, White House officials said 
today, despite opposition from Congress. The annual recommendation 
for ``most-favored nation'' status comes at a time when allegations 
that China stole sensitive nuclear secrets from U.S. research 
facilities and NATO's mistaken bombing of the Chinese Embassy in 
Belgrade have strained U.S. relations with Beijing. But aides say 
Clinton is convinced that continued engagement with China is key to 
improving relations. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Ups Kosovo Commitment  
</P>
<P>
	COLORADO SPRINGS, Colo. (AP) -- President Clinton has raised the  
U.S. commitment to a Kosovo peacekeeping force from 4,000 to 7,000 
troops today, saying: ``We have a moral responsibility to oppose 
crimes against humanity.'' NATO has proposed an international force 
of some 50,000 troops for Kosovo peacekeeping. Meanwhile, Russian 
and European envoys flew to Yugoslavia's capital for talks with 
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic today after resolving many 
major differences of a Kosovo peace plan. The talks with Milosevic 
began early this evening. 

</P>
<P>
	Killing Halts Paris Transportation  
</P>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- A strike by transport workers angry about the  
killing of a co-worker paralyzed public transportation in Paris and 
its suburbs today. The deadly attack against Eric Douet was only 
the latest in a rising number of assaults against French transport 
workers. Douet was beaten to death by a peddler he had confronted. 
The government responded to the rising violence by deploying elite 
police on trains and buses, but the transport union said the 
measures weren't enough. Meanwhile, thousands of French commuters 
walked through the muggy weather to work. 

</P>
<P>
	World Bank Estimates 200M New Poor  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The World Bank in its annual update on global  
poverty estimates there are millions of ``newly poor'' people, and 
recommends urgent changes in financial rescue programs. The bank 
said programs, including unemployment insurance and subsidized 
school fees, are needed to avoid and deal with financial crises. 
The bank responded to data showing poverty rising again in India, 
continuing to go up in Africa and sharply worsening across Eastern 
Europe and Central Asia. The bank said the number of people 
classified as living in abject poverty rose 200 million in 1993 to 
1.5 billion. 

</P>
<P>
	Iraq Faces Food 'Catastrophe'  
</P>
<P>
	BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) -- Iraq is enduring its worst drought in  
nearly 100 years and will soon face a food ``catastrophe'' if new 
aid funds are not immediately found, U.N. and Iraqi officials said 
today. According to figures released yesterday by the U.N., Iraq 
has lost about 70 percent of its crops in the country's 
breadbasket. An Iraqi agriculture official said water levels across 
Iraq were only 43 percent of normal. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Down 25  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks are lower today as investors begin  
preparing for a possible increase in interest rates when the 
Federal Reserve meets later this month. Just before 4 p.m. EDT, the 
Dow industrials were down 25.65 points at 10,570.61. Decliners on 
the NYSE lead advancers 1,705-1,231. The Nasdaq was up 20.51 at 
2,432.54. 

</P>
<P>
	Devil Rays Select Hamilton No. 1  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Tampa Bay Devil Rays made Josh Hamilton  
today the first high school player to go No. 1 in the baseball 
draft since Alex Rodriguez went to Seattle in 1993. Hamilton, an 
outfielder at Athens Drive High in North Carolina, hit .514 with 13 
homers and 36 RBIs this season. Five of the first six players taken 
in the draft are high schoolers. Pitcher Josh Beckett, from Spring 
High in Texas, went second to Florida. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by VINCENT CINISOMO  

  	   	
</P>
