<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 22:20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lawsuit Filed Against Gunmakers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAMDEN, N.J. (AP) -- Camden County has joined the list of  
governments suing the gun industry to recover costs stemming from 
handgun violence. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit does not specify a damage amount, but officials said  
Wednesday that the county has spent millions cleaning up the damage 
wrought by firearms. 
</P>
<P>
	The county, the first local government to file such a suit in  
the state, wants to recoup part of the cost of running offices for 
the prosecutor, sheriff and medical examiner, and the juvenile 
detention center and county jail, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit, filed Tuesday in U.S. District Court, also seeks to  
compel the gun industry to use so-called ``smart gun'' technology, 
rendering guns inoperable by anyone except the registered owner. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, 30 people were killed by handguns in Camden County,  
across the Delaware River from Philadelphia. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit names 21 gun manufacturers, and also includes 20  
``John Doe'' manufacturers, distributors and dealers whose names 
are not yet known. 
</P>
<P>
	Nearly a dozen municipal or county governments have sued,  
including New Orleans, Chicago, Miami and Dade County, Fla.; 
Bridgeport, Conn.; Atlanta; Cleveland; Detroit and Wayne County, 
Mich.; and Cincinnati. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990602.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 09:30:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Continental Involved in Aeroperu </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LIMA, Peru (AP) -- U.S.-based Continental Airlines has agreed to  
take a 49 percent stake in Peru's flagship airline Aeroperu, which 
had grounded its flights in March while saddled with $174 million 
in debt, Aeroperu officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials at the airlines, along with Aeroperu's debtors,  
hammered out a debt restructuring agreement to refloat Aeroperu 
with a 30 percent stake in the airline going to debtors, 16 percent 
to Peru's government and 5 percent to workers, Aeroperu President 
Roberto Abusada said Tuesday night. 
</P>
<P>
	The stake Continental will acquire is worth about $30 million,  
said Hugo Silva, a spokesman for Indecopi, the state agency 
overseeing the deal. 
</P>
<P>
	Continental officials were not immediately available for  
comment. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S.-based Delta and Aeromexico had each held 35 percent shares  
of Aeroperu, but had dissolved their stakes earlier in the year, 
deepening Aeroperu's financial problems. 
</P>
<P>
	Aeroperu's shutdown had left Peru with just one major air  
carrier, Aerocontinente, to serve its internal market, affecting 
tourism in the poor South American nation, tour operators said. 
</P>
<P>
	Aeroperu is expected to resume its flights by June 22, Abusada  
said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
