<DOCNO> APW19990602.0024 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 16:20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> McCain Wants Social Security Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SUN CITY, Ariz. (AP) -- Telling senior citizens Wednesday that  
Social Security is little better than burying savings in a tin can, 
Republican presidential hopeful John McCain advocated letting 
people invest some Social Security tax dollars in the stock market. 
</P>
<P>
	The three-term senator, flanked by posters of himself as a Navy  
pilot in Vietnam, stepped away from Kosovo, the issue that has 
given him a national spotlight, to tell a crowd of about 70 people 
in this retirement community that Social Security must be reformed. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't come here to warn you that your Social Security would  
stop coming,'' he said. ``That's not going to happen. This issue is 
more about your children and grandchildren.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McCain said unless there is bold reform of the Social Security  
system, Americans could soon be paying 18 percent of their income 
to support the growing number of elderly Americans. 
</P>
<P>
	McCain said President Clinton had not carried out his promise to  
use part of the federal budget surplus to save Social Security. But 
he also criticized Congress for what he called loopholes in a bill 
designed to put Social Security funds into a ``lockbox'' to prevent 
them from being used for other projects. 
</P>
<P>
	The only way to support the retired is to allow them to use part  
of their Social Security tax dollars to invest on their own in the 
stock market, McCain said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is the same premise upon which the federal employee pension  
program and the 401K retirement plans are based,'' he said. ``It 
works.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McCain trails Texas Gov. George W. Bush and former American Red  
Cross president Elizabeth Dole in the polls but his numbers have 
benefited from exposure in criticizing Clinton's decision not to 
use ground troops in Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	The reaction he got Wednesday from his elderly audience was  
mixed. 
</P>
<P>
	George Johnson, 72, a retired construction worker, liked what  
McCain said about Social Security. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sure, there's a risk with investing on your own,'' Johnston  
said. ``But it's a lot better than the system we have now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Aville Honeywell, a 67-year-old retired teacher, was  
skeptical about allowing private investment of Social Security 
taxes. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a lot of uneducated people out there who wouldn't know  
what to do with their money,'' she said. ``And I also think there 
would be a bureaucratic nightmare with all that money going in 
different places.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
