<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Wash. Pays Top Dollar for Tech Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- Washington state is tops in the nation when it  
comes to the average compensation earned by high-technology workers 
-- and Microsoft stock options are a big reason why, a new report 
says. 
</P>
<P>
	The report to be released today by the American Electronics  
Association says the average high-tech wage in Washington in 1997 
was $81,400, compared with $62,800 in second-place California. The 
national average was $53,000. 
</P>
<P>
	``The stock options within Microsoft certainly become a driving  
factor in pushing that average up,'' said Dennis Fusco, chief 
economist for the state Employment Security Department. ``I would 
assume that is why Washington ranks so much higher than the other 
states.'' 
</P>
<P>
	New Jersey ranked third, with an average high-tech wage of  
$62,600; the District of Columbia was fourth at $61,900; and 
Massachusetts was fifth at $59,600. 
</P>
<P>
	In terms of the number of workers in the industry, California  
was tops with 784,000, followed by Texas, 376,000; New York, 
320,000; Illinois, 207,000; and Massachusetts, 205,000. Washington 
ranked 16th, with 97,025. 
</P>
<P>
	In calculating compensation, the association included bonuses,  
tips and employer contributions to 401(k) plans. Stock options were 
included only if they were exercised. 
</P>
<P>
	Washington has ``a concentration of software companies up there  
that classically pay more money than other computer companies,'' 
said John Hatch of the association's Silicon Valley office in 
California. 
</P>
<P>
	Redmond-based Microsoft, the world's largest software company,  
said last month that it planned to boost employee pay to retain 
workers. The company had been paying workers at about the 50th 
percentile for the industry, and said it would raise that to the 
65th percentile. 
</P>
<P>
	But it's stock options that have turned hundreds of Microsoft  
employees into millionaires. 
</P>
<P>
	The average compensation -- including stock options exercised --  
in the pre-packaged software industry in Washington was $158,000, 
the report says. 
</P>
<P>
	Fusco puts the figure even higher, at $197,878.  
</P>
<P>
	For all private-sector jobs in Washington, the average was far  
lower: $30,337, the report says. 
</P>
<P>
	The association report uses figures from the U.S. Bureau of  
Labor Statistics, and looks at three broad categories: high-tech 
manufacturing, software services and communication services. 
</P>
<P>
	The report also found:  
</P>
<P>
	--High-tech companies employ 47 of every 1,000 private-sector  
workers in Washington, and high-tech products account for $3.3 
billion of the state's $41.8 billion in exports. 
</P>
<P>
	--Nationwide, about 1 million high-tech jobs were added from 1993  
to 1997, for a total of 4.5 million. 
</P>
<P>
	--The highest number of high-tech workers per capita was in New  
Hampshire, with 82 such workers for every 1,000 private-sector 
employees. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
