<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Sweeps Dashes at German Event </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHEMNITZ, Germany (AP) -- American sprinters broke a string of  
German victories by sweeping the 100-meter dashes in an 
international track and field meet Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Dennis Mitchell cruised to victory in the men's 100 in 10.17  
seconds to beat Eric Nkansah of Ghana, who was second in 10.40. 
</P>
<P>
	The women's 100 went to Zundra Feagin, who won in 11.55 to nip  
Martha Adusei of Canada, also timed in 11.55. 
</P>
<P>
	Derek Mills gave the small American contingent another victory  
by winning the men's 400 in 45.44, with Kennedy Ocheing of Kenya 
second in 45.50. Pjotr Haczek of Poland was third in 45.64. 
</P>
<P>
	German veteran Heike Drechsler and her teammate Susen Tiedtke  
were beaten in the women's long jump. 
</P>
<P>
	Dawn Burrell won at 22 feet, 2 1/4 inches. Olga Rublyova of Russia  
was second at 21-8 3/4. Drechsler went only 21-5 1/2 and Tiedtke 21-5 1/4. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990602.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 06:20:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Government's Rail Monopoly Ends </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ALTOONA, Pa. (AP) -- For the two railroads that bought Conrail  
Inc., breaking up the 23-year-old rail monopoly was the easy part. 
</P>
<P>
	Many weeks, perhaps months or years, will pass before CSX Corp.  
and Norfolk Southern Corp. are ready to declare success in their 
attempt to redraw the Eastern rail map by absorbing portions of 
Conrail. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think we've had a great initial success but we have to be  
very vigilant here in the coming weeks in terms of safety and in 
terms of having all of our assets in the right place -- the people, 
locomotives and cars,'' said Pete Carpenter, president of CSX's 
transportation division. 
</P>
<P>
	Norfolk Southern and CSX heralded a new era in railroading  
Tuesday when they carved up a carrier set up by the government in 
1976 as the industry's last hope for survival. Conrail was sold to 
the public in 1987 and grew in value as railroads in general became 
profitable again. 
</P>
<P>
	Tuesday's restructuring came at a time of heightened concerns  
over safety and service in light of a string of fatal accidents and 
prolonged disruptions that followed the 1996 merger of Union 
Pacific Railroad with Southern Pacific. 
</P>
<P>
	Much was at stake as the new owners underwent the most complex  
restructuring in modern railroading, one that unlike typical 
mergers involved breaking up an active carrier. 
</P>
<P>
	Major mishaps could delay letters and packages, impede commuter  
trains and boost shipping costs for farm products and consumer 
goods. Disruptions also could alienate shippers just as railroads 
are trying to become more competitive with trucks. 
</P>
<P>
	``The whole country's watching,'' said Ed Rastatter, director of  
policy with the National Industrial Transportation League, a 
shipping group. ``We're hoping against hope that the same mistakes 
with Union Pacific do not recur.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Although early reports indicated that the transition occurred  
with no major glitches, many of the operational changes have yet to 
come. And from a marketing standpoint, the railroads need to 
capture traffic that now moves by trucks to pay for the $10.3 
billion purchase of Conrail. 
</P>
<P>
	David Goode, the Norfolk Southern chief executive, told hundreds  
of workers gathered at a locomotive repair shop here, that the 
start of the transition went well. Beyond the need for smooth 
operations, Goode acknowledged the challenges ahead in making his 
business grow. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal Railroad Administrator Jolene Molitoris toured rail  
operations in Altoona, Pa., and Jacksonville, Fla., encouraging 
employees to report problems and concerns to managers and 
regulators. She said more than 40 inspectors will be dispatched 
throughout the former Conrail system for five years. 
</P>
<P>
	She said the first-day operations appeared smooth, but ``we are  
not going to be lulled into any sort of comfortable feeling that 
now everything is taken care of.'' 
</P>
<P>
	CSX reported that fewer than 10 of its 180 trains in operation  
went too far or did not reach the proper destination. Those trains 
were moved to the correct locations early in the day. 
</P>
<P>
	The day was one of both joy and apprehension for longtime  
workers. Railroad officials projected a net decrease in 1,500 union 
jobs, although the Altoona shop would gain positions. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've been an optimist all my life, and there's no sense in  
changing now,'' said Paul Muri Jr., a welder who donned a 
``Gonerail'' T-shirt. ``It's scary in a way, but this is part of 
progress.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Workers joining Norfolk Southern got informational pamphlets, a  
souvenir bag and a baseball cap, while CSX employees got pins 
pairing CSX and Conrail locomotives. 
</P>
<P>
	The split of Conrail gives Norfolk Southern and CSX access to  
lucrative markets in the Northeast and restores competition for 
many shippers along former Conrail routes for the first time since 
1976. That was when Congress created Conrail out of six bankrupt 
carriers. 
</P>
<P>
	Norfolk Southern and CSX now control virtually all rail traffic  
east of the Mississippi River, with tracks stretching nearly 45,000 
miles from Montreal to Miami and from Boston to Kansas City, Mo. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
