<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> US Airways Workers To Get Raises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ARLINGTON, Va. (AP) -- US Airways plans to give pay raises of  
nearly 14 percent to 9,500 passenger-service workers who have gone 
seven years without a pay increase. 
</P>
<P>
	US Airways chairman Stephen Wolf and president Rakesh Gangwal  
said in a statement the raises are ``not only deserved but 
necessary, long overdue and critical in order for the company to 
operate effectively and fairly.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The airline's action came four days after a federal Appeals  
Court overturned the 1997 election giving the Communications 
Workers of America the right to represent the workers, but a CWA 
spokeswoman said the union negotiated most of the improvements. 
</P>
<P>
	Two weeks ago, workers protested at the company's annual meeting  
about going long stretches without raises while executives were 
awarded incentive plans potentially worth millions. 
</P>
<P>
	At that meeting, Wolf and Gangwal agreed to drop out of the  
incentive plan and acknowledged employee raises were overdue. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the pay plan announced Tuesday, each passenger-service  
employee will get a 13.7 percent pay raise. 
</P>
<P>
	Besides the pay increases, the company said it will restore  
benefits and seniority accrual for part-time employees, and 
vacation, holiday and sick pay. Moreover, the management announced 
new overtime procedures, increased uniform allowances and job 
protection in case of subcontracting. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
