<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sound Bites: Audio Reviews </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	``The Secret Life of Reinhold Messner'' (550 Music) -- The Ben  
Folds Five 

</P>
<P>
	The Ben Folds Five already proved with their last studio album,  
``Whatever and Ever, Amen,'' that not only can they incorporate 
influences like Squeeze, Elton John, the Beatles and the Beach 
Boys, but they can improve upon them and be absolutely hilarious to 
boot. 
</P>
<P>
	So why not tackle rock's concept album.  
</P>
<P>
	If Radiohead's stellar ``OK Computer'' was the ``Dark Side of  
the Moon'' of the 1990s, then this group's latest, ``The Secret 
Life of Reinhold Messner,'' aims at the hallowed ground of ``Sgt. 
Pepper.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Unlike the grand statements made by Radiohead, ``Secret Life''  
is a concept album musically first and foremost. The Ben Folds Five 
takes the listener on a pop journey that continuously surprises. 
</P>
<P>
	``Don't Change Your Plans'' follows in perfect ``Sgt. Pepper''  
mode only to unfold in a Burt Bacharach horn flourish. ``Mess'' 
mines the same rich Byrds vein that R.E.M. made a career of. There 
is even a soul track to an otherworldly answering machine message. 
The songs are flushed with strings, harmonies, quirky tempos and, 
of course, Folds' trademark baby grand piano licks. 
</P>
<P>
	That said, the songs on ``Secret Life'' aren't as good as this  
band's previous effort. Experimentalism and musicianship supersede 
its indelible pop instincts at times. There is no song on the level 
of ``Brick,'' the tune from ``Whatever'' that had at its 
well-disguised core a heart-wrenching tale about abortion. 
</P>
<P>
	When Radiohead unleashed ``OK Computer'' two years ago it was a  
revelation -- nothing short of an Orwellian update put to music. 
Folds could author such a masterpiece with his unique storytelling, 
but is only half-interested in doing so. Which is a shame. 
</P>
<P>
	-- By John Pacenti, Associated Press Writer.  
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	``Echo'' (Warner Bros.) -- Tom Petty and the Heartbreakers  

</P>
<P>
	In the early 1980s, Tom Petty and the Heartbreakers released two  
studio works of perfect pop rock: ``Hard Promises'' and ``Long 
After Dark.'' They were filled with men done wrong by their girls, 
often morally challenged, ``looking for something big.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Then Petty got happy and started exploring a less edgy side with  
former ELO frontman Jeff Lynne as his producer. 
</P>
<P>
	Freshly separated from his wife, Petty's recent woes are the  
listener's gain as the Heartbreakers' newest release, ``Echo,'' 
hails back to their leader's best work. Lynne is gone as producer 
and Petty gives a lesson in the A-B-Cs of rock 'n' roll. 
</P>
<P>
	The nasal-voiced Petty fills the disc with acid-tongued rockers  
like ``Free Girl Now, ``Swingin''' and ``Rhino Skin.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But ``Echo'' offers an autobiographical dimension missing from  
most of Petty's well-established catalogue. The lyrics here may be 
the best he has ever written. ``Room at the Top'' captures the 
isolated millionaire good ol' boy without coming off as an exercise 
in self pity, while the title song and ``One More Day, One More 
Night'' simply has him breaking down. 
</P>
<P>
	Petty offers no solace to the heartbroken in ``Rhino Skin,''  
hissing, ``You need Rhino Skin if you are going to begin to walk 
through this world.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Echo'' does have a few so-so tunes but the best of the songs  
rank with ``The Waiting'' or ``You Got Lucky'' from Petty's heyday. 
They may be even better. 
</P>
<P>
	-- By John Pacenti, Associated Press Writer.  
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	``Take Your Shoes Off'' (Rykodisc) -- The Robert Cray Band  

</P>
<P>
	Guitarist Robert Cray takes off his shoes, his socks and his  
bluesman label for his debut on Rykodisc. The result is a soulfest. 
Cray assembled his band in a Nashville studio and produced a fine 
rhythm and blues record that showcases his sweet voice more than 
his playing. 
</P>
<P>
	As if to give the record an extra measure of credence, he dips  
into the soul vaults to bring new life to Mack Rice's ``24-7 Man'' 
and ``Won't You Give Him (One More Chance),'' a 1964 hit for 
Soloman Burke. After 13 years with Mercury Records, Cray headed to 
the independent Rykodisc and used the occasion to give full voice 
to the soul roots that have always been a part of his music. His 
six originals are right at home with the soul covers. 
</P>
<P>
	-- By James Reindl, Associated Press Writer.  
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	``Borders'' (Red House Records) -- Cliff Eberhardt  

</P>
<P>
	Songwriter Cliff Eberhardt explores boundaries on his second  
record for Minnesota-based Red House Records. There's a rawness to 
his voice and a spareness to his guitar playing that sharpens the 
emotion of his well-written lyrics. 
</P>
<P>
	``Lines,'' which pretty much defines the theme for the record,  
showcases some of his best writing. Eberhardt also offers a 
haunting Civil War account of the ravages of battle on those with 
no reason to fight in ``The Wrong Side of the Line.'' There are 
some quirky elements that mar ``Borders,'' such as the lyric bridge 
in ``Lines,'' but it's a heartfelt record sung with passion. 
</P>
<P>
	-- By James Reindl, Associated Press Writer.  
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	``The Green Gate'' (J Seven Records) -- Phil DeGreg  

</P>
<P>
	Pianist and professor Phil DeGreg gets right to the point on  
this recording for Cincinnati-based J. Seven Records. DeGreg is an 
associate professor of jazz studies at the University of Cincinnati 
Conservatory of Music who also has played with the Woody Herman 
Orchestra, Slide Hampton, Stanley Turrentine and Eddie Harris. Here 
he leads a trio for most of the disc, playing straight-up jazz with 
confidence and authority. He has an easy grace and a strong sense 
of tradition. Four DeGreg compositions also showcase his writing. 
Tim Ries offers support on the tenor and soprano saxes as well as 
blowing some sweet solos to spice the mix. 
</P>
<P>
	-- By James Reindl, Associated Press Writer.  
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	``Spirit -- A Journey in Dance, Drums &AMP; Song'' (Hollywood  
Records) -- Peter Buffett 

</P>
<P>
	Quite simply, this is a stunning recording. The compact disc is  
a recording of a live performance of composer/keyboardist Peter 
Buffett's celebration of Native American culture. 
</P>
<P>
	The live show, first done in August, includes more than 80  
performers, including 20 dancers and a children's choir, who use 
rock music, movement, chants and songs to pay homage to Native 
American culture. And while it is a celebration, the overall tone 
is of a civilization lost. 
</P>
<P>
	Indeed, the third piece, ``Hidden Heritage,'' includes a  
recitation of tribes who have gone before. Robert Mirabal's flute 
work is particularly haunting throughout. A television presentation 
of the performance was broadcast by PBS nationwide in March and a 
live touring show is set to kick off in Chicago in October. Buffett 
is known for his score work for such films as ``Dances With 
Wolves'' and ``The Scarlet Letter,'' and TV shows like CBS' ``500 
Nations.'' 
</P>
<P>
	-- By James Reindl, Associated Press Writer.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990602.0036 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 10:17:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Charismatic Draws No. 4 Post </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Charismatic's bid for the Triple Crown in  
Saturday's Belmont Stakes will begin from the No. 4 post, a spot 
that has produced eight winners of the race in the past 94 years. 
</P>
<P>
	In today's draw for post positions at Belmont Park, a field of  
12 was entered for the grueling 1 1/2-mile race, final leg of racing's 
Triple Crown. 
</P>
<P>
	Charismatic was installed as the 2-1 morning-line favorite,  
while Menifee, who drew the No. 10 post, was the second choice at 
7-2. The filly Silverbulletday, trained by Bob Baffert, drew the 
No. 3 post and was the third choice at 4-1. 
</P>
<P>
	Charismatic, trained by D. Wayne Lukas, will become either the  
12th Triple Crown winner and first since Affirmed in 1978 or the 
15th Kentucky Derby and Preakness winner to fall short in the 
Belmont. 
</P>
<P>
	Should Charismatic win the Triple Crown, owners Bob and Beverly  
Lewis would collect a $5 million bonus from VISA, a sponsor of the 
three-race series. 
</P>
<P>
	After a 90-minute delay at the Louisville airport due to a  
rainstorm earlier today, Charismatic and Silverbulletday arrived 
safely at Belmont Park at about 11:45 a.m. 
</P>
<P>
	The Belmont field, with jockeys and odds, from the rail out:  
Teletable (John Velazquez, 99-1); Vision and Verse (Herberto 
Castillo Jr., 20-1); Silverbulletday (Jerry Bailey, 4-1); 
Charismatic (Chris Antley, 2-1); Pineaff (Sidney LeJune Jr., 30-1); 
Lemon Drop Kid (Jose Santos, 20-1); Patience Game (Kent Desormeaux, 
20-1); Adonis (Jorge Chavez, 20-1); Prime Directive (Mike Smith, 
30-1); Menifee (Pat Day, 7-2); Stephen Got Even (Shane Sellers, 
10-1); and Best of Luck (Jean-Luc Samyn, 6-1). 
</P>
<P>
	Menifee, trained by Elliott Walden, finished second to  
Charismatic in the Derby and Preakness, while Silverbulletday, a 
winner in 11 of 12 starts against her own sex, will run against 
males for the first time. 
</P>
<P>
	In the last two Belmonts, horses trained by Baffert were foiled  
in their Triple Crown bids -- Silver Charm by Touch Gold in 1997 and 
Real Quiet by Victory Gallop in 1998. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
