<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Astronomers Study Star's Behavior </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- A star that erupted in a famous stellar  
observation 150 years ago has suddenly brightened again and 
astronomers are watching closely for what may be another celestial 
fireworks show. 
</P>
<P>
	Eta Carinae once was one of the brightest stars in the Southern  
night sky, but then it dimmed for decades. Now instruments 
monitoring the star have detected a doubling and tripling of 
energy, mostly in invisible light. 
</P>
<P>
	What puzzles astronomers is that Eta Carinae was not supposed to  
do this. 
</P>
<P>
	``Occasionally something happens in astronomy that is so  
bewildering that it makes astronomers nervous,'' said Kris 
Davidson, a University of Minnesota astrophysicist. ``This is 
weird. We don't understand.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A report on the star was given Wednesday at the national meeting  
of the American Astronomical Society. 
</P>
<P>
	Eta Carinae has a prominent place in astronomy lore because of  
its history, its size and what experts believe eventually will 
happen to it. 
</P>
<P>
	The star, about 7,500 light-years from Earth, is among the most  
massive and energetic in the known universe, equal in size to 100 
suns. The energy it emits, much of it in invisible radiation, is up 
to five times more powerful than the sun. 
</P>
<P>
	Eta Carinae was a routine part of the sky in the Southern  
Hemisphere until the 1840s when it was observed to erupt with a 
massive outflow of energy, dust and gas. For awed watchers on 
Earth, it was as if a light bulb in the heavens was suddenly turned 
on. 
</P>
<P>
	``It became very, very bright and for 20 years it was one of the  
brightest stars in the Southern sky,'' said Davidson. For a while, 
its brilliance matched that of a supernova. And then it started 
becoming dimmer and dimmer until it faded from view to the naked 
eye. 
</P>
<P>
	Astronomers theorized, and later telescopic images confirmed,  
that the light from the Eta Carinae faded because an immense cloud 
of dust from the eruption was obscuring the view. They forecast 
that it would become visible again as the dust cleared. 
</P>
<P>
	That happened about 20 years ago when Eta Carinae blinked into  
view, dimly at first, after an 80-year absence. A widely published 
image from the Hubble Space Telescope showed the star at the center 
of barbell-shaped clouds. Astronomers expected the star to slowly 
brighten until, sometime in the next century, it again would become 
one of the a most prominent features in the Southern sky. 
</P>
<P>
	But Eta Carinae surprised the experts. Over a matter of months,  
telescopes detected the star spewing out vast amounts of energy in 
all bands of the electromagnetic spectrum. The star's image reached 
a visible brightness unequaled since 1864. 
</P>
<P>
	Astronomers had not expected such an energy burst for many  
decades and, when it came, it was expected that the star would 
first emit cooler radiation, sort of as a warning of a coming 
violence. That didn't happen. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are about 6,000 stars in the sky visible to the naked  
eye,'' said Davidson. ``We understand them all with the sole 
exception of Eta Carinae. There is no theoretical explanation for 
it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Eta Carinae's demise may bring another surprise. Stars many  
times more massive than the sun have short lives and spectacular 
deaths. Eta Carinae is only about 3 million years old (the sun is 
more than 4 billion years old). 
</P>
<P>
	Sometime in the next 10,000 years, the sudden explosion of Eta  
Carinae is expected to be seen. Davidson said theorists believe it 
may create a hypernova, a stellar explosion many times more 
powerful than a supernova. It could then start spewing gamma 
radiation in short waves that might equal the entire energy of the 
sun. 
</P>
<P>
	Such bursts ``might even be hazardous at 7,500 light-years,''  
the distance to Earth, Davidson said. 
</P>
<P>
	A light-year is the distance light travels in one year, or about  
6 trillion miles. This means the events on Eta Carinae that are 
being observed now occurred 7,500 years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Eta Carinae also could collapse, said Davidson, and become ``an  
instant black hole.'' This is an object so dense that its gravity 
will not permit even light to escape and is, thus, invisible to 
direct detection. 
</P>
<P>
	If that happens, said Davidson, ``it would just disappear,  
overnight.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
