<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Investigators Examining Air Crash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- Investigators sought Wednesday to  
determine whether an American Airlines pilot had adequate warning 
of a fierce hailstorm that struck the airport just before his jet 
slid off the runway on landing and burst into flames. 
</P>
<P>
	Nine of the 145 people on board were killed, including the  
pilot. 
</P>
<P>
	Scores of passengers, their clothes drenched with fuel, escaped  
the burning plane just before midnight Tuesday by squeezing through 
a twisted emergency exit and scrambling out gaping holes in the 
fuselage. Some jumped off a burning wing into a swamp. 
</P>
<P>
	``A fire started at the front of the plane and spread back,''  
passenger Barrett Baber said. ``Once the smoke got too thick, there 
was nothing we could do. People were screaming, `God, please save 
us!''' 
</P>
<P>
	Federal accident investigators said it was too early to say  
whether the rapidly moving storm caused or contributed to the 
crash. The storm packed steady winds of 50 mph and gusts of 75 mph. 
</P>
<P>
	Whether the pliot was aware of how bad things were on the ground  
is one focus of the investigation said George Black, a spokesman 
for the National Transportation Safety Board. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's ultimately a pilot's decision to land or not, but they  
have to base that on the information they have,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	American Airlines executive vice president Bob Baker said  
regular weather updates were relayed to the plane's captain, 
Richard Buschmann. 
</P>
<P>
	The flight data and cockpit voice recorders, which were taken to  
Washington for analysis, should reveal what controllers told the 
pilot about the weather conditions. 
</P>
<P>
	The turbulent Flight 1420 from Dallas to Little Rock had been  
delayed two hours because of bad weather. Some passengers said the 
plane seemed to be coming in for landing faster than normal, 
although others said it did not seem unusual. 
</P>
<P>
	Passengers said the MD-82 never seemed to get any traction  
before it slid off the left side of a runway, went down a rock 
levee and whipped around a metal tower supporting airport lights. 
</P>
<P>
	``We had a hard landing, and in my opinion the pilot just never  
did gain control once we got on the ground,'' said Brigadier Gen. 
Stephen Korenek, 52, a passenger and commander of the Alaska Army 
National Guard who is a 30-year veteran of flights in Alaska. 
</P>
<P>
	Lt. Col. Jeff Arnold, a training officer with the Army National  
Guard in Alaska, said they hit the runway hard, ``but I've felt 
harder.'' He said the plane started to swerve when the pilot hit 
the brakes. 
</P>
<P>
	``He eased up on the brakes and used the reverse thruster. He  
used the brakes again, and the plane swerved a second time,'' he 
said. ``It felt like the landing gear gave way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The steel stanchion they hit acted like a can opener, peeling  
back the plane's thin shell on the left side from the captain's 
controls through the first-class section. When the plane finally 
came to a stop, its tail was facing away from the runway on a low 
spot near an Arkansas River backwater. 
</P>
<P>
	Some survivors crawled on hands and knees through several inches  
of water and began pushing each other through the darkness. 
</P>
<P>
	``All I thought was that I was going to die,'' passenger Bonnie  
Montgomery said. ``Everyone was pushing and pulling to get out of 
that plane. We were on our hands and knees, and the smoke was so 
thick we couldn't breathe. Even I pushed a few people, because your 
natural instinct to survive just kicks in.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The coroner said nine people were killed. Hospitals treated 83  
people for injuries, mostly cuts and burns. Another 51 people were 
unhurt and were reunited with friends and relatives in a theater at 
a nearby aerospace museum. 
</P>
<P>
	Two people were unaccounted for but were presumed to have left  
the crash safely without notifying the airline. 
</P>
<P>
	The fatalities were the first aboard a U.S. carrier in nearly 1 1/2  
years. They also were the first in a commercial carrier at Little 
Rock's airport in its 82-year history. 
</P>
<P>
	Radar images reviewed Wednesday by the National Weather Service  
showed the storm arriving at Little Rock's airport about the same 
time the jet arrived. There was no distress call from the cockpit 
before the landing, said William Shumann, a Federal Aviation 
Administration spokesman. 
</P>
<P>
	American Airlines' chief pilot, Cecil Ewell, said he would not  
have attempted to land the plane if wind speeds exceeded 57.5 mph. 
</P>
<P>
	Black also said that power went out at the airport about the  
time of the accident, although he said it wasn't known whether the 
accident caused the power outage or whether any power outage 
contributed to the accident. 
</P>
<P>
	Buschmann apparently died at the controls. The first officer was  
badly injured but survived. 
</P>
<P>
	The pilot had been on duty for 13 1/2 hours, just short of the  
federal maximum of 14 hours. His day began in Chicago. He flew to 
Salt Lake City and Dallas before Little Rock. Ewell said such long 
days are common. 
</P>
<P>
	A check of the plane's maintenance records revealed no major  
problems. Twelve years ago, the plane lost power in one of its 
engines during a landing in Las Vegas because the housing around a 
part had worn away. 
</P>
<P>
	The deaths were the first in an U.S. commercial airline accident  
since Dec. 28, 1997, when a woman was killed aboard a United 
Airlines 747 that encountered severe turbulence over the Pacific. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, aviation officials celebrated a fatality-free year  
aboard U.S. commercial flights. U.S. airlines also had one of their 
safest years ever in 1997, a year after one of the deadliest on 
record. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
