<HEADLINE> Schwab, Tokio Marine Plan Venture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Charles Schwab Corp., a leading U.S. discount  
broker, and Tokio Marine and Fire Insurance Co. of Japan plan to 
create a securities joint venture in Japan by this fall. 
</P>
<P>
	The new firm, according to plans announced Wednesday, will  
initially offer individual investors trading in U.S. stocks and 
bonds and Japanese and offshore investment trusts, and add trading 
in Japanese stocks in early 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	It will be owned 50 percent by Charles Schwab, 30 percent to 35  
percent by Tokio Marine and 15 percent to 20 percent by Tokio 
Marine's three allied financial institutions in the Mitsubishi 
Group, said Manami Imagi, a spokeswoman for Tokio Marine. 
</P>
<P>
	The three firms are Bank of Tokyo-Mitsubishi Ltd., Mitsubishi  
Trust and Banking Corp. and Meiji Mutual Life Insurance Co. 
</P>
<P>
	Tokio Marine has offered non-life and life insurance since 1879.  

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
