<HEADLINE> Chemical Executive Sentenced </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRUNSWICK, Ga. (AP) -- The former chief executive of a company  
that operated a chemical plant in southeast Georgia was sentenced 
Wednesday to nine years in federal prison for polluting the 
surrounding marshland. 
</P>
<P>
	Christian A. Hansen Jr., 72, the ex-CEO of the New Jersey-based  
Hanlin Group Inc., also was ordered to pay a $20,000 fine over what 
some environmental officials have called one of the worst cases of 
industrial pollution in the country. 
</P>
<P>
	Alfred R. Taylor, the former manager at the LCP  
Chemicals-Georgia Inc. plant, also was sentenced Wednesday to six 
and a half years in prison. 
</P>
<P>
	Sentencing was delayed for Randall Hansen, another former  
executive of the Hanlin Group and the son of Christian A. Hansen 
Jr. 
</P>
<P>
	The LCP plant was closed in February 1994 and declared a  
Superfund cleanup site by the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency. 
</P>
<P>
	The EPA said the 550 acres were rife with contaminants including  
mercury, lead, polychlorinated biphenyls and refinery wastes. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
