<HEADLINE> Mail-Newspaper Advertising Promoted </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Newspapers and direct mail, longtime  
competitors for advertising dollars, have decided to try working 
together instead. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Newspaper Association and the Postal Service said  
Wednesday they are launching a new ``Say it in Print'' campaign to 
encourage a blend of the two media. 
</P>
<P>
	The NNA represents the nation's community newspapers, which are  
generally published once or twice a week. The effort is also being 
backed by the American Forest and Paper Association. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a revitalized alliance between two industries which  
recognize that by working together we can accomplish more than by 
working alone,'' said Postmaster General William J. Henderson. 
</P>
<P>
	The campaign will contact 30,000 advertisers across the country  
promoting the combination of newspaper and direct-mail campaigns, 
officials said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
