<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sugar Up on Russian Buying  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Sugar futures jumped Wednesday on the Board of Trade of the City  
of New York as Russian importers sharply increased purchases ahead 
of new tariffs. 
</P>
<P>
	On other markets, natural gas and unleaded gasoline rose  
sharply, while gold posted new 20-year lows. 
</P>
<P>
	Sugar futures have been on the rise ahead of Russia's  
implementation of a new tax on Aug. 1. Shipments must be loaded and 
delivered to importers by the date to avoid the increased taxes, 
which are jumping to 45 percent from as low as 1 percent for raw 
sugar as that country moves to protect domestic growers. 
</P>
<P>
	Russia is the world's largest sugar importer, but shipments this  
year to that country have been sharply lower because of economic 
turmoil. 
</P>
<P>
	That came as Brazil, Cuba and other growers produced bumper  
crops, contributing to a global supply glut. Prices tumbled to 
their lowest in 14 years earlier this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Raw sugar for July delivery rose .25 cent, or 4.8 percent, to  
5.49 cents a pound. 
</P>
<P>
	Natural gas futures rose sharply on the New York Mercantile  
Exchange amid concern that above-normal temperatures in parts of 
the country will force utilities to use more fuel at a time when 
domestic production is weaker than normal. 
</P>
<P>
	The American Gas Association was expected to report that storage  
remains below normal for this time of year. 
</P>
<P>
	Meantime, the National Weather Service again predicted  
above-normal temperatures in the Midwest and parts of the South. If 
those conditions persist, market participants are worried about 
shortages of natural gas later this summer. 
</P>
<P>
	Gasoline futures also moved higher after Sunoco cut processing  
at its Philadelphia refinery amid weak profit margins. 
</P>
<P>
	That move, which follows similar ones recently in Europe, could  
lead to spot shortages of gasoline during the peak summer driving 
period. 
</P>
<P>
	Heating oil and crude followed unleaded gasoline higher.  
</P>
<P>
	July natural gas rose 6.4 cents to $2.407 for each 1,000 cubic  
feet; July gasoline rose 1.60 cents to 48.97 cents a gallon; July 
heating oil rose 1.06 cents to 40.19 cents a gallon; July crude 
rose 31 cents to $16.65 a barrel. 
</P>
<P>
	Gold futures posted new 20-year lows on the New York Mercantile  
Exchange as investors continued to bail out of a market beset by 
concern over producer and government sales. 
</P>
<P>
	Australian producers this week dumped new supplies on the market  
in response to Britain's decision to sell more than half of its 
reserves beginning a few weeks. Prices have tumbled on that 
decision, and producers are dumping inventories as inventories sell 
for less than they cost to produce. 
</P>
<P>
	In recent years, Australia, Canada, the Netherlands and Belgium  
have quietly sold reserves, while Switzerland and the International 
Monetary Fund are moving to do the same. 
</P>
<P>
	August gold fell $2.40 to $267.10 an ounce.  


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
