<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Passengers Describe Ark. Jet Crash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- They'd already flown through buffeting  
winds and driving rain and could see flashes of lightning off the 
wings. But the first sense passengers on American Airlines Flight 
1420 had their landing was in big trouble was the sickening slide 
down the runway, as if the tires couldn't grip. 
</P>
<P>
	Seconds later, the skidding Super MD-80 spun around 150 degrees,  
slammed into a steel beacon tower on the banks of the Arkansas 
River and split into pieces. Jet fuel splashed over the passengers, 
and fire erupted in the economy section. 
</P>
<P>
	``We hit the runway too hard. Then we started turning  
sideways,'' said Randy Hill of Arkadelphia. ``The plane broke apart 
right in front of me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Everyone started yelling, `Get out, get out!' There was about  
a 10-inch gap in the metal in front of me. I pushed my way out,'' 
said Hill, who lost his shoes in the crash and was soaked in fuel. 
</P>
<P>
	``I saw a big chunk of the plane just fall away,'' said Jason  
Klamm, 19, of Pine Bluff. ``The plane seemed to stop about 10 
seconds after that. I looked back and saw a fire.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He and his father, Richard, 49, were in first class seats 2D and  
2E. They scrambled out through the shattered fuselage. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I first got off the plane, I heard screaming,'' Jason  
Klamm said. ``It almost went in the river. I would say it was about 
100 feet from the river. 
</P>
<P>
	``Once the smoke got too thick, there was nothing we could do,''  
said Barrett Baber, another survivor. ``People were screaming, 
`God, please save us!''' 
</P>
<P>
	Baber was seated in Row 30 and said flames were 15 feet from him  
by the time he escaped. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was panic, craziness. There were flames,'' Baber said.  
``The emergency door was cracked, and people were able to get out 
only one at a time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At least nine people were killed in the crash, three sources  
told The Associated Press, but the airline would not confirm the 
toll pending reports from local officials and the National 
Transportation Safety Board. 
</P>
<P>
	``You don't know if anyone on impact was thrown into the  
swamp,'' American Airlines spokesman John Hotard said. 
</P>
<P>
	Survivors waiting for rescuers stood on the edge of the river  
and watched their plane burn under pelting rain and hail. 
</P>
<P>
	``The patients we got in were wet,'' said Diane Ficker,  
Southwest Hospital's director of marketing. ``A lot of them had 
diesel fuel or aviation fuel on them. So we got extra clothes for 
them and hot coffee, and we have been trying to help them contact 
relatives.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Friends and relatives awaiting the flight were told that the  
plane had landed and would be pulling up to the gate shortly. When 
it failed to arrive, they were directed to the Imax theater in the 
airport's Aerospace Education Center. 
</P>
<P>
	The crowd at the museum soon grew to about 100. With vintage  
aircraft hanging above them, dozens of people waiting for 
passengers watched ambulances and fire trucks scream past outside. 
</P>
<P>
	No American Airlines representative was at the museum to explain  
what had happened, relatives said. 
</P>
<P>
	``There was no word from the airline other than to come over  
here,'' said Tom Ashcraft, who was waiting for his two 
granddaughters, ages 13 and 11, to arrive from Dallas. 
</P>
<P>
	Two hours after the accident, Ashcraft discovered the girls had  
been taken to Arkansas Children's Hospital but did not know their 
conditions. 
</P>
<P>
	About three dozen survivors were brought to the museum in a  
school bus 2 1/2 hours after the crash, most soaking wet and wrapped 
in sheets or airline blankets. 
</P>
<P>
	Their relatives and friends rushed the bus, searching for loved  
ones. A few burst into tears when their search came up empty. 
</P>
<P>
	Another bus arrived 15 minutes later and the scene repeated  
itself. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
