<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> British Steel Discusses Merger </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- British Steel PLC confirmed Wednesday that it is  
holding merger talks with Dutch steel and aluminum producer 
Koninklijke Hoogovens NV. 
</P>
<P>
	British Steel's share price jumped 16 percent on the news, while  
shares of Koninklijke Hoogovens rose by 0.5 percent in Amsterdam 
after increasing 5 percent Tuesday on press reports that there 
would be a merger. 
</P>
<P>
	A detailed announcement will be made by Monday, the companies  
said in a joint statement. 
</P>
<P>
	The merger talks come amid tough times for Western steel  
producers with relatively high fixed costs. 
</P>
<P>
	Koninklijke Hoogovens' net profit fell 17 percent in 1998 to  
$196.7 million, due largely to lower steel prices and increased 
competition from companies in Asia and Eastern Europe. 
</P>
<P>
	British Steel posted a net profit of $364.5 million for the year  
ending March 28, 1998, down 27 percent from the previous year. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990602.0057 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 10:00:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Northwest Rapped on Storm Handling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ROMULUS, Mich. (AP) -- A lack of planning and communication by  
Northwest Airlines led to thousands of passengers being stranded on 
runways at Detroit Metropolitan Airport during a major January 
snowstorm, according to a federal report released today. 
</P>
<P>
	The report from the U.S. Department of Transportation found that  
Northwest did not violate any federal regulations during the 
blizzard that dumped nearly 2 feet of snow at Detroit Metropolitan 
Airport. 
</P>
<P>
	However, the report said the conditions on the stranded  
aircraft, which included a lack of food and water and broken 
bathrooms, were ``severe enough to have jeopardized passengers' 
well-being.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Northwest spokesman Jon Austin said the airline has already  
fixed the problems the report cites. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nobody doubts the passengers caught in that snowstorm were in  
a horrible, uncomfortable, inconvenient position,'' he said. ``But 
our goal throughout the whole event was to ensure their safety.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The delays prompted a lawsuit from some exhausted, angered  
passengers who were stuck aboard planes stacked on runways for up 
to eight hours. Northwest accounts for about three-quarters of all 
flights at the airport. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. John Dingell, a Michigan Democrat, said the report showed  
the need for an airline passengers bill of rights and for more 
competition in the airline industry. 
</P>
<P>
	An airplane passenger ``has less rights than anyone in our  
society except someone on death row,'' Dingell said at a news 
conference at Detroit Metropolitan Airport, where he released the 
report today. 
</P>
<P>
	The report said Northwest officials in Minneapolis continued to  
send planes to Detroit at the beginning of the blizzard even after 
other airlines had canceled flights and said staff in Detroit did 
not communicate the severity of the problem. 
</P>
<P>
	The report also criticizes Northwest for not having a snow  
emergency plan for Detroit, even though it is the airline's 
second-largest hub, behind Minneapolis. 
</P>
<P>
	The report also says some Northwest officials said changes made  
since the storm would not necessarily prevent ``a recurrence of 
lengthy passenger strandings.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At a congressional hearing in March, Northwest executives said  
weather conditions were extraordinary. Wind chill was 30 below zero 
and on the first day of the storm, a Saturday, snow was falling two 
inches per hour, they said. 
</P>
<P>
	Richard Hirst, Northwest's senior vice president of corporate  
affairs, said at the March hearing that passengers were forced to 
wait on airplanes for gates to open because it was unsafe to bring 
them down the metal airline steps used by mechanics. The steps were 
frozen and slippery, he said, and passengers without proper winter 
clothing could have suffered from frostbite within minutes. 
</P>
<P>
	But the report said Northwest ``did not consider all of its  
stair deplaning options.'' It noted that Northwest's snow plan for 
the Minneapolis airport includes options for using stairs, and said 
while Northwest was right to reject using maintenance stairs, it 
could have borrowed the right kind of stairs from other airlines. 
</P>
<P>
	Austin said all available options were considered.  
</P>
<P>
	In February, Northwest apologized for the delays and released  
its plans to revamp the way the airline handles snow emergencies. 
</P>
<P>
	That report said Northwest will form ``Go Teams'' -- Northwest  
employees to be sent to Detroit when bad weather is likely. The 
airline also said it would set up a companywide system allowing 
instant communication among executives -- and make more phone lines 
available to employees calling to say they are or aren't available 
for work. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
