<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Today In History  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Today is Thursday, June 3, the 154th day of 1999. There are 211  
days left in the year. 
</P>
<P>
	Today's Highlight in History:  
</P>
<P>
	Ten years ago, on June 3, 1989, Iranian spiritual leader  
Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini died, the same day Chinese army troops 
began their sweep of Beijing to crush student-led pro-democracy 
demonstrations. 
</P>
<P>
	On this date:  
</P>
<P>
	In 1621, the Dutch West India Company received a charter for New  
Netherlands, now known as New York. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1808, Jefferson Davis, the first and only president of the  
Confederacy, was born in Kentucky. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1888, the poem ``Casey at the Bat,'' by Ernest Lawrence  
Thayer, was first published, in the San Francisco Daily Examiner. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1937, the Duke of Windsor, who had abdicated the British  
throne, married Wallis Warfield Simpson in Monts, France. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1948, the 200-inch reflecting telescope at the Palomar  
Mountain Observatory in California was dedicated. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1963, Pope John XXIII died at the age of 81. He was succeeded  
by Pope Paul VI. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1968, pop artist Andy Warhol was shot and critically wounded  
in his New York film studio, known as ``The Factory,'' by Valerie 
Solanas, an actress and self-styled feminist. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1981, Pope John Paul II left a Rome hospital and returned to  
the Vatican three weeks after the attempt on his life. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1983, Gordon Kahl, a militant tax protester wanted in the  
slayings of two U.S. marshals in North Dakota, was killed in a gun 
battle with law-enforcement officials near Smithville, Ark. 
</P>
<P>
	Five years ago: President Clinton, continuing his tour of Italy,  
visited the graves of American soldiers killed in the Anzio landing 
during World War II. The United States began consultations with 
South Korea, Japan and Russia on how to retaliate for North Korea's 
removal of vital evidence about its nuclear weapons capability. 
</P>
<P>
	One year ago: President Clinton urged Congress to renew normal  
trade benefits for China, saying good relations with Beijing were 
crucial amid fears of a nuclear arms race in South Asia. A 
high-speed train derailed in Eschede, Germany, killing 101 people. 
</P>
<P>
	Today's Birthdays: Actor Tony Curtis is 74. Musician Boots  
Randolph is 72. TV producer Chuck Barris is 70. Musician Curtis 
Mayfield is 57. Rock singer Ian Hunter (Mott The Hoople) is 53. 
Musician Too Slim (Riders in the Sky) is 51. Singer Suzi Quatro is 
49. Singer Deneice Williams is 48. Rock musician Billy Powell 
(Lynyrd Skynyrd) is 47. Singer Dan Hill is 45. Actor Scott 
Valentine (``Family Ties'') is 41. Singers Ariel and Gabriel 
Hernandez (No Mercy) are 28. 
</P>
<P>
	Thought for Today: ``What is history but a fable agreed upon?''  
-- Attributed to Napoleon Bonaparte (1769-1821). 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990602.0060 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 10:21:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  ANC Expected To Win in South Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) -- South Africans of all races  
tested their new democracy today, waiting patiently in long lines 
to choose a new government five years after Nelson Mandela's 
election ended the tyranny of apartheid. 
</P>
<P>
	Voting went forward peacefully in a parliamentary election the  
ruling African National Congress is expected to win easily. 
</P>
<P>
	Mandela, who is credited with bringing about the amazingly  
peaceful transition of power to an angry black majority, will 
retire June 16, ending a term aimed at reconciliation in a nation 
still divided by a shameful past. 
</P>
<P>
	His hand-picked successor, Deputy President Thabo Mbeki, is  
expected to lead the governing African National Congress to a 
landslide victory and begin a term aimed at materially improving 
the lives of millions of disadvantaged blacks. The new National 
Assembly will formally elect Mandela's successor on June 14. 
</P>
<P>
	Millions of South Africans voted today in ramshackle black  
townships, wealthy white suburbs, in villages in the Karoo desert 
and near the wind-whipped Cape of Good Hope. 
</P>
<P>
	In black townships, lines were up to a third of a mile long,  
with some people standing outside polling stations all night. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is a lot of enthusiasm,'' Mbeki said.  
</P>
<P>
	Mandela cast his ballot at a country club in an upscale  
Johannesburg neighborhood, his thumb marked with ink to show he had 
voted. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is a wonderful experience,'' declared Mandela, who was  
jailed for 27 years for fighting apartheid, which denied blacks the 
vote and most other basic rights. 
</P>
<P>
	Mandela asked South Africans to vote for the ANC -- but above all  
to vote peacefully. About 100,000 soldiers and police patrolled the 
country. 
</P>
<P>
	Opposition parties tried to rally voters to prevent the ANC from  
winning a two-thirds majority in Parliament, warning that would 
allow the party to tamper with the constitution and consolidate 
power. Mbeki has denied such plans. 
</P>
<P>
	But in a message Tuesday night, the ANC asked voters for ``an  
overwhelming mandate'' to ``accelerate change in our country.'' It 
did not elaborate on the statement. 
</P>
<P>
	The campaign period has been remarkably free of violence -- a  
stark contrast to the 1994 elections, which were preceded by 
bloodletting by white supremacists and rival black parties. 
</P>
<P>
	As blacks, whites and people of other races quietly lined up  
together, common concerns were on their minds -- especially 
unemployment, crime and corruption. 
</P>
<P>
	``We can stop crime through Christianity, but moreover, job  
creation would help,'' said Michael Ledwaba, a pastor in a voting 
line in Johannesburg. 
</P>
<P>
	Marthinus van Schalkwyk, leader of the New National Party, which  
ruled during apartheid, lauded the election process as he cast his 
ballot in an upscale Cape Town suburb. 
</P>
<P>
	``My impression is ... it will be a peaceful election and every  
South African will have the opportunity to cast a vote without 
intimidation,'' he told reporters after voting in a school, located 
near a tennis club and golf course. 
</P>
<P>
	A few miles away, in a dusty squatter camp, John Gumede waited  
all night to vote. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't get to my bed last night, but it was worth it,''  
Gumede said, clutching a small ANC banner. ``It's very important to 
vote. Everyone has to be counted so that we can get houses and 
jobs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	F.W. de Klerk, the last white president who opened the door to  
apartheid's fall, flew in from London and voted near Cape Town with 
little fanfare. 
</P>
<P>
	Thousands of voters waited for hours because some polling  
stations opened late. At others, ballot papers did not arrive in 
time and ID reading machines malfunctioned. But overall, elections 
officials said voting went smoothly. 
</P>
<P>
	However, one person was killed and another injured early today  
when gunmen opened fire on a house in an ANC stronghold in 
Richmond, perhaps the most volatile hotspot in South Africa. The 
body of a woman was found elsewhere in the town in KwaZulu-Natal 
province. Police were investigating whether the attacks were 
politically motivated. 
</P>
<P>
	Deputy Defense Minister Ronnie Kasrils warned that anyone trying  
to disrupt the election would be dealt with speedily and 
forcefully. 
</P>
<P>
	Pre-election polls predicted the ANC would win at least 60  
percent of the vote, but were split on whether it will get the 
two-thirds majority. None of the opposition parties was expected to 
win much more than 10 percent of the vote. 
</P>
<P>
	Left in doubt was whether the ANC would expand its control of  
the country's nine provinces. In the last election, the ANC won 
control of seven. 
</P>
<P>
	Voting was expected to be along racial lines, with most blacks  
voting for the ANC, the Zulu-nationalist Inkatha Freedom Party and 
a few other parties. Whites were expected to vote mostly for the 
New National Party and the Democratic Party. 
</P>
<P>
	In the 1994 election, which ended apartheid, the ANC won 62  
percent of the vote, giving it a majority to pass laws in 
parliament on its own. 
</P>
<P>
	Today, some 18.2 million people were registered to vote for the  
400-seat National Assembly. 
</P>
<P>
	Unofficial results were likely early Thursday.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990602.0061 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 10:21:53 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  ANC Expected To Win in South Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) -- South Africans of all races  
tested their new democracy today, waiting patiently in long lines 
to choose a new government five years after Nelson Mandela's 
election ended the tyranny of apartheid. 
</P>
<P>
	Voting went forward peacefully in a parliamentary election the  
ruling African National Congress is expected to win easily. 
</P>
