<DOCNO> APW19990602.0065 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 23:30:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Pak Seeks Revival at Women's Open  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WEST POINT, Miss. (AP) -- It doesn't necessarily take years of  
experience to win a major championship. Six of the last 10 U.S. 
Women's Open champions have been 20-somethings. 
</P>
<P>
	The major title was the first LPGA victory for four of the  
youthful champions. Defending champ Se Ri Pak and 1991 winner Meg 
Mallon earned their first tour wins earlier in the same season they 
captured the Open. 
</P>
<P>
	Youth and disregard for the real pressure of a major tournament  
appears to be an advantage. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I won the Open in 1995 and 1996, especially in 1995, I  
really didn't know what I was doing,'' said Annika Sorenstam, 24 
and a second-year pro when she first won. ``I was just going out 
there and I was just playing. Then things turned out the way they 
did.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Heading into today's opening round of the 54th U.S. Women's Open  
at Old Waverly Golf Club, Sorenstam is still one of the top women's 
golfers in the world. 
</P>
<P>
	After an LPGA record scoring average of 69.99 last year,  
Sorenstam has lowered that to 69.5 this season with five top 5 
finishes in nine tournaments. Sorenstam has been the LPGA Player of 
the Year three of the last four years. 
</P>
<P>
	But she hasn't fared well in the Open since her consecutive  
titles. She missed the cut in 1997 and then tied for 41st last year 
at Blackwolf Run in Kohler, Wis., with an 18-over-par total. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think I expected myself to do better because I had done it  
in the past,'' said Sorenstam, one of three two-time Open winners 
since 1986. ``I thought, `Well, I'm older, I should be wiser. You 
know, I should be able to do this.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, Pak became the youngest U.S. Open winner. The  
20-year-old rookie took the title after a 20-hole playoff with 
Jenny Chuasiriporn, a 20-year-old amateur. 
</P>
<P>
	Things have already changed for Pak, who hasn't won since  
capturing the Open and two other tournaments last July. The 
expectations, especially in her native South Korea, have swelled 
tremendously. 
</P>
<P>
	``I try my best, but every week I cannot get No. 1 in the  
trophy,'' she said, still struggling to learn English. 
</P>
<P>
	A year ago, many of her countrymen didn't know the difference  
between a birdie and a bogey. They now expect Pak, who hasn't had a 
top 10 finish this year, to win every time she sticks a tee in the 
ground. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sometimes I not play good,'' Pak said. ``They don't understand  
how tough all players, golf course condition, anything. Sometimes 
they are pretty upset, not playing good. That makes pretty hard 
time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Meg Mallon was 28 years old during her fourth pro season when  
the U.S. Open was one of her four victories in 1991. She now has 28 
career victories, including two this year, but hasn't won another 
major. 
</P>
<P>
	Jane Geddes, Laura Davies and Liselotte Neumann all have at  
least 11 career victories. But their firsts were at the U.S. Open, 
when they won in consecutive years -- 1986-88. 
</P>
<P>
	All six of those former 20-something winners are in this year's  
field. 
</P>
<P>
	Among those in the field that could be considered favorites are  
Karrie Webb, Juli Inkster and Dottie Pepper. 
</P>
<P>
	The 24-year-old Webb, a fourth-year pro who hasn't won a major,  
has won four times this year. In her other seven '99 tournaments, 
she finished in the top eight. 
</P>
<P>
	Inkster, a 17-year pro, has 19 career victories after winning  
twice this year. She has won three majors, but none in the 1990s 
and never the Open. 
</P>
<P>
	Pepper is riding a wave of confidence from her win in the first  
major, a record 19-under in the Dinah Shore in late March that 
provided her first victory since 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	In the month after the Dinah Shore, Pepper was forced to take  
some time off because of a bacterial infection. But she appears 
back in form, carrying consecutive top 10 finishes into the Open. 
</P>
<P>
	``I eked out two top 10s by the hair on my teeth the last two  
times out, and done that when I haven't felt that I haven't been 
able to fire on all cylinders yet,'' Pepper said. ``I've had my 
instructor here to work with me a little bit. I think we made 
mirror adjustments that we needed to make, and I feel pretty good 
about it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The conditions at Old Waverly are not nearly as brutal as they  
were a year ago at Blackwolf Run, when Pak and Chuasiriporn tied at 
6-over 290 before their 20-hole Monday playoff. 
</P>
<P>
	With showers Wednesday night making the course even softer,  
rough that is little more than a nuisance and not much wind in the 
forecast, the record score of 10-under set two years ago by Alison 
Nicholas could be in danger. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990602.0066 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 23:30:10 </DATE_TIME>
