<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Northwest Mechanics Get New Union </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A federal board on Monday cleared the Aircraft  
Mechanics Fraternal Association to take over representation of 
Northwest Airlines' 9,500 mechanics. 
</P>
<P>
	However, the National Mediation Board concluded the AMFA had  
violated the secrecy of ballots in polling last November and 
decided that another election could be held as soon as six months 
from now. A union normally cannot be challenged for two years after 
it is certified. 
</P>
<P>
	The International Association of Machinists, which lost the  
Northwest election, complained that some AMFA supporters made 
photocopies of their ballots during the polling. 
</P>
<P>
	``It shows the blatant arrogance of the National Mediation Board  
for them to hold us back for six months and two weeks and then say 
the incumbent can have another election in six months,'' said AMFA 
President O.V. Delle-Femine. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the union would begin contract negotiations with  
Northwest as soon as officers are elected. The mechanics rejected a 
proposed contract last summer. 
</P>
<P>
	IAM has collected $400,000 in monthly dues since the election  
and plans to keep the money. 
</P>
<P>
	IAM officials said the union dues were used in the labor  
relations process to handle grievances and arbitrations. 
</P>
<P>
	``Obviously we're disappointed,'' said John Massetti, secretary  
treasurer of IAM District 149. ``This group will now begin a 
venture alone without the financial resources or political muscle 
and outside the mainstream of organized labor.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The IAM, which is affiliated with the AFL-CIO, represents  
Northwest baggage handlers, ramp workers, stock clerks, ticket 
agents, reservationists, office clerks and security guards. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990602.0068 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 14:45:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sales of New Homes Up 9.2 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Americans have a case of home buying fever.  
New home sales reached their second highest level on record in 
April as buyers, trying to stay ahead of rising mortgage rates, 
rushed to close deals. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales of new single-family homes jumped 9.2 percent in April,  
following four straight months of declines, the Commerce Department 
said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The surge pushed up sales of new homes to a seasonally adjusted  
annual rate of 978,000 units in April, the second highest level on 
record. The all-time high was a sales rate of 985,000 units set 
last November. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts said Americans, buoyed by a healthy economy but  
concerned about the prospects of even higher mortgage rates, are 
buying homes now to take advantage of existing rates, which have 
been creeping up. 
</P>
<P>
	``No doubt some of the strength in sales ... is due to buyers  
locking in before mortgage rates go higher,'' said David Orr, 
economist with First Union. 
</P>
<P>
	A national survey of mortgage rates showed them hitting 7.23  
percent for the past two weeks, the highest level in 18 months. 
</P>
<P>
	And, the Mortgage Bankers Association of America reported  
Wednesday that loan applications increased 1.7 percent last week 
from the previous week. 
</P>
<P>
	``Because interest rates are rising, households are jumping off  
the fence buying homes to lock in rates. So you are going to see a 
nice boost in housing activity because of that,'' said the 
association's economist David Lereah. 
</P>
<P>
	The report on new home sales showed the surge in demand was  
accompanied by a rise in prices. The median price of all new homes 
sold last month climbed 3 percent to a record $159,500. The median 
is the midpoint where half the homes sold for more and half for 
less. 
</P>
<P>
	The average sales price rose 3.7 percent to $193,100, also a  
record. 
</P>
<P>
	Some analysts believed that the rise in home prices along with  
the jump in sales increase the odds that the Federal Reserve would 
jack up interest rates to slow economic activity down to a more 
sustainable pace and relieve rising price pressures. 
</P>
<P>
	The Fed next meets on interest rates June 29-30. At their last  
meeting, Fed officials changed their policy stance in the direction 
of leaning toward a rate increase, a move that has raised worries 
in financial markets that a rate increase could be imminent. 
</P>
<P>
	While stocks were down as much as 131 points at one point  
because of those worries, the Dow Jones industrial average managed 
to rally and close at 10,578, down 18 points. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan said Wednesday he was  
concerned about rising protectionist pressures in the United States 
but he gave no hint in his speech to a Boston business audience 
about the Fed's current thinking on the economy and inflation. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts had expected a fifth straight decline in home sales in  
April, contending that rising mortgage rates were cooling off what 
had been a red hot housing market. But the report showed strong 
sales in every region of the country except the West. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales surged 33.5 percent to an annual rate of 211,000 units in  
the Midwest. Sales were up 17.1 percent to a rate of 89,000 units 
in the Northeast and climbed 7.5 percent to a rate of 429,000 units 
in the South. 
</P>
<P>
	The West, which had seen sales jump 22.9 percent in the previous  
month, suffered a drop of 5.3 percent in April to an annual rate of 
249,000 units. 
</P>
<P>
	``It may be the cooling-off pattern that we thought was  
developing hasn't really developed and it may in fact take the 
higher rates to hold for a little bit to truly cool this market 
down,'' said economist David Seiders with the National Association 
of Home Builders. 
</P>
<P>
	Some analysts believe that a 3.3 percent decline in existing  
homes sales in April and a sharp 2.4 percent decrease in 
construction spending -- including single-family homes -- for the 
same month were signaling a slowdown in housing activity. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990602.0069 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 17:30:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> BB Owners To Review Sale of Royals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) -- Miles Prentice and the people trying to  
sell him the Kansas City Royals learned Wednesday they will meet 
next week with commissioner Bud Selig and baseball's ownership 
committee. 
</P>
<P>
	Prentice, Royals chairman David Glass and team president Mike  
Herman are scheduled to meet with the 11-member committee June 10 
in Milwaukee. 
</P>
<P>
	The ownership committee studies applications for franchise  
ownership and then passes the, along to the 30 major league owners 
for their approval or rejection, usually with a recommendation. 
</P>
<P>
	Prentice, whose group has a deal to purchase the team for $75  
million, had hoped the ownership committee would take up his 
application next week at baseball's quarterly meeting in 
Pittsburgh, but Selig canceled the meeting last week, saying there 
weren't enough agenda items. 
</P>
<P>
	Owners have not met since January and aren't scheduled to gather  
until September at Cooperstown, N.Y. 
</P>
<P>
	``We can only view the invitation to meet with the ownership  
committee as encouraging news,'' Prentice said from New York. 
``It's obviously a sign that the process is moving forward.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Several baseball officials, speaking on the condition they not  
be identified, told The Associated Press last month that Prentice's 
group would not be approved in its proposed form and he would be 
asked to make modifications. 
</P>
<P>
	Some baseball officials were not happy with the size of  
Prentice's group, which numbers more than 40 investors, and want 
fewer people putting up more money. 
</P>
<P>
	Selig is concerned the group may not have enough money to  
operate the franchise successfully, several baseball officials have 
said, also speaking on the condition they not be identified. 
</P>
<P>
	Prentice said he did not know what the committee wanted to  
discuss. 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope they want to talk about our application,'' he said.  
``But I don't know. I was out all day and Mike Herman called and 
said we just got word that we're back on for a meeting on Thursday. 
No one seems to know why or what. But maybe they're in a position 
to have some things to adjudicate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Royals' board gave its approval to the Prentice group's bid  
last November after he met its demand that more than half of the 
money be raised from Kansas City sources. 
</P>
<P>
	The team has been in ownership limbo since the death in 1993 of  
founder Ewing Kauffman. 
</P>
<P>
	``We believe in the integrity of the process,'' Prentice said.  
``We know we have a wonderful group that may be a little larger 
than they're used to. It's one of those things we have to work 
through.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The ownership committee includes Selig, NL president Len  
Coleman, AL president Gene Budig and four team representatives from 
each league: Bill Bartholomay (Atlanta), Andy MacPhail (Chicago 
Cubs), Drayton McLane (Houston), Bill DeWitt (St. Louis), Richard 
Jacobs (Cleveland), Peter Angelos (Baltimore), John Ellis (Seattle) 
and Mike Ilitch (Detroit). 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
