<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Volvo May Build Some Cars in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) -- Volvo Passenger Cars, purchased by Ford  
Motor Co. this year, is considering building some of its next 
generation of cars at Ford's U.S. plants, according to chief 
executive Tuve Johannesson. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's in the nature of things that we at some time will have  
industrial production in North America,'' Johannesson said Tuesday 
at a meeting of business leaders in Goteborg, Volvo's headquarters 
city, according to the Swedish news agency TT. 
</P>
<P>
	Volvo AB sold its car division to Ford in January for $5.8  
billion, saying that the technical challenges faced by carmakers 
could be best solved by large companies with substantial resources. 
</P>
<P>
	Volvo's car production has been about 400,000 a year, a small  
number for the industry as a whole. Volvo AB's remaining divisions 
make trucks, buses, heavy equipment and marine and aircraft 
engines. 
</P>
<P>
	Johanneson said Volvo Cars wants to increase its production by  
some 50 percent to 600,000-700,000 a year by 2005. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is connected to the product line that will come after the  
S/V 40. The volume ambitions we have for these products say to us 
that they will go beyond the European capacity we have at the Born, 
Netherlands, plant of 150,000 cars a year and that we will need 
additional capacity,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Born plant is jointly operated with Mitsubishi Motors of  
Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	Johannesson said there were no plans to begin Volvo production  
at other Mitsubishi plants, ``but our cooperation with Mitsubishi 
remains,'' the business newspaper Dagens Industri quoted him as 
saying. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
