<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AOL Adds Online Music Providers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DULLES, Va. (AP) -- America Online Inc. acquired two Web music  
providers, saying it wants to enable its almost 20 million 
customers to easily play and transmit music over the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	AOL added Spinner Networks Inc. and Nullsoft Inc., the developer  
of the Winamp and SHOUTcast brands, in a deal valued at 
approximately $400 million, according to a company statement 
released Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Spinner, which will maintain its headquarters in San Francisco,  
broadcasts 2 million songs daily and attracts 1.5 million users 
monthly to its Web site, spinner.com. 
</P>
<P>
	The Winamp software, downloaded for free, allows Internet users  
to listen to music transmitted in the MP3 format. SHOUTcast is used 
to broadcast music in the MP3 format over the Internet. Nullsoft 
will move its base from Sedona, Ariz., to San Francisco to merge 
operations with Spinner. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition to building the Spinner and Nullsoft brands, AOL  
plans to create custom-branded music services, offer live and 
Internet-only radio, sporting and other public events, and provide 
downloadable music with directory and search features. 
</P>
<P>
	The acquisitions mark the first major push by AOL to enter the  
online music arena. 
</P>
<P>
	Dulles-based AOL operates two Internet services, America Online  
with more than 17 million members, and CompuServe with 2 million 
members. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
