<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Influx of Cubans Blamed on I.N.S </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- More than 200 Cuban refugees came ashore or were  
picked up off the Florida coast in a recent five-day span, an 
influx that some blame on a new U.S. policy. 
</P>
<P>
	In a clarification of the Cuban Adjustment Act, Immigration  
Commissioner Doris Meissner ruled last month that Cuban refugees 
are immediately eligible for a work permit. 
</P>
<P>
	Before her order, Cuban refugees were not guaranteed employment.  
</P>
<P>
	One Border Patrol agent said the new policy is the reason for  
the increase in refugees, most of whom paid smugglers between 
$5,000 and $7,000 to get here. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no fear of deportation, there's no fear of being held  
in detention a long time,'' Border Patrol agent Dean Sinclair said 
Wednesday. ``The most they'll be held is a week while they're being 
processed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	However, Carmen Marrero, who works with refugees for the  
Catholic Charities Group in Miami, said recent refugees have not 
mentioned the change in INS policy as a reason for coming to the 
United States. 
</P>
<P>
	``They say they come here because they have no freedom and  
because of the economic problems'' in Cuba, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	INS spokesman Dan Kane said he saw no connection between the  
clarified policy and an increase in immigrants from Cuba. 
</P>
<P>
	The Coast Guard detained 272 Cubans found at sea in May, the  
highest monthly total since 1994. From Friday through Tuesday 
night, 222 came ashore or were picked up at sea. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
