<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Steel Makers Request More Tariffs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Leading U.S. steel producers broadened their  
fight against low-priced imports Wednesday, asking the federal 
government to impose punitive tariffs on a high-grade steel 
product. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. industry targeted cold-rolled flat carbon steel from  
Japan, Russia and 10 other countries in the third major round of 
trade complaints since imports reached record levels last year. 
They blame the import surge for thousands of layoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	The latest complaints came despite reductions in imports by  
roughly 40 percent since November. U.S. producers say foreign 
countries continue to flaunt U.S. trade laws that prohibit unfair 
pricing practices. 
</P>
<P>
	``In spite of months of fighting, American steelmakers, their  
employees and communities continue to be devastated by unfairly 
priced and subsidized steel imports,'' said Richard K. Riederer, 
president and chief executive of Weirton Steel Corp, one of eight 
steel producers joining the United Steelworkers of America in the 
official complaints. 
</P>
<P>
	The Asian economic crisis has reduced demand for steel abroad,  
leading foreign producers to find an outlet in a healthy U.S. 
economy. However, In part because of previous trade cases, foreign 
shipments have dropped for five of the past six months. 
</P>
<P>
	A Japanese steel executive, Hidenori Tazawa of NKK America Inc.,  
said the latest complaint ``has absolutely no economic or factual 
basis ... (and) only indicates the lengths to which U.S. steel 
mills are willing to go to stifle legitimate domestic and 
international competition.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The filings with the Commerce Department and the U.S.  
International Trade Commission seek steel tariffs to effectively 
raise prices of foreign shipments. The targeted importing countries 
are Argentina, Brazil, China, Indonesia, Japan, Russia, South 
Africa, Slovakia, Taiwan, Thailand, Turkey and Venezuela. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. industry accused the 12 countries of selling goods  
below production costs or home-market prices. Brazil, Indonesia, 
Thailand and Venezuela also were charged with subsidizing their 
producers to artificially lower prices. 
</P>
<P>
	The Commerce Department already has ruled that Japan illegally  
sold the industry's leading product, hot-rolled carbon steel, at 
unfair prices. The U.S. International Trade Commission is to 
determine next week whether the pricing practices warrant tariffs. 
Similar cases are pending against Russia and Brazil. 
</P>
<P>
	The latest product targeted, cold-rolled flat carbon steel, is  
pressed from hot-rolled sheets into a thinner, stronger material 
that commands a higher price. Typical applications include washing 
machines, refrigerators and some internal auto parts. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
