<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Kashmir Rebels Dismiss Indian Offer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) -- Islamic guerrillas occupying an icy  
Himalayan frontier on Wednesday rejected India's offer of safe 
passage out of the battle zone if they leave their dugouts and 
return to Pakistan. 
</P>
<P>
	The United Jehad Council, which represents 14 militant groups,  
including four main groups fighting in the remote Kargil mountains, 
said the guerrillas would not leave the area because it is their 
``homeland.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It is the Indians who need safe passage,'' Council chairman  
Syed Salahuddin told The Associated Press. ``The Indians are the 
occupation forces.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Muslim guerrillas seized strategic mountain positions in the  
Indian-held part of Kashmir last month. India accuses Pakistan of 
backing the guerrillas in a bid to change the cease-fire line 
through the territory. 
</P>
<P>
	Pakistan, which denies giving military backing the guerrillas  
but allows them to train on its territory, on Wednesday also 
dismissed the safe passage offer by Indian Prime Minister Atal 
Bihari Vajpayee. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is an indigenous movement ... and we have nothing to do  
with it,'' said Pakistani Foreign Ministry spokesman Tariq Altaf. 
</P>
<P>
	India has launched a ground and air offensive to flush out the  
guerrillas from the mountain heights 440 miles north of New Delhi, 
the Indian capital. It says its troops have made major gains during 
the last week, but the militants claim they have not lost ``an 
inch'' during the fighting. 
</P>
<P>
	It was not possible to verify the conflicting claims.  
</P>
<P>
	Kashmir, a former princely state, has been the cause of two wars  
between Pakistan and India since their independence from Britain in 
1947. Each country holds part of Kashmir and claims the rest. 
</P>
<P>
	Muslim militants, who have been waging a bloody secessionist  
insurrection for more than one decade in Kashmir, want either 
outright independence or a merger with Islamic Pakistan. 
</P>
<P>
	India directed all private cable networks to drop Pakistan's  
television channel Wednesday, accusing it of broadcasting biased 
news about hostilities, United News of India news agency said. 
</P>
<P>
	Casualties in the conflict continued to mount Wednesday.  
</P>
<P>
	India said Pakistan artillery left five civilians dead and an  
Indian television transmitter in smoking ruins. Indian air raids 
and artillery reportedly killed at least eight guerrillas and 
wounded five others in the Batalik sector. 
</P>
<P>
	Pakistan officials said all schools were closed near the border  
after three children were killed by Indian shelling in Nar, 50 
miles east of Pakistan's capital, Islamabad. India denied the 
claim. 
</P>
<P>
	Artillery duels and troop reinforcements in the area, more than  
70 miles south of Kargil, raised fears of an escalation along a 
second front. 
</P>
<P>
	In New Delhi, army spokesman Brig. Mohan Bhandari said Indian  
troops pushed back infiltrators two miles and were preparing to 
occupy four or five mountain peaks in the Batalik sector. 
</P>
<P>
	Close-quarters combat was reported for the control of a  
strategic peak where Indian soldiers have reached to within a few 
yards of guerrillas positions. 
</P>
<P>
	India says since the fighting began last month, 46 soldiers have  
been killed, 174 wounded and 12 missing. India estimates it has 
killed 400 guerrillas, but only a few bodies had been recovered. 
</P>
<P>
	India and Pakistan -- two of the world's newest nuclear powers --  
have fought two of their three wars during the past five decades 
over Kashmir, which is claimed by both in its entirety. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
