<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Philly Exchange Urges Trading Delay </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- The chairman of the Philadelphia Stock  
Exchange on Wednesday urged Security and Exchange Commission 
Chairman Arthur Levitt to delay plans for extended stock trading 
hours that would put massive demands on exchanges. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Association of Securities Dealers, which governs  
Nasdaq, approved a plan last week to extend trading hours from the 
current 9:30 a.m. to 4 p.m. Eastern time schedule, with a second 
session that would likely start at 5:30 p.m. and end at 9 p.m. or 
later. 
</P>
<P>
	The board of the New York Stock Exchange is expected to consider  
a proposal Thursday to extend trading hours starting in July as the 
traditional markets try to respond to rising competition from 
overseas exchanges and alternative computer-based exchanges. 
</P>
<P>
	Philadelphia Exchange Chairman Meyer S. Frucher said in a letter  
to Levitt that alternative trading systems ``have increasingly 
assumed many of the economic functions of exchanges but not the 
full range of their regulatory functions.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While Levitt has said the SEC supports investor choice trading  
hours, the SEC also has suggested a delay so the industry would not 
be extending hours at the same time it confronts potential computer 
problems with the Year 2000 date change and shifts from reporting 
stock prices in fractions to using decimals. 
</P>
<P>
	``However attractive extended trading hours may be in the long  
run, extending them at this juncture would create massive 
additional technical and personnel demands on electronic and 
surveillance systems that are already under pressure,'' Frucher 
wrote. 
</P>
<P>
	Weeks of tests have indicated no likelihood of severe Y2K  
problems, he noted, adding, ``It would be unfortunate to see that 
preparation upset by an ill-timed proposal that will require 
substantial resources.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Orderly transition must remain a guiding principle in the face  
of any proposal to alter trading hours,'' he wrote. ``The rush to 
extend hours helter-skelter on a 'me, too' basis makes no sense.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
