<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Nursing Homes Feel Medicare Pinch </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                               *and    	
</P>
<P>
                            *HOLLY RAMER   	
</P>
<P>
                      *Associated Press Writers    	
</P>
<P>
	CONCORD, N.H. (AP) -- The possibility that her nursing home will  
run out of money keeps Ruth Baron awake at night. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm an early-to-bedder,'' Baron told a recent visitor. ``They  
don't have enough help. ... I'm ready to go to bed and there's just 
nobody to put me in bed. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just can't do it on my own.''  
</P>
<P>
	Baron, 77, lives at Harris Hill Center, a nursing home owned by  
Pennsylvania-based Genesis Health Ventures Inc., one of several 
national chains that have taken a financial beating recently. 
</P>
<P>
	The industry blames the financial woes on cuts to Medicare, the  
federal health insurance program for the elderly. Some others, 
however, question whether the nursing home industry contributed to 
its own problems by borrowing heavily in recent years to expand and 
move into new businesses such as rehabilitation therapy. Now, 
they're struggling to pay back loans. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, Sun Healthcare Group, one of the nation's largest  
nursing home chains with 390 facilities in the United States, said 
it failed to make a $7 million interest payment on a $150 million 
loan. 
</P>
<P>
	``The entire industry did a poor job in terms of managing their  
balance sheet,'' said John Ransom, an analyst with Raymond James in 
St. Petersburg, Fla. ``They should have known this was coming.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nursing home officials insist Medicare cuts went deeper than  
initially planned, and that is what's causing their fiscal 
distress. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our finances are out of whack because our reimbursement is not  
adequate,'' said Sun spokesman Charlie Leonard. ``It is ignorant to 
suggest we did something inappropriate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The federal government used to pay nursing homes according to  
actual costs of caring for Medicare patients. Last July, it 
switched to a fixed-rate system. 
</P>
<P>
	Nursing homes complain that the switch, part of the 1997  
balanced-budget deal between President Clinton and Congress, has 
squeezed far more savings from Medicare than lawmakers intended. 
</P>
<P>
	And many nursing homes have been hit by a double financial  
whammy. 
</P>
<P>
	First, under the fixed-rate system, if a nursing home's costs to  
treat a patient exceed the federal reimbursement, it loses money. 
(If the costs are less, the nursing home profits). 
</P>
<P>
	Second, Medicare in January imposed a $1,500 annual limit in  
coverage per patient for physical therapy, and the same annual cap 
for occupational and speech-language therapy. Many nursing homes 
firms had set up companies to deliver highly profitable therapy 
services to their residents and others. 
</P>
<P>
	Staff members at Harris Hill Center said physical therapy and  
other therapy services have been particularly hard hit, but that 
patients haven't been affected yet. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're really pushing us to do more with less,'' said Janet  
Ripel, an occupational therapist. 
</P>
<P>
	John Allard, a Harris Hill administrator, said it will take time  
to adjust to the changes. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to have to learn how to manage and how to live  
within this system in order to survive,'' he said. ``I have no 
reason to believe Genesis will go bankrupt. I have every reason to 
believe we will weather and adjust to this change.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hospitals, which were moved to a similar fixed-rate Medicare  
payment system in the mid-1980s, also feared financial disaster. 
But the hospitals eventually learned how to survive under the new 
system. 
</P>
<P>
	The nursing home industry wants the government to loosen  
restrictions on therapy services to allow exceptions for complex 
cases. It also want Medicare to raise nursing home fees so they 
take into account residents' high drug costs. 
</P>
<P>
	But federal officials are not sure changes are needed.  
</P>
<P>
	``What you're seeing is the failure of the industry to react  
quickly enough to what they knew was coming,'' said Nancy Ann 
DeParle, administrator of the Health Care Financing Administration, 
which oversees Medicare. 
</P>
<P>
	Patient groups also aren't convinced of a problem.  
</P>
<P>
	American Association of Retired Persons lobbyist Tricia Smith  
said there's no evidence that Medicare beneficiaries are having 
trouble getting nursing home care. 
</P>
<P>
	But Sen. Chuck Grassley, R-Iowa, estimates that about 13 percent  
of Medicare beneficiaries, or 750,000 people, will exceed the limit 
this year. And many of those people won't be able to pay for 
coverage on their own. 
</P>
<P>
	Medicare routinely covers fewer than 15 percent of a nursing  
home's patients because the program does not cover long-term care. 
But Medicare can comprise up to 30 percent of nursing home 
companies' revenues because of the outpatient rehabilitation 
services. 
</P>
<P>
	Donald Shumway, New Hampshire's health and human services  
commissioner, has warned that some national chains could run out of 
money. He considers all 2,250 beds in New Hampshire's 
nationally-owned nursing homes at risk. 
</P>
<P>
	``Those chains, while not in the same position uniformly, are  
experiencing financial difficulty due to the losses in Medicare,'' 
Shumway said at a May 17 hearing. ``The reduction in Medicare 
payments have been so significant for many nursing homes it has led 
to very real financial difficulties.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Genesis, which owns 10 nursing homes in the state, has announced  
a loss of $10.8 million for the second quarter. Vencor Inc., which 
operates three New Hampshire homes, lost $12.4 million during the 
second quarter. The Louisville, Ky., company also failed to make a 
recent rent payment of about $19 million for its nursing homes and 
hospitals. 
</P>
<P>
	Seven New Hampshire homes are owned by Sun Healthcare Group of  
Albuquerque, N.M. 
</P>
<P>
	Shumway says the state is keeping close tabs on homes owned by  
the chains to ensure that patients don't suffer. ``Quality of care 
has been assured,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Genesis' regional director, Arthur O'Leary, said the company has  
no plans to cut staff. 
</P>
<P>
	``The reality of the situation is we have to be able to provide  
a certain level of care, and we're not going to be able to do that 
with fewer people,'' he said. ``They have really just cut the 
expense for caring for folks, and we're kind of just riding out the 
storm and hoping legislators come to their senses.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Baron, the Harris Hill Center resident, said the home doesn't  
have enough staff as it is, though she enjoys living there. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's hard to leave your home, but if you have to, this is the  
place to go,'' she said. ``If only they could get some help.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990602.0085 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 15:20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stars' Coach Ignores Tensions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DALLAS (AP) -- Ken Hitchcock has a curious way of handling the  
gut-wrenching tension surrounding Game 7 of the NHL's Western 
Conference finals. 
</P>
<P>
	He ignores it.  
</P>
<P>
	``I think there's almost a peaceful feeling that comes when you  
reach this stage,'' the Dallas Stars coach said Wednesday. ``You 
almost become relaxed because you know a lot of things that are in 
your control were put in place six months previous. 
</P>
<P>
	``You trust your players, you trust your own instincts, then you  
just go out and play.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The top-seeded Stars play the second-seeded Colorado Avalanche  
on Friday night in Dallas to determine which team will face Buffalo 
in the Stanley Cup finals. The Sabres wrapped up the Eastern 
Conference title Monday night. 
</P>
<P>
	The Avalanche had a chance to eliminate the Stars on Tuesday  
night in Denver. They led 1-0 late in the first period but Dallas 
tied it in the second and scored three times in the third for a 4-1 
victory. 
</P>
<P>
	The two days off to prepare for Game 7 allows for a lot of time  
to think about a game that will determine whether they'll be 
playing hockey or golf next week. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's nerve-wracking,'' said Dallas' Guy Carbonneau, a veteran  
of many Game 7s. ``But that's what you play for.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Colorado forward Theo Fleury has played in five Game 7s, so he  
has a good understanding of what it's like, even if his record in 
those games is 1-4. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everybody's a bundle of nerves,'' Fleury said. ``Nobody wants  
to make a mistake out there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Going into the series finale, neither team can claim much of an  
edge. 
</P>
<P>
	Dallas is 6-2 at home in the postseason, but both losses were to  
Colorado. The Avalanche are 8-1 on the road in the playoffs, but 
the only loss was in Dallas. 
</P>
<P>
	Colorado's Patrick Roy is the winningest goaltender in playoff  
history, but he's 2-3 in Game 7s. Dallas' Ed Belfour has a 
reputation for melting under playoff pressure, but he's 2-0 in Game 
7s. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think we're going to see a great Game 7,'' Avalanche coach  
Bob Hartley said. ``The sad part of this is one team will be on 
vacation at the conclusion of Game 7.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hitchcock, who lost his only Game 7 as Dallas' coach, said  
experience has taught him that one team will dominate and clearly 
prove it is better. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's not left up to the seesaw battles that some of the others  
are,'' he said. ``It's the team that plays the best in every aspect 
that usually wins -- the best 5-on-5, has the better special teams 
and the best goaltender.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Stars will definitely be fresher for Game 7 than they were  
in their last Reunion Arena appearance, a 7-5 loss Sunday in Game 
5. Hitchcock blamed his team's sloppy play partly on a 38-hour 
turnaround between games. 
</P>
<P>
	This time they'll have 69 hours.  
</P>
<P>
	``Any time you get extra time off at this time of year,'' he  
said, ``it can't do anything but help.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990602.0086 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 11:40:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Taiwan Shows Its Computer Skills </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) -- Open any personal computer and chances are  
most of its insides were made in Taiwan -- even though the companies 
that produce this technology are relative unknowns. 
</P>
<P>
	This week, however, they're strutting their stuff and trying to  
make a name for themselves at the annual Computex trade show in 
Taipei, one of the top three computer shows in the world. 
</P>
<P>
	With output forecast to rise nearly 15 percent to more than $45  
billion this year, Taiwan is firmly entrenched as the world's third 
largest producer of information technology products, behind Japan 
and the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet, apart from Acer Inc., Taiwan's largest maker of personal  
computers, few Taiwanese companies have established themselves as 
international brand names. For the most part, Taiwan remains a 
high-tech powerhouse whose firms toil in obscurity, crafting the 
parts for computers bearing other companies' names. 
</P>
<P>
	The other two big shows, November's Comdex convention in Las  
Vegas and March's CeBIT in Frankfurt, are where new technology 
often debuts and the big deals are signed. 
</P>
<P>
	But Computex puts buyers face to face with the people who  
actually make many of those products, companies that produce 
computers and their parts on contract for such household names as 
Compaq and IBM. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a chance to get together with clients, and for the  
smaller makers who rent the booths, an opportunity to show off 
their products,'' said Henry Chen, a sales manager with Compal, 
maker of computers for several top U.S. brands. 
</P>
<P>
	Beginning as makers of basic computer parts and Apple and IBM  
knockoffs in the 1980s, Taiwanese companies have built a reputation 
for speed, cost effectiveness and flexibility. 
</P>
<P>
	A wealth of local engineering talent, entrepreneurial spirit and  
funding from venture capital companies have brought it to the 
forefront of the computer hardware business. 
</P>
<P>
	Hardware accounts for about 85 percent of Taiwan's information  
industry product output. At more than 800 booths, companies 
highlighted Taiwan's forte in all its breadth -- from makers of 
cooling fans and switches to assembled notebook computers barely 
thicker than a copy of Reader's Digest. 
</P>
<P>
	``Taiwan is still about manufacturing. Only really Acer Inc. and  
a few others can establish their brand names,'' said Watson Lu of 
industrial computer maker Axiom, standing in front of his company's 
stand on the bustling exhibition floor at Taipei's World Trade 
Center. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite Taiwanese companies' skills in the made-to-order  
contract business, some new design trends were on display at the 
show. 
</P>
<P>
	The semi-opaque hues of Apple's iMac glowed on everything from  
computer mouse devices to speakers. Notebook computers, an area 
where Taiwanese vendors have more than 50 percent of world market 
share, were smaller and more powerful, with sleeker finishes, 
sharper screens and even shockproof and waterproof models. 
</P>
<P>
	Several companies had lower-cost versions of cutting-edge  
products such as video phones. And Taiwan's monitor makers, who 
dominate the industry with more than 60 percent of global market 
share, had new lines of flat-screen LCD monitors that the companies 
say will replace boxy, traditional picture-tube monitors in coming 
years. 
</P>
<P>
	Computer image scanners, another area where Taiwanese companies  
excel with 84 percent of the world market, came in smaller forms 
along with types that run on power from the computer rather than a 
separate outlet. 
</P>
<P>
	Other trendy items included digital cameras, Internet phones and  
game controllers in a myriad designs and sizes. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
