<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stock Prices Rise in Asia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HONG KONG (AP) -- Asia's three biggest stock markets, Tokyo, Hong  
Kong and Singapore, finished higher Wednesday, leading shares 
across the region higher despite concerns that the U.S. Federal 
Reserve could raise interest rates. 
</P>
<P>
	The Tokyo exchange rose for a third straight day on expectations  
that the government may stimulate Japan's economy with new 
measures. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained 9.49 points,  
or 0.06 percent, closing the day at 16,417.99. On Tuesday, the 
index rose 1.84 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nikkei's rise was limited as investors cashed in on gains  
after Tuesday's rally, following a plunge in U.S. technology stocks 
overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	``Fears of a sharp fall in the Nikkei have abated,'' said  
Hiroichi Nishi of Nikko Securities in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders apparently were unconcerned by speculation that higher  
prices in the United States could lead to higher interest rates, 
which make stocks a less attractive investment. 
</P>
<P>
	On currency markets, the U.S. dollar slipped against the  
Japanese yen. The dollar bought 120.54 yen at late afternoon, down 
0.57 yen from late Tuesday in Tokyo and also lower than its late 
New York level of 120.56 yen overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	In Hong Kong, shares closed higher as strong buying in market  
heavyweight HSBC Holdings offset worries over the U.S. economy. 
</P>
<P>
	The blue-chip Hang Seng Index rose 95.08 points, or 0.8 percent,  
to 12,458.64. On Tuesday, the index rose 1.8 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Banking giant HSBC Holdings soared 1.9 percent, lifting market  
sentiment worried over Hong Kong interest rates. 
</P>
<P>
	ELSEWHERE:   	
</P>
<P>
	SINGAPORE: Shares rose as investors waited for fresh news on  
U.S. interest rates. The STI rose 18.48 points, or 1 percent, at 
1,927.36. 
</P>
<P>
	SEOUL: Shares soared 2.8 percent, rising for the seventh  
straight day amid foreign buying and expectations of faster 
economic recovery. The benchmark KOSPI rose 21.28 points to 775.00. 
</P>
<P>
	BANGKOK: Shares rose 2.8 percent as favorable inflation data  
supported heavy buying. The SET index rose 13.07 points to 474.86. 
</P>
<P>
	JAKARTA: Shares fell as investors sold banking stocks on an  
announcement by major banks of large rights issues. The JSX 
Composite Index fell 8.942 points, or 1.5 percent, to 574.315. 
</P>
<P>
	KUALA LUMPUR: Shares fell on foreign selling, which pulled the  
index down 1.3 percent. The Kuala Lumpur Composite Index fell 9.91 
points at 749.46. 
</P>
<P>
	MANILA: Shares fell as traders cashed in profits after two  
sessions of gains. The PSE Index fell 24.55 points, or 1 percent, 
to 2,415.77. 
</P>
<P>
	SYDNEY: Shares fell on weakness in banking, insurance and other  
industrial sector stocks. The All Ordinaries Index fell 0.9 points, 
or 0.03 percent, at 2914.7. 
</P>
<P>
	TAIPEI: Shares rose on buying into technology shares amid news  
of a possible alliance between two of the island's blue-chip 
electronics firms. The Weighted Price Index rose 90.41 points, or 
1.22 percent, at 7,488.03. 
</P>
<P>
	WELLINGTON: Shares rose for a second straight session, boosted  
by solid gains in Telecom Corp. of New Zealand Ltd. and Air New 
Zealand Ltd. The NZSE-40 Capital Index rose 29.74 points, or 1.4 
percent, at 2,127.96. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
