<DOCNO> APW19990602.0095 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 15:00:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Golfer Fred Couples Seeks Comeback  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DUBLIN, Ohio (AP) -- In the last year, Fred Couples has gained a  
family and lost the fire that made him one of the top golfers in 
the world. 
</P>
<P>
	He is back at Muirfield Village Golf Club this week to defend  
his title in the Memorial Tournament. He's talking as if he's more 
homesick than hungry. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not into it right now,'' Couples said Wednesday after his  
final tuneup before the Memorial. ``I love playing still. I'm still 
going to play 16 or 18 tournaments. I'm not quitting. I just don't 
feel like going home at this time and beating my brains into the 
ground.'' 
</P>
<P>
	At 39, he says his time is ``semi-passed.''  
</P>
<P>
	Couples married Thais Bren last September. He and her two  
children from a previous marriage live in Pacific Palisades, Calif. 
Two weeks after he met her, she discovered she had breast cancer. 
After weathering months of treatment -- Couples said she's now doing 
fine -- why get panicky over a few hours playing golf for thousands 
of dollars? 
</P>
<P>
	``I have a ball when I go home,'' Couples said. ``I find other  
things to do. ... I have chosen to stick around and have fun, 
because really that's what I want to do. It's a lot of fun to go to 
softball games and to go to soccer games and to the park and to the 
zoo.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As a result, Couples has never been happier -- and has seldom  
been more erratic in his profession. 
</P>
<P>
	He has played nine tournaments in 1999, has missed two cuts and  
made four top 10s, leaving him 50th on the money list. 
</P>
<P>
	``I played yesterday and today and every shot, you know, it was  
a struggle,'' he said. ``If I don't hit a good one on the 12th 
hole, on the 13th tee I'm thinking of some kind of thought to make 
sure I hit a good one that time. Whereas before, I teed off on 
Thursday and I knew I was going to play well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It is a battle that many golfers lose. You can spend all of your  
time with your family and lose your edge, or you can hit thousands 
of balls and lose precious time with your family. A career teeters 
on the brink, with fame and riches on one side and personal 
satisfaction on the other. 
</P>
<P>
	The addition of children has made the hours away from home even  
worse. 
</P>
<P>
	``I never had any kids. I see Jay Haas, I've been to his house  
and I see his son look up at him and say, `Dad, you have to go 
already?''' Couples said. ``That's hard. It's hard for them to 
understand, that I'm in a plane going to another tournament.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Couples' solution is to pick his spots.  
</P>
<P>
	``Everyone says of basketball players that you don't want to get  
to a game until the fourth quarter,'' he said. ``I don't blame 
them. They're out there playing and busting their butts. You do 
that 82 games a year and there's got to be times when you go out 
there and just go through the motions.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Golf, he said, is different. But not much.  
</P>
<P>
	``For us, you don't ever want to do that,'' he said. ``Every  
week is very important. I never just want to go like I am now, just 
to show up. That's a waste of your time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Couples said he's making the most of his time. In addition to  
defending his title at Muirfield Village Golf Club, he is also 
working on his game for the U.S. Open in two weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	But winning an Open requires something akin to perfection, at  
least off the tee when the fairways are no wider than a tennis 
court and the rough approaches knee deep. 
</P>
<P>
	``What needs to happen for me is I just have to have everything  
go right,'' Couples said. 
</P>
<P>
	The look on his face said he didn't really believe that was  
likely. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
