<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Seles Vs. Graf Reignites Rivalry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- Monica Seles and Steffi Graf have been down this  
path before -- facing each other on center court at Roland Garros in 
the final stages of the French Open. 
</P>
<P>
	On Thursday, they will renew a once-promising rivalry that never  
quite developed when they play in the semifinals of the clay 
tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	Martina Hingis, seeded No. 1, faces defending champion Arantxa  
Sanchez-Vicario in the other semifinal. 
</P>
<P>
	Seven years ago, Seles and Graf played one of the more memorable  
French Open finals. Seles won 6-2, 3-6, 10-8 in a classic contest 
that tennis fans hoped would start a rivalry to match Martina 
Navratilova and Chris Evert. 
</P>
<P>
	It never happened and now they meet again, bringing a different  
perspective to the match, 
</P>
<P>
	``It is definitely a match to look forward to,'' Graf said. ``We  
have had a lot of close matches especially at this tournament and 
we had that one memorable match.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``A couple of matches against Steffi are probably the highlights  
of my career,'' Seles said. 
</P>
<P>
	Over the years, there's been little separating Seles and Graf.  
</P>
<P>
	In six Grand Slam finals, they have won three each. Overall,  
Graf leads 9-5. In Grand Slam matches, the score is 5-3. But Seles 
has won three of five matches on clay. 
</P>
<P>
	The players last met in the quarterfinals of the 1999 Australian  
Open, when Graf uncharacteristically lost concentration and the 
match, 7-5, 6-1. 
</P>
<P>
	Until that match, Seles hadn't beaten Graf since winning the  
1993 Australian Open final. 
</P>
<P>
	``In Australia I played a good match till a certain point. I  
don't know what happened then, but I could not put a ball in the 
court anymore. I completely flunked,'' Graf said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I lost my concentration in a way that has rarely ever happened  
to me,'' she said. ``I was extremely nervous. I didn't have any 
explanation for it, which made it more difficult.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Seles doesn't think that match will have any bearing this time.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's such a different surface here. I just have to be 100  
percent. I did that in Australia. We'll see if I can do it on 
Thursday.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Seles and Graf have had their struggles. A stabbing in 1993 kept  
Seles out of tennis for two years and Graf had knee surgery 
following the French Open two years. That makes matches like 
Thursday's semifinal more meaningful for both of them. 
</P>
<P>
	Seles said she spoke to Graf about it after the Australian Open.  
</P>
<P>
	``Both of us decided to come back because of semifinal and final  
matches, when you have to be 100 percent fit physically, mentally 
and game wise,'' she said. ``The crowd is in it, you are playing 
center court. Those are the times you just love to play.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Among them, Graf, Seles and Sanchez-Vicario have won 11 of the  
last 12 French Open titles. 
</P>
<P>
	Hingis, the only semifinalist looking for a first French Open  
win, has a brilliant record against Sanchez-Vicario. Her 6-4, 6-0, 
win at the German Open last month gave her a 9-1 record, with 
Sanchez-Vicario's sole win coming three years ago, when Hingis was 
15. 
</P>
<P>
	Hingis, who has reached at least the semifinal of every Grand  
Slam since the 1996 Wimbledon championship, has an 18-1 record on 
clay this season and is the tournament favorite. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Sanchez-Vicario has played consistently well over the  
last two weeks and hasn't lost at Roland Garros since her defeat to 
Hingis in the 1997 quarterfinals. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
