<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks End Mixed; Dow Down 18.37 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stock prices were mixed Wednesday as investors  
prepared themselves for a possible increase in interest rates but 
nonetheless went in search of bargains in the battered technology 
sector. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones industrial average fell 18.37 to close at  
10,577.89. The index dropped as much as 131.40 earlier in the 
session before erasing most of the losses in the final hour. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators were slightly higher after paring big  
losses. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 rose 0.55 to 1,294.81, and the 
technology-dominated Nasdaq composite index rose 20.38 to 2,432.41. 
</P>
<P>
	An afternoon speech by Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan  
helped calm a jittery market. The influential policy-maker kept his 
remarks at an international business conference in Boston tightly 
focused on trade, and did not address interest rates. 
</P>
<P>
	The market has been rattled for more than two weeks by  
persistent fears that the Fed will raise rates this summer, hoping 
to cool off the booming economy. 
</P>
<P>
	``The biggest bull market in history has been aided and abetted  
by a friendly Fed,'' said Larry Wachtel, a market analyst at 
Prudential Securities. ``Everyone is afraid of what will happen if 
the Fed turns unfriendly.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While the Dow remained in a narrow trading range throughout  
Greenspan's speech, market watchers strained to catch any hints he 
might offer about the Fed's future course. Alan Skrainka, chief 
market strategist at Edward Jones of St. Louis, said many expect 
the Fed to raise interest rates when its Open Market Committee 
meets June 29. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Fed doesn't want to shock the system, so Greenspan's  
lieutenants have been warming us up for a while,'' he said. 
``People are selling on the rumor of a rate hike, so they may buy 
when the news hits.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wachtel said the market is likely to remain off-balance at least  
until Friday, when the Labor Department reports May's unemployment 
figures. 
</P>
<P>
	``Given the emotional component of that report, there won't be  
any real direction until then,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bond prices continued their tumble after a robust report on new  
home sales. The price of the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond 
recovered slightly by the afternoon and yielded 5.93 percent, but 
the yield had soared to 5.97 in earlier trading. 
</P>
<P>
	A yield of 6 percent is viewed as a critical point for stocks,  
because at that level, higher yields make bonds a more attractive 
investment. 
</P>
<P>
	Interest rate worries depressed bank and financial stocks, with  
J.P. Morgan falling 2 5/8 to 130 7/8. The financial sector is especially 
vulnerable to higher interest rates because lending volume shrinks 
when it becomes more expensive to borrow. 
</P>
<P>
	Investment firms, including online brokerages, also fell on  
interest rate concerns. DLJ Direct was down 5 1/8 to 33 5/8. Analysts 
said Merrill Lynch's announcement Tuesday that it plans an online 
service put additional pressure on the brokerage sector. Merrill 
Lynch itself was down 4 9/16 to 70 11/16. 
</P>
<P>
	Technology companies began the day by tumbling yet again, but  
their weakened prices enticed some buyers later in the session. 
Intel, which has slipped amid concerns about its earnings outlook, 
rose 1 1/4 to 51 15/16. 
</P>
<P>
	Yahoo! rose 4 5/16 to 142 1/2, buoyed by the news that Sprint  
Corp.'s PCS Group will offer Yahoo! content to users of its 
wireless phones. 
</P>
<P>
	Bookseller Barnes &AMP; Noble rose 1 1/4 to 28 5/8 after it called off its  
planned acquisition of book distributor Ingram Book Group. The 
company's online wing, barnesandnoble.com, fell 2 13/16 to 17 3/16. 
</P>
<P>
	Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 6-to-5 margin on the  
New York Stock Exchange, where consolidated volume totaled 877.17 
million shares, compared with 824.34 million in the previous 
session. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index fell 0.78 to 620.50, and the American  
Stock Exchange composite index fell 4.88 to 771.23. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 0.72 to 436.74.  
</P>
<P>
	Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average rose 0.06 percent.  
Germany's DAX index rose 0.6 percent, Britain's FT-SE 100 gained 
0.8 percent, and France's CAC-40 ended nearly flat, just 1.65 
points higher than Wednesday's close. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
