<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Athletes Want Bigger IOC Role </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAUSANNE, Switzerland (AP) -- As the International Olympic  
Committee opened debate on possible reforms, athletes made forceful 
arguments for being given decision-making roles. 
</P>
<P>
	``Will the IOC, who claim that the Olympics are for the  
athletes, support the athletes, empower the athletes, give them 
full status in the Olympic family?'' said Johann Olav Koss, the 
Norwegian speedskater who won three gold medals at the 1994 
Lillehammer Games. 
</P>
<P>
	``If it's not about the athletes,'' Koss said, ``then what is it  
about?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Koss sits on the IOC athletes' commission, the only IOC panel  
with democratically elected members. He and the nine other member 
athletes are serving on IOC 2000, an reform commission set up in 
the wake of the Salt Lake City bribery scandal. 
</P>
<P>
	In a speech at the opening session Tuesday, Koss proposed that  
10 more athletes be elected to the athletes' commission and that 
all 20 be appointed members of a restructured IOC. He suggested 
that two athletes serve on the powerful IOC executive board. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are the most legitimate people in the IOC,'' said Algerian  
runner Hassiba Boulmerka, the women's 1,500-meter gold medalist at 
the 1992 Barcelona Games. ``We were elected. We should have the 
most power.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Boulmerka said the selection of Olympic host cities should be  
based on site visits by those who will be competing there, not by 
``an institution of elderly men.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't want to have the same problems of Atlanta (in 1996),  
where athletes suffered from the heat and heavy security,'' she 
said. ``We want to choose the best sites.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While the IOC has dozens of former Olympians among its ranks,  
the athletes stressed the need for current or recently retired 
competitors to serve on the committee. 
</P>
<P>
	Bob Ctvrtlik, who played on three U.S. Olympic volleyball teams,  
said athletes ``do have a voice, but it's a small voice. If we are 
to have a role as a third pillar in the Olympic movement, we have a 
long way to go.'' 
</P>
<P>
	IOC 2000 is examining ways of reshaping the IOC's structure and  
the process for selecting Olympic host cities. 
</P>
<P>
	Former Secretary of State Henry Kissinger was among several  
speakers who called on the IOC to be more open, accountable and 
representative. 
</P>
<P>
	But the opening session was tempered by words of caution, with  
delegates warning against radical change in a 105-year-old 
organization, which has endured world wars, terrorism and boycotts. 
</P>
<P>
	``The main theme was there should more of an evolution, not a  
revolution,'' IOC spokesman Franklin Servan-Schreiber said. ``We 
need to adapt and to update the structure of the IOC -- not destroy 
and rebuild it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The commission is expected to consider changes to the way IOC  
members are selected, including introducing term limits and 
reducing the mandatory retirement age, which is now 80. 
</P>
<P>
	The commission, which is divided into three working groups, is  
to submit a preliminary report June 20 at the next IOC general 
assembly in Seoul, South Korea. Final recommendations are scheduled 
to be adopted at a special IOC session in December. 
</P>
<P>
	Consensus on some issues might be hard to reach. Ctvrtlik said  
there were ``probably 50-60 divergent views'' expressed during the 
working group meeting on the site-selection process. 
</P>
<P>
	In other developments:  
</P>
<P>
	--Dick Ebersol, the president of NBC Sports and an IOC 2000  
member, said American athletes were suffering from ``cynical ... 
self-serving'' attacks on the IOC by John Hancock insurance 
president David D'Alessandro. 
</P>
<P>
	D'Alessandro, whose company is a top-level Olympic sponsor, said  
Ebersol was concerned that the scandal would devalue his network's 
$3.5 billion Olympics rights package. 
</P>
<P>
	--Australian IOC member Phil Coles said he would have a lot to  
present in his defense during today's appearance before a special 
panel investigating charges of ethical misconduct. 
</P>
<P>
	Coles, who denies any wrongdoing, could be expelled from the IOC  
if the panel concludes he abused his position. Most recently, he 
has faced allegations that he passed memos and evaluations of other 
IOC members to Salt Lake City's bid team. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
