<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 14:54:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> EU Ministers Insist on Doping Ban </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PADERBORN, Germany (AP) -- European Union sports ministers  
remained on a collision course with some major sports by insisting 
Wednesday on a two-year ban for first-time doping offenders. 
</P>
<P>
	A joint statement issued after a two-day informal meeting of the  
15 ministers said a planned worldwide anti-doping agency should be 
independent and empowered to impose sanctions. 
</P>
<P>
	Otto Schily, Germany's interior minister and chairman of the  
meeting, said the ministers had agreed about the two-year ban, 
although he conceded that there could be legal problems. 
</P>
<P>
	``An international system of sanctions is needed, such as a  
minimum ban of two years for first-time offenders,'' Schily said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We still have to check it legally though,'' Schily said. ``Our  
goal remains to have a strict and hard punishment for doping 
violations.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Several major sports, such as soccer, cycling and tennis, are  
opposed to a two-year ban, arguing that such a punishment for a 
first offense would never hold up to challenges under right-to-work 
laws. 
</P>
<P>
	Schily met later in the day with Sepp Blatter, president of  
FIFA, soccer's world governing body, and the two men indicated a 
possible compromise. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are differences of opinion on the legal interpretation  
of the minimum punishment,'' Schily said. 
</P>
<P>
	``But we've agreed that these differences should be examined by  
a panel of international experts,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Blatter said FIFA must be flexible.  
</P>
<P>
	``We are going to set up in-training controls through our  
national federations and perhaps impose punishments that would go 
beyond the minimum two-year ban,'' Blatter told reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	At a meeting in Lausanne in February, the 15 EU governments and  
the International Olympic Committee failed to agree on an 
anti-doping program. 
</P>
<P>
	The EU governments refused to allow the IOC a lead role in the  
proposed anti-doping agency, which would supervise worldwide drug 
testing and policy and have an initial budget of $25 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The joint statement said it would be ``desirable'' for the  
agency to be based in one of the EU capitals and not in Lausanne, 
which also serves as the seat of the IOC. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990602.0101 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 20:00:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Pilot in Crash Had Worked 13 1/2 Hours </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) -- American Airlines pilot Richard  
Buschmann had been on duty for 13 1/2 hours as he tried to land in a 
severe thunderstorm. 
</P>
<P>
	Capt. Buschmann, who had significant experience with MD-80 jets,  
was nearing his maximum of roughly 14 hours on duty when the plane 
skidded off an Arkansas runway shortly before midnight Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The jet crashed against a light tower at the Little Rock airport  
and burst into flames, killing nine people. 
</P>
<P>
	American's chief pilot, Cecil Ewell, said such long days and  
difficult flying conditions are not talked about often, but are not 
infrequent for airline pilots. 
</P>
<P>
	``These are the kinds of things you don't hear about. These guys  
work very hard,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Buschmann was the airline's chief pilot in Chicago, with 9,600  
flight hours and 5,500 flight hours on MD-80s, the same class as 
the MD-82 twin-engine jet that crashed. 
</P>
<P>
	His experience qualified him to check other American pilots on  
their handling of that aircraft, American spokeswoman Andrea Rader 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Both he and the other pilot in the cockpit, First Officer  
Michael Origel, were nearing their federally regulated maximum of 
roughly 14 hours when the plane crashed. Their scheduled 11-hour 
day, with 3 flights, ran long because of delays, including 
thunderstorms in Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	``If they couldn't get to Little Rock within the limits, we  
never would have sent them,'' said Bob Baker, executive vice 
president of flight operations. 
</P>
<P>
	Origel, who escaped with a broken leg, joined Fort Worth,  
Texas-based American in February and was based in Chicago. In bad 
weather, the first officer's responsibility would have been manning 
the radios to get weather reports from the airport control tower. 
</P>
<P>
	Two of the four flight attendants also were injured. Nancy Luna  
suffered a fractured pelvis and Jennifer Chapman broke her leg. 



  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990602.0102 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 11:20:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Another Lawsuit Against Dennis Rodman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAS VEGAS (AP) -- Dennis Rodman is being sued again.  
</P>
<P>
	A Kentucky woman has filed suit against the flamboyant former  
NBA player, claiming he assaulted her in the lobby of a Las Vegas 
resort. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit, filed Tuesday in state District Court by Rebecca  
Mardis of Laurel County, Ky., is the latest of several filed 
against Rodman in Las Vegas. 
</P>
<P>
	Mardis alleges Rodman slammed her camera to the floor and lifted  
her into the air in a threatening manner, then laughed at her 
fright. The suit alleges it took place in January in the lobby of 
the MGM Grand Hotel when she tried to take his photo. 
</P>
<P>
	Messages to Rodman's representative at International Creative  
Management were not immediately returned Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Mardis seeks $1 million in punitive damages because she alleges  
Rodman has a history of assaulting people. In her lawsuit, Mardis 
alleges assault, battery, intentional infliction of emotional 
distress and property damage. 
</P>
<P>
	On May 19, a casino security guard sued Rodman, accusing him of  
grabbing her breast while she was working at the Las Vegas Hilton. 
</P>
<P>
	Three lawsuits filed in Las Vegas in June 1998 involve other  
allegations about Rodman's behavior in casinos. 
</P>
<P>
	A Las Vegas Hilton employee accused him of grabbing her and  
lifting her off the ground in April 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	A Las Vegas woman accused Rodman of sexually assaulting her in  
April 1998 at the Las Vegas Hilton. 
</P>
<P>
	A craps dealer at The Mirage filed a lawsuit alleging Rodman  
humiliated him at work by rubbing his groin and head. 
</P>
<P>
	Rodman played for the Detroit Pistons and Chicago Bulls before  
joining the Los Angeles Lakers for a short stint this year. The 
Lakers waived him in April. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
