<DOCNO> APW19990602.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 20:10:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Atlanta Olympics Report Details Bid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Atlanta Olympic officials acknowledged Wednesday  
that they dispensed gifts and favors to try to land the 1996 Games, 
including a $25,000 donation to a South African anti-apartheid 
group and a used bus that was sent to Peru. 
</P>
<P>
	The gifts were detailed in an internal report that was given to  
the House Commerce Committee on Tuesday. It includes numerous 
examples of gifts to International Olympic Committee members or 
their families that exceeded the IOC's $200 limit. 
</P>
<P>
	The report did not suggest any laws were broken.  
</P>
<P>
	Other gifts included $30,000 in sports equipment and  
infrastructure to the Republic of Congo and about $15,000 for two 
teen-age tennis players from the African nation to attend an 
exclusive tennis camp in Florida. Both gifts were in 1990. 
</P>
<P>
	The House committee is looking into Atlanta's successful bid for  
the 1996 Summer Games while it investigates the bribery scandal 
surrounding the 2002 Winter Games in Salt Lake City. The Salt Lake 
scandal includes allegations of scholarships, medical care and job 
offers for IOC members and their families. 
</P>
<P>
	Billy Payne, who headed Atlanta's effort to land the Olympics,  
dismissed most of the violations off as minor. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think we've established in this report that we've acted with  
integrity and honesty,'' he said. ``In fact, most of the issues we 
discuss in our report were conducted with goodwill and humanitarian 
goals in mind.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The biggest beneficiary was the Republic of Congo. Gifts were  
provided at the request of the country's Jean-Claude Ganga, one of 
six IOC members expelled after the Salt Lake scandal, according to 
the report. 
</P>
<P>
	Andrew Young, the former Atlanta mayor and one of the leaders of  
Atlanta's campaign, said Ganga never made any requests for himself 
but was looking out for his country and for other African 
countries. 
</P>
<P>
	``The amounts of assistance involved were really  
insignificant,'' Young said. He said IOC investigators have ``been 
unfair by holding representatives from struggling, strife-ridden 
countries up to the same standard as, say, England or France.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Atlanta campaign violated the $200 limit on individual gifts  
38 times, according to the report. Four gifts exceeded $500, 
including a live bulldog that cost $875 and a $948 carburetor kit. 
</P>
<P>
	Another donation included a $25,000 gift to the South African  
Non-Racial Olympic Committee, an anti-apartheid organization 
seeking to get South Africa back into the Olympics. And the Atlanta 
group sent a used bus worth $10,310 to Lima, Peru and a fast-food 
chain eventually paid for the bus. 
</P>
<P>
	The report shows six IOC members brought two or more companions  
on trips to Atlanta that were financed by the Atlanta group. IOC 
rules limit members to one companion on such trips. 
</P>
<P>
	In several instances, IOC members showed up with children or  
other family members, Payne said. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was just Southern hospitality,'' he said. ``It wasn't like  
we were going to turn them away.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The report was compiled by the Georgia Amateur Athletic  
Foundation, which oversaw the formation of Atlanta Committee for 
the Olympic Games. It holds about 1,400 boxes of records that 
include the history of the bid. 
</P>
<P>
	Rep. Fred Upton, R-Mich., chairman of the subcommittee heading  
the investigation, said that he was glad to get the report but that 
investigators will be in Atlanta as early as Thursday to look 
through the rest of the city's Olympic records. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990602.0105 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 22:20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Grain Storage Bins Full / Farm Scene  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WICHITA, Kan. (AP) -- Less than three weeks from the start of  
wheat harvest, Duane Boyd uneasily takes stock of his bulging grain 
bins at the Offerle Co-op in southwest Kansas. 
</P>
<P>
	By this time, the soybean crop should have been gone, but he  
still has half of it left in storage at the elevator. And he has 
too much corn, too much milo and even too much of last year's wheat 
still in the bins. 
</P>
<P>
	Not enough room for the new crop, he said.  
</P>
<P>
	``We have less space available this year than we did last year,  
and a lot of that is due to larger carryover of corn and milo 
stocks, plus additional stocks of wheat that hasn't been sold from 
the previous year,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Normally, Boyd would have just 15 percent of the corn and milo  
crop still in the elevator by this date. But he has closer to 35 
percent of those crops still in the bins, and no prospects of 
selling much of it before the local wheat harvest begins around 
June 17. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have just about all the space made that I can make right  
now,'' Boyd said. 
</P>
<P>
	He figured that even if the wheat harvest comes in at 15 percent  
less than last year, he will still have to scramble to find another 
terminal to take 300,000 to 400,000 bushels of wheat, which doesn't 
store very well on the ground. 
</P>
<P>
	But in Salina, Chuck Elsea at Scoular Grain Co. said his  
elevator has plenty of room for this year's wheat harvest. 
</P>
<P>
	``We worked pretty hard beginning back in February to get  
ourselves ready for harvest,'' Elsea said. ``We are there now. We 
have more room than a year ago. We are ready.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And at the Collingwood grain elevator outside Hutchinson, wheat  
trader Brian Simpson said grain stocks are a little higher than 
last year because of carryovers in the market, ``but we feel pretty 
comfortable about taking wheat stocks.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Just where the state stands in grain stocks still in storage  
won't be known officially until the end of June, when Kansas 
Agricultural Statistics compiles its quarterly grain stocks report. 
By that time, the Kansas winter wheat harvest will be in full 
swing. 
</P>
<P>
	Kansas is going into the 1999 wheat harvest with a 60 million to  
80 million bushels worth of new storage space added in the past 12 
months, said Tom Tunnell, president of the Kansas Feed and Grain 
Association. 
</P>
<P>
	``People are rapidly constructing new bins, and anything that  
can be brought out of mothballs has been retrofitted and brought 
back,'' Tunnell said. 
</P>
<P>
	In the past few years, grain storage shortages have surfaced  
mostly in the fall, when the harvests for corn, milo and soybean 
are brought in. Low prices and a weak export market have just 
aggravated the situation as farmers hang onto larger than usual 
grain stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think our real problem is going to come between wheat  
harvest and fall harvest, when we are kind of looking at ideal 
conditions for those crops,'' Boyd said. ``If they come in real 
strong, we almost have to empty our elevator in three months to 
make room for milo, corn and beans.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
