<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Poll: Aussies Wary on Olympic Ads </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SYDNEY, Australia (AP) -- The International Olympic Committee  
scandal has resulted in 14 percent of Australians being less 
positive towards sponsors for the Sydney 2000 Olympic games, 
according to a survey. 
</P>
<P>
	The poll, published in The Australian newspaper on Thursday, was  
conducted from May 28-30 and surveyed 1,200 people over 18 years 
old in all Australian states. The results were weighted to reflect 
the population distribution. 
</P>
<P>
	The survey has a margin of error of 5 percent.  
</P>
<P>
	While the poll shows an 80 percent majority of those surveyed  
feel the same about sponsors, the number less positive towards them 
was 14 percent, against 3 percent who are more positive. 
</P>
<P>
	Carden Calder, Olympic communications manager with Australian  
torch relay sponsor AMP, played down the results, saying Sydney's 
construction-zone existence also could have led to declining 
attitudes. 
</P>
<P>
	``If sponsors have strong commercial programs in place, they  
have nothing to worry about,'' Calder said. 
</P>
<P>
	Figures showing general attitudes to the Olympics also show a  
significant number of people are more negative about the Games. 
</P>
<P>
	The poll showed 71 percent of people have the same attitude in  
the wake of the scandals, 22 percent less positive and 5 percent a 
more positive attitude about the Olympics. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
