<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> First Lady Speaks at NYC Graduation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- As she edges closer to a run for the Senate,  
Hillary Rodham Clinton told City College graduates today that they 
should be wary of those who criticize schools ``to score political 
points'' -- a subtle jab at a potential Republican rival. 
</P>
<P>
	``Run, Hillary, run,'' the graduates exhorted Mrs. Clinton, who  
aides say is virtually certain to seek the Senate seat being 
vacated by Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan of New York. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton called for investing in early childhood education,  
rebuilding crumbling schools and raising educational standards. 
</P>
<P>
	``We can do this if instead of pointing fingers we roll up our  
sleeves and pledge to work together,'' she told the 3,000 graduates 
and their families who gathered in the open-air Lewisohn Plaza at 
the Harlem campus. 
</P>
<P>
	She said that criticism of the schools should be used ``not just  
to score political points. 
</P>
<P>
	``We can never lift up our public schools by tearing them down  
and undermining the public education system that is at the very 
foundation of the American dream,'' Mrs. Clinton said. 
</P>
<P>
	She did not mention a potential Republican rival for Senate,  
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, by name, but Giuliani has been embroiled in 
a very public debate with Schools Chancellor Rudy Crew over the 
state of city school system. 
</P>
<P>
	The first lady held a round of campaign staff interviews at the  
White House on Tuesday. Aides said Mrs. Clinton would notify New 
York Rep. Nita Lowey, a Democrat who was considering the race 
herself, of her plans sometime in the next few days. 
</P>
<P>
	Barring a ``dramatic change of heart,'' Mrs. Clinton will run,  
said one aide, who spoke on condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	Wearing a purple graduation gown, Mrs. Clinton today was awarded  
the City College President's Medal for championing women's rights 
and children's and educational issues. 
</P>
<P>
	When she mentioned her recent visit to Macedonia to visit ethnic  
Albanian refugees from Kosovo, several dozen graduates lifted a 
huge banner and began chanting, ``Stop the War.'' Mrs. Clinton 
continued without comment. 
</P>
<P>
	The crowd was otherwise jubilant at Mrs. Clinton's appearance,  
at times chanting, ``Run, Hillary, run.'' As she walked through 
their ranks to the podium, many gave her impromptu hugs and reached 
over to shake her hand. 
</P>
<P>
	One graduate had written, ``It takes a village,'' a reference to  
Mrs. Clinton's book, on the inside of her mortarboard. Later in her 
speech, Mrs. Clinton acknowledged the student's message and noted 
that many of the graduates had reached their educational goals with 
help from their families and friends. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton was also scheduled to attend a Democratic Party  
luncheon honoring the president of a powerful local teachers' union 
and an evening fund-raising reception for Rep. Carolyn Maloney, 
D-N.Y. 
</P>
<P>
	As for the first lady's Senate designs, Lowey spokesman Howard  
Wolfson said Tuesday the congresswoman had not been notified. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are not aware of any decision having been made,'' Wolfson  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	A senior adviser to the first lady who is involved in her  
deliberations said she is close to finalizing her decision to run. 
</P>
<P>
	The official said Mrs. Clinton seemed even more likely to run  
after spending the Memorial Day weekend with her husband in 
Florida. 
</P>
<P>
	For the record, Mrs. Clinton's spokeswoman, Marsha Berry, said:  
``Nothing has changed except that they are back from vacation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The first lady met Tuesday at the White House with potential  
campaign workers, including Hank Morris, a New York consultant 
coming off Chuck Schumer's victorious 1998 Senate campaign to 
unseat Republican incumbent Alfonse D'Amato; and Gabrielle 
Fialkoff, who was the chief fund-raiser for New York City Council 
Speaker Peter Vallone's unsuccessful gubernatorial bid last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Several of Mrs. Clinton's friends and advisers said they expect  
the next step in her deliberative move toward a campaign to be the 
announcement of a formal exploratory committee. That likely won't 
occur until Mrs. Clinton returns from foreign travel set for June 
15-30. She is scheduled to travel through Europe with President 
Clinton to the summit of G-8 leaders in Germany, and then split off 
for a solo tour through Israel, Jordan and Morocco. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
