<CATEGORY> weather </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Storms that spawned killer tornadoes in Illinois and Oklahoma  
were continuing this morning in the Midwest, bringing more damaging 
winds, hail and rain to the sodden region. 
</P>
<P>
	Showers and thunderstorms were hanging along a stationary front  
in the Midwest, bringing hail and high winds to Illinois, Iowa, and 
Missouri. 
</P>
<P>
	More than a dozen tornadoes were reported Tuesday and early  
today in central and southern Illinois. One blew railroad cars off 
a track near Carlinville, between Springfield and St. Louis. 
</P>
<P>
	Another ripped through a rest stop in Farmersville, Ill.,  
Tuesday evening, killing a trucker who was apparently asleep inside 
his rig when it blew over, crushing him, authorities said. 
</P>
<P>
	In eastern Oklahoma, a woman died when a twister hit two  
communities on the eastern shore of Fort Gibson Lake just north of 
Sequoyah State Park. 
</P>
<P>
	Storms were expected to continue, with winds reaching 60 mph, in  
parts of Indiana, Ohio, Kentucky, and Tennessee. 
</P>
<P>
	Scattered showers were also possible in the northern Plains,  
while partly cloudy skies and a chance of showers and storms were 
forecast for the southern Plains, particularly eastern Texas and 
central and east Oklahoma. 
</P>
<P>
	A cold front stretching from the Great Lakes region to New  
England was pushing light to moderate showers into Maine, Vermont, 
New Hampshire, Massachusetts and New York. Forecasters predicted 
the front would stall this morning, keeping the wet weather in the 
Northeast. 
</P>
<P>
	High pressure was bringing clear to partly cloudy skies in the  
mid-Atlantic states and the Southeast, where typical warm-weather 
afternoon storms were possible. Mild storms in southern Florida 
were expected to die out this morning. 
</P>
<P>
	Clouds and scattered showers covered the Pacific Northwest due  
to a stationary front across central Montana, Idaho and southern 
Oregon. Rain also was falling this morning in Nevada and central 
California, and clouds were gathering in the desert Southwest due 
to a low off the coast. 
</P>
<P>
	Highs today were expected in the 90s in parts of Florida, Texas  
and the desert Southwest; the 80s from the East Coast through the 
Southeast and mid-South to the central and northern Plains; the 60s 
and 70s from the Great Lakes to extreme northern New England; and 
ranging from the 50s to the 70s from the West Coast to the eastern 
Rockies. 
</P>
<P>
	Temperatures Tuesday in the lower 48 states ranged from 108 in  
Mineral Wells, Texas, to 30 in Leadville, Colo. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990602.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 12:20:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lewises Enjoy Ride With Charismatic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEWPORT BEACH, Calif. (AP) -- Bob Lewis will always remember  
Charismatic, whether or not the colt makes Triple Crown history 
with a victory in the Belmont Stakes. 
</P>
<P>
	The horse bit the hand that buys his feed when Lewis visited  
Charismatic in the barn after the Preakness Stakes. Ten stitches 
and a few laughs later, Lewis says, ``I just keep my hands to 
myself.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lewis and his wife, Beverly, bought Charismatic for $200,000. He  
could turn out to be their best investment in nine years of owning 
horses. 
</P>
<P>
	For the second time in three years, racing's favorite senior  
citizens own another horse with a chance to become the 12th Triple 
Crown winner in history. If Charismatic should win Saturday, Bob, 
75, and Beverly, 72, don't believe it would change their lives. 
</P>
<P>
	``It would be fun,'' he said. ``It would be another milestone.''  
</P>
<P>
	After the Preakness last month, the Lewises returned to their  
harbor-front home on Lido Isle across a bridge from Newport Beach. 
</P>
<P>
	On a table behind the floral sofa in the living room are the  
trophies won by Silver Charm in the 1997 Kentucky Derby and 
Preakness. His Triple Crown bid fell short when the colt lost by 
three-quarters of a length in the Belmont. 
</P>
<P>
	That year, the Lewises chartered a plane to New York for more  
than 100 friends, many of whom cried when Silver Charm lost. Bob 
Lewis didn't like the reaction. 
</P>
<P>
	``I kind of gave my old first sergeant approach,'' the former  
World War II platoon sergeant said, ``and had them snap to and told 
them, `This isn't the end of the world for God's sakes. We just 
lost a horse race and I'm sure we're going to lose a lot more.''' 
</P>
<P>
	His pep talk worked. The group went back to their hotel and  
partied. 
</P>
<P>
	The Lewises are unlike many big-time owners. They didn't grow up  
around horses, have sat on the animals only twice in their lives, 
and aren't diehard gamblers. 
</P>
<P>
	``Love the horses, love seeing the race,'' said Bob Lewis, who  
when he was 10 years old accompanied his parents to Santa Anita on 
the first Saturday the track was open in 1934. 
</P>
<P>
	Lewis, who started out as a beer sales representative, earned  
his wealth as founder of Foothill Beverage Co., one of the largest 
Anheuser-Busch distributors in the country. He remains chairman, 
and his oldest son is general manager. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1990, the Lewises bought their first two thoroughbreds.  
Success wasn't far behind. They won their first race and had their 
first stakes winner that year. 
</P>
<P>
	Their champions include Timber Country, winner of the 1995  
Preakness, and filly Serena's Song, who won several Grade I stakes. 
</P>
<P>
	After Charismatic won the Kentucky Derby and Preakness, the  
couple watched two of their 55 horses currently in training win at 
Hollywood Park. 
</P>
<P>
	``It almost gets to a point where it's a little embarrassing,''  
Lewis said. ``We kind of backed into the winners' circle. Maybe 
somebody up there was going to boo us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Don't bet on it.  
</P>
<P>
	Chris Antley, who rides Charismatic, said the Lewises remind him  
of Chip and Dale, the upbeat Disney cartoon chipmunks who 
constantly look out for each other. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're always happy,'' Antley said. ``They're always  
shoulder-length apart. If he turns to the left, she turns to the 
left behind him. They're about as true a people as you would ever 
know.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The couple met at the University of Oregon, where Bob asked  
Beverly out for a beer after she auditioned for the pep squad. 
Their horses race in the university's green-and-gold colors. 
</P>
<P>
	``I went along not for the beer but for the nice young man who  
invited me out,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	They married in 1947 and honeymooned at Del Mar race track.  
Fifty years later, they returned to the seaside track for their 
anniversary. 
</P>
<P>
	The couple isn't overly sentimental about their horses. Lewis  
insists they are business investments, not family members. 
</P>
<P>
	``Don't you believe he's not emotional,'' Mrs. Lewis told a  
visitor. ``I've never seen him so out of control at the 
Preakness.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't get nervous at all until the race has ended,'' he  
said. ``After the Preakness, I was trembling.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Trembling and yelling,'' she added. ``My legs turned to  
noodles. It's draining.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In the celebratory rush after Charismatic won the Kentucky  
Derby, Mrs. Lewis forgot to cash her ticket. Liking the 31-1 odds 
on her horse, she bet $20 across the board. The payoff was more 
than $1,000. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've never made so much on a ticket in my life,'' she said,  
smiling. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of the same friends who supported the Lewises two years ago  
in New York are coming in again. The couple won't cry in their beer 
if Charismatic loses. 
</P>
<P>
	``If the fifth day of June isn't our day, we'll have one less  
trophy sitting on the bar,'' he said. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990602.0112 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 11:00:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Nuke Treaty Remains in Senate Limbo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- If ratified, a nuclear test ban treaty that  
has languished before the Senate for 20 months could make it harder 
for China to advance its acquired nuclear-weapons capacity, 
arms-control advocates say. 
</P>
<P>
	But the pact -- the Comprehensive Nuclear Test Ban Treaty --  
remains caught in a dispute between the Clinton administration and 
the Republican-led Senate over modifications to an earlier 
arms-control agreement, the 1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile treaty. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., has refused to schedule hearings on  
the Comprehensive Nuclear Test Ban Treaty until the administration 
sends the ABM amendments to the Senate for ratification. Helms had 
given the White House until Tuesday to submit the ABM legislation -- 
threatening to put a freeze on all treaties if it failed to do so. 
</P>
<P>
	The ABM modifications, which concern how the treaty affects  
other former Soviet republics as well as Russia, were agreed to by 
Clinton and Russian President Boris Yeltsin. But the administration 
doesn't want to submit them to the Senate until the Russian 
parliament ratifies a later arms control regimen -- the so-called 
START II treaty. 
</P>
<P>
	With US-Russian relations strained by NATO's bombing in  
Yugoslavia, the Russian Duma does not seem inclined to act soon. 
</P>
<P>
	``The situation has been thrown off course by the Kosovo  
operation,'' said a senior White House official who spoke on 
condition of anonymity. ``We intend to try to put the arms control 
track back in gear with the Russians.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Administration officials fear that Helms and other Senate  
conservatives will use the delay to pull the United States out of 
the ABM treaty entirely. Helms has said the 1972 treaty belongs in 
the ``dust bin of history'' because the Soviet Union no longer 
exists. 
</P>
<P>
	Some Democratic supporters of the Comprehensive Nuclear Test Ban  
Treaty have hinted that they may use procedural devices in the 
Senate this month to pressure Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, 
R-Miss., to put the treaty on the agenda this summer. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Byron Dorgan, D-S.D., said he and the others would ``speak  
with some aggressiveness on this issue.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The treaty -- which obligates its signatories not to carry out  
any nuclear weapons test explosions -- sets a September 1999 
deadline for winning ratification. 
</P>
<P>
	But neither the Senate GOP leadership nor the administration  
seemed ready to budge. 
</P>
<P>
	Daryl Kimball, executive director of the Coalition to Reduce  
Nuclear Dangers, an umbrella group of the 17 largest 
nonproliferation organizations, said the Comprehensive Nuclear Test 
Ban Treaty ``is one of the few tools that is available to the 
United States to prevent China from conducting nuclear tests on its 
warhead designs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``How helpful is it to national security to delay consideration  
of a treaty that's been in the Senate for 20 months now?'' Kimball 
asked. 
</P>
<P>
	The treaty has been signed by 152 countries, including Russia  
and China. But only 29 have ratified it. And of those, only two are 
nuclear powers: Britain and France. To take effect, all 44 nations 
with nuclear technology must ratify the treaty. 
</P>
<P>
	China held its last underground nuclear test in 1996 and then  
declared a moratorium on nuclear testing. It has given no 
indication that it will resume testing. 
</P>
<P>
	Even so, many treaty advocates claim the Senate delay is keeping  
other nations from ratifying the treaty. They say this is 
especially important given last year's nuclear tests by India and 
Pakistan. 
</P>
<P>
	The treaty would set up a worldwide monitoring system.  
</P>
<P>
	``These are not salad days for arms control,'' said Chris  
Madison, a spokesman for Sen. Joseph Biden of Delaware. Biden, the 
senior Democrat on the Foreign Relations Committee, is leading the 
charge for the treaty but has been frustrated by Helms. 
</P>
<P>
	``I will do everything within my power to ensure that the ABM  
treaty is never resurrected or reconstituted,'' Helms said last 
week. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, the administration contends the ABM treaty ``remains  
in force'' with Russia, even though the Soviet Union no longer 
exists, the official said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990602.0113 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 20:44:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> `NewsHour' Plans New Program </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The team behind public television's ``NewsHour  
with Jim Lehrer'' hopes to begin a second national newscast to 
compete with local late-night news shows early next year. 
</P>
<P>
	So far, about a dozen PBS stations have agreed to air the show,  
which is being developed with The New York Times, said Robert 
MacNeil, the former ``NewsHour'' anchor who is working on it for 
MacNeil-Lehrer Productions. 
</P>
<P>
	MacNeil said the second newscast will provide a substantive  
alternative to the ``body bag'' journalism of late-night local news 
programs. 
</P>
<P>
	MacNeil and Lehrer, his former partner, received Quinnipiac  
College's Fred Friendly First Amendment Award on Wednesday for 
their nightly newscast, which celebrates its 25th anniversary next 
year. MacNeil retired from the show in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	Accepting their awards, both men sharply denounced TV networks  
for viewing news as entertainment. 
</P>
<P>
	The late Friendly, the former CBS News president and Columbia  
University professor who helped put MacNeil and Lehrer together as 
a team, would be appalled at many news programs today, Lehrer said. 
</P>
<P>
	With their opinionated reporters, invasions of privacy and  
public leering, many news shows resemble professional wrestling, 
Lehrer said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The American people are on to what's going on in television  
news,'' he said, ``and television news is either going to change or 
become even more irrelevant than it already is.'' 
</P>
<P>
	MacNeil suggested the lust for ratings makes public television  
news even more important than when ``NewsHour'' began in 1975. Even 
PBS is not immune, said MacNeil, who suggested the recent 
controversy about PBS's ``Washington Week in Review'' illustrated 
what happens when ratings become paramount. 
</P>
<P>
	The show's former moderator, Ken Bode, walked away after he said  
new management there wanted ``more attitude'' at the program. 
Management denied the characterization, but it proved an 
embarrassingly public airing of differences. 
</P>
<P>
	``By dumbing itself down, by whoring just for numbers, public  
television will lose not only its numbers but its soul,'' MacNeil 
said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990602.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 15:11:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Rebels Support Ocalan's Peace Calls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	IMRALI ISLAND, Turkey (AP) -- Kurdish guerrillas said they  
support rebel leader Abdullah Ocalan's calls for peace, but warned 
Wednesday they will keep fighting if his conciliatory offer goes 
unanswered. 
</P>
<P>
	The court trying Ocalan for treason asked both sides Wednesday  
to wrap up their cases, a sign that a verdict could come as soon as 
next week. The Kurdish rebel chief could be sentenced to hang. 
</P>
<P>
	In the largely Kurdish southeast, a suspected rebel blew himself  
up near a military garrison Wednesday, causing no other casualties. 
There have been sporadic rebel attacks since the trial began 
Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Emotions ran high at the trial Wednesday, with the widow of a  
slain soldier describing how she watched her husband being led away 
from a rebel roadblock and shot. 
</P>
<P>
	Spectators and lawyers were moved to tears when a sobbing Yildiz  
Namdar shouted: ``You apologize, but will you bring my husband 
back?'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I share your grief,'' Ocalan replied.  
</P>
<P>
	Ocalan pressed his defense, stating that since 1993 his  
Kurdistan Workers Party, or PKK, has wanted to pursue a peaceful 
solution to the rebel fight for autonomy. Earlier, he told rebels 
from his bulletproof, bombproof enclosure in the courtroom to lay 
down their arms and said he was ready to work for peace. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want my message regarding peace and brotherhood to be  
noticed,'' Ocalan told the court. 
</P>
<P>
	The PKK leadership said it fully backed Ocalan's offer.  
</P>
<P>
	``Such a brave initiative is being left unanswered,'' it warned  
in a statement. ``We have fought for 15 years... If necessary we 
can do the same thing again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The statement was carried by the Kurdish news agency DEM, which  
is based in Germany. 
</P>
<P>
	Turkey regards any hint of Kurdish nationalism as a threat to  
the state and has rejected offers to talk with the rebels. Ocalan 
launched his guerrilla war in 1984, and so far the conflict has 
killed 37,000 people, most of them Kurds. 
</P>
<P>
	Turgut Okyay, the head of the three-member panel trying Ocalan,  
asked both sides Wednesday to prepare their final arguments. 
</P>
<P>
	A verdict in the trial could come as early as June 11, said  
Cengiz Erkoyuncu, a lawyer representing the families of fallen 
Turkish soldiers. 
</P>
<P>
	Trials in Turkish courts usually take months if not years  
because sessions are often held only once every month or two. But 
there is strong pressure within Turkey to quickly conclude the 
Ocalan trial, and sessions have been held every day. 
</P>
<P>
	The trial also is moving swiftly because Ocalan has already  
accepted responsibility for many of the PKK's actions, which are 
considered treasonous under Turkish law and punishable by death. 
</P>
<P>
	``There have been many signs that Turkish authorities are keen  
to get the trial over quickly,'' said Neil Hicks of the New 
York-based Lawyers Committee for Human Rights. ``That does call 
into question the presumption of innocence requirement in the 
trial.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, Ocalan's lawyers and his relatives said they would  
not attend Thursday's session because their security had not been 
guaranteed. 
</P>
<P>
	They said they had been attacked both physically and verbally  
and were forced to leave their hotel after the management received 
threats. 
</P>
<P>
	On Wednesday, Ocalan pressed forward with what appears to be a  
strategy of disassociating himself from some of the group's 
bloodiest acts and attacks against civilians. He blamed violence 
against civilians on factions within the PKK that were outside of 
his control. 
</P>
<P>
	Any death sentence must be approved by parliament. Although  
several dozen Turks have been sentenced to death, Turkey has not 
executed anyone since 1984. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990602.0115 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 15:11:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Rebels Support Ocalan's Peace Calls </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	IMRALI ISLAND, Turkey (AP) -- Kurdish guerrillas said they  
