<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Researchers Find Flooding Link </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Scientists say they have found a link between  
weather patterns that can potentially help predict devastating 
floods on the Yangtze River. 
</P>
<P>
	A team of Chinese and American scientists collected radar,  
weather, satellite and other data in 1998 in the hope of better 
predictions. Flooding in southeastern China last year killed more 
than 3,700 people and caused an estimated $30 billion in damage. 
</P>
<P>
	Government planners want better information to take measures to  
reduce losses of human life, livestock, crops and property. 
</P>
<P>
	William Lau, a NASA atmospheric scientist who helped oversee the  
project, said its researchers found that a pair of early May 
cyclones over the Indian Ocean seemed to delay by a week the onset 
late that month of the storm pattern known as the South China Sea 
monsoon. The weaker and later monsoon, in turn, appeared to 
foretell the contrasting heavy rains to the north in the Yangtze 
basin. 
</P>
<P>
	Project scientists said they need to study data over a broader  
area to gain greater certainty and draw more connections. 
</P>
<P>
	``No matter how good you are in terms of understanding, there is  
some randomness in nature,'' Lau said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Scientists for the project, known as the South China Sea Monsoon  
Experiment, spoke at a meeting of the American Geophysical Union, 
which includes many climatologists. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
