<HEADLINE> Latin American Briefs /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LIMA, Peru (AP) -- A Japanese businessman kidnapped and robbed by  
two policemen met his alleged abductors at the police station where 
he was filing a complaint, officials said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Masahito Ake, 40, part of a delegation accompanying Japan's  
Princess Sayako during a visit to Peru, was leaving a Lima 
discotheque Tuesday when he was forced into a patrol car by the 
suspects, police said. 
</P>
<P>
	His captors forced him to withdraw money from ATM machines and  
took him to his hotel, where they gave him 10 minutes to return 
with more cash, the Lima newspaper El Sol reported. 
</P>
<P>
	But Ake called his embassy and later arrived at the police  
station accompanied by top police officials. There, he recognized 
the suspects, who were arrested, police said. 
</P>
<P>
	Former and active service police officers on Peru's notoriously  
corrupt forces are often linked to criminal and kidnapping gangs. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	LA PAZ, Bolivia AP) -- Japan's Princess Sayako was given a warm  
welcome in this Andean city Wednesday and received by President 
Hugo Banzer on the second day of a week-long visit to Bolivia. 
</P>
<P>
	Sayako, the only daughter of Emperor Akihito and Empress  
Michiko, will visit the tropical city of Santa Cruz Thursday to 
mark the 100th anniversary of Japanese emigration to Bolivia. Later 
in the day she will fly to the Colonial city of Sucre where she 
will visit Colonial churches and dinosaur tracks found in the 
outskirts of the city. 
</P>
<P>
	Sayako was also given the keys to the city Wednesday by La Paz  
Mayor Lupe Andrade. Thousands of onlookers wove Japanese flags as 
Sayako passed through this city of one million located at an 
altitude of 3,600 meters. 
</P>
<P>
	Sayako, who is also known by the title Norinomiya, will attend  
exhibitions and ceremonies celebrating Japanese emigration to the 
tropical rain forests near the city of Santa Cruz and also visit 
areas where people of Japanese ancestry have settled. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) -- Despite opposition objections,  
El Salvador's former intelligence chief took office Wednesday as 
the head of the national police in one of Latin America's most 
violent countries. 
</P>
<P>
	Mauricio Sandoval was sworn in to head the 17,000-member force  
by President Francisco Flores, who took office on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Farabundo Marti Front, the political party formed by former  
leftist guerrillas, claims that Sandoval, as head of the State 
Intelligence Agency, spied on politicians -- including some from the 
governing party. 
</P>
<P>
	Gerson Martinez, a legislator from the Front, said Sandoval  
could use the police to carry out intelligence activities, which he 
said would violate the 1992 peace agreement that ended the 
country's 12-year civil war. 
</P>
<P>
	Sandoval also served as government spokesman during the 1989-94  
administration of President Alfredo Cristiani. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
