<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Something Swampy at Shea Stadium </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Shea Stadium was built on landfill, but it  
seemed more like a swamp around home plate Wednesday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Before the first pitch of their 8-7 win over the New York Mets,  
the Cincinnati Reds complained to umpires that the batter's box was 
a quagmire, and umpires made the grounds crew come out and pour a 
drying substance over the area. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know what they're trying to do over there,'' said Mike  
Cameron, who drove in four runs with a two-run triple and a 
go-ahead, two-run single off John Franco with two outs in the 
ninth. ``I guess they figure we got good speed, so they tried to 
slow us down a bit.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cincinnati and New York each had 47 steals coming in, tied for  
fourth in the NL. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was like a beach out there,'' Reds manager Jack McKeon  
said. ``A beach and a swimming pool.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Asked about whether the Mets deliberately soaked the field, Mets  
manager Bobby Valentine shrugged his shoulders and didn't answer. 
</P>
<P>
	McKeon wouldn't speculate whether it was Valentine's decision,  
but was happy it happened. 
</P>
<P>
	``Don't let us go to sleep. Do something to wake us up,'' he  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Reds also complained about the glove of Mets starting  
pitcher Jason Isringhausen, saying there was white on it -- which is 
against baseball's rules. 
</P>
<P>
	Valentine then took a marker and blacked out the white on the  
glove. 
</P>
<P>
	McKeon said Reds coach Don Gullett noticed the glove.  
</P>
<P>
	``I said, `Oh, yeah, we'll get that changed,''' McKeon said.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
