<DOCNO> APW19990602.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 08:40:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Euro Sinks to Record Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) -- As the euro sank to a new low today,  
European Central Bank chief Wim Duisenberg said he remained 
confident that Europe's new single currency remained sound. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm inclined to play down short-term volatility moves in the  
exchange rate,'' he said after the bank's regular biweekly meeting. 
``In the long run, I see more factors pointing at an appreciation 
of the euro than at a depreciation of the euro.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Duisenberg's comments came as the euro fell under $1.035 for the  
first time in European trading. The euro's value was roughly 11 
percent below its Jan. 1 launch level. The drop followed last 
week's decision by European Union finance ministers to condone 
Italy's plan to increase its planned deficit for 1999 to 2.4 
percent from 2 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Key central bankers have called Italy's decision shortsighted,  
complaining it weakens the strict fiscal criteria adopted to ensure 
the euro's stability. 
</P>
<P>
	Duisenberg noted that Italy was not breaking the rules, which  
allow for a 3 percent deficit, but warned against fiscal laxity 
spreading through the European Monetary Union. ``If that were to 
become a trend, then there would be a real reason for concern,'' he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	German Finance Minister Hans Eichel, in a newspaper interview  
published today, denied the decision to give Italy more budgetary 
leeway was any ``weakening of the criteria.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Italy remains committed to cutting its deficit to 1 percent of  
gross domestic product by 2001 and must take extra measures to 
achieve this, Eichel told the Frankfurter Allgemeine Zeitung. 
</P>
<P>
	Duisenberg also said the main economic factor weighing on the  
euro is the diverging economies between the United States and 
Europe, as well as the Kosovo conflict. 
</P>
<P>
	He also noted that the economic outlook for the 11 Euro  
countries signals favorable conditions for a recovery toward the 
end of the year and next year. 
</P>
<P>
	European Central Bank officials have stressed that the euro's  
weakness is no cause for concern, and have ruled out intervening in 
foreign exchange markets to support the single currency, 
emphasizing instead the euro's medium- and long-term potential. 
</P>
<P>
	At its biweekly meeting, bank policy makers left key interest  
rates unchanged, as widely expected. 
</P>
<P>
	Nations participating in the euro are: Austria, Belgium,  
Finland, France, Germany, Ireland, Italy, Luxembourg, the 
Netherlands, Portugal and Spain. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990602.0124 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 06:24:55 </DATE_TIME>
