<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Baffert's Aim is Winning at Belmont </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) -- Trainer Bob Baffert doesn't see the filly  
Silverbulletday's role as that of spoiler when she competes in the 
Belmont Stakes against Charismatic, winner of the first two legs of 
the Triple Crown. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're not going in as a spoiler,'' Baffert said. ``We're going  
in to win. We want a Belmont trophy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Baffert went to the 1997-98 Belmonts with Kentucky  
Derby-Preakness winners Silver Charm and Real Quiet. Silver Charm's 
bid was spoiled by Touch Gold by three-quarters of a length in 
1997. The bid of Real Quiet was repulsed by a nose by Victory 
Gallop. 
</P>
<P>
	Real Quiet is owned by Mike Pegram, owner of Silverbulletday.  
Silver Charm is owned by Bob and Beverly Lewis, owners of 
Charismatic. 
</P>
<P>
	Out to foil Charismatic's bid will be Menifee, the Elliott  
Walden-trained stablemate of Victory Gallop. The two colts were 
runnersup in both the Derby and Preakness. 
</P>
<P>
	D. Wayne Lukas, Charismatic's trainer, said Tuesday he doesn't  
care how many other 3-year-olds test his strapping chestnut, and 
that he welcomes tough opponents. He doesn't want to hear comments 
about the quality of the competition or questions about whether 
Charismatic deserves to be a Triple Crown champion. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just hope everybody who has one ready, runs him,'' Lukas  
said. ``We don't want any second-guessing on Sunday.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A 12-horse field was expected to be entered today, with the  
post-position draw set for 11:30 a.m. 
</P>
<P>
	Other Derby-Preakness starters to try the Belmont are the Nick  
Zito-trained pair of Adonis and Stephen Got Even. Back for another 
shot at Charismatic are Derby starter Lemon Drop Kid and Patience 
Game. Set to join the Triple Crown competition are Best of Luck, 
Pineaff, Prime Directive, Vision and Verse and Teletable. 
</P>
<P>
	Charismatic and Silverbulletday both put in their final Belmont  
workouts Tuesday at Churchill Downs on a track wet from an 
overnight rain. 
</P>
<P>
	Charismatic worked in predawn darkness at about 6 a.m. EDT, and  
went five-eighths of a mile in 1:00 2-5, going the last quarter in 
24 seconds. He galloped out three-quarters in 1:14. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was pleased,'' Lukas said. ``I was happy he was able to  
stretch his legs and open his lungs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Silverbulletday, who will be making her debut against males,  
worked five-eighths of a mile about 2 1/2 hours later. 
</P>
<P>
	Trainer Bob Baffert said the winner of 11 of 12 starts was timed  
in 59 1-5 and galloped out in 1:12. 
</P>
<P>
	``Doesn't she look beautiful, though,'' Baffert said as the  
filly raced down the Churchill Downs stretch. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a fantastic,'' Baffert said. ``It showed me what I was  
looking for.'' Then, he quipped, ``I don't know what I was looking 
for, but it looked good when I saw it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I just hope she runs the way she worked,'' Pegram said.  
</P>
<P>
	The Belmont will be Charismatic's fifth race in 10 weeks. A  
fourth straight victory -- he won the Lexington on April 18 at 
Keeneland -- would make him the 12th Triple Crown winner and the 
first since Affirmed in 1978. 
</P>
<P>
	Silverbulletday will be the 21st filly to start in 131 Belmonts.  
The only two to win were Ruthless in the first Belmont in 1867 and 
Tanya in 1905. Ruthless beat three males over 1 5/8 miles, while Tanya 
beat six rivals, including another filly, at 1 1/4 miles. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
