<DOCNO> APW19990602.0125 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 16:40:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> NCAA Clears DePaul in Hoops Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- NCAA investigators decided that the DePaul men's  
basketball program didn't commit a major recruiting violation last 
year when it signed one of the best freshmen classes in the nation. 
</P>
<P>
	The only infraction investigators cited was an instance when two  
recruits were served pizza in the DePaul locker room after a game, 
said James R. Doyle, the school's vice president for student 
affairs. 
</P>
<P>
	Doyle said Tuesday that the university had received a letter  
from the NCAA that concurred with the school's own finding that 
there were no violations that warranted sanctions. 
</P>
<P>
	``The bottom line is they found nothing except what we  
self-reported,'' Doyle told the Chicago Sun-Times. 
</P>
<P>
	Messages left with Doyle and NCAA spokeswoman Kimberly Dixon  
were not returned Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The investigation was prompted by an allegation that a DePaul  
player had bought a video game for Quentin Richardson -- a recruit 
who went on to become Conference USA's player of the year as a 
freshman -- with money provided by an assistant coach. 
</P>
<P>
	``We found no evidence that would support those allegations,''  
Doyle said of a claim made by Innis Glover, a DePaul player whose 
scholarship was taken away by coach Pat Kennedy before last season. 
</P>
<P>
	DePaul's investigation did confirm that a DePaul player had  
taken a prospective recruit to a strip club, but that the coaching 
staff wasn't involved and no NCAA rules were violated. 
</P>
<P>
	The two players involved with serving the pizza donated the cost  
of the pizza to charity, Doyle said. 
</P>
<P>
	Besides Richardson, fellow Chicago high school standouts Lance  
Williams and Bobby Simmons became freshmen starters for the Demons 
last season. Richardson thought about turning pro but decided last 
month to return to the Chicago school for his sophomore year. 
</P>
<P>
	DePaul (18-13) lost to California in the second round of the  
NIT. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990602.0126 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 22:20:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Influx of Cubans Blamed on INS </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- In an influx some blame on a new U.S. policy, more  
than 200 Cuban refugees came ashore or were picked up off the 
Florida coast in a recent five-day span. 
</P>
<P>
	Immigration Commissioner Doris Meissner ruled last month that  
Cuban refugees are immediately eligible for a work permit. Before 
her order, Cuban refugees were not guaranteed employment. 
</P>
<P>
	One Border Patrol agent said the new policy is the reason for  
the increase in refugees, most of whom paid smugglers $5,000 to 
$7,000 to get here. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's no fear of deportation, there's no fear of being held  
in detention a long time,'' Border Patrol agent Dean Sinclair said 
Wednesday. ``The most they'll be held is a week while they're being 
processed.'' 
</P>
<P>
	However, Carmen Marrero, who works with refugees for the  
Catholic Charities Group in Miami, said recent refugees have not 
mentioned the change in INS policy as a reason for coming to the 
United States. 
</P>
<P>
	``They say they come here because they have no freedom and  
because of the economic problems'' in Cuba, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	INS spokesman Dan Kane said he saw no connection between the  
clarified policy and an increase in immigrants from Cuba. 
</P>
<P>
	The Coast Guard detained 272 Cubans found at sea in May, the  
highest monthly total since 1994. From Friday through Tuesday 
night, 222 came ashore or were picked up at sea. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
