<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 8 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EU Orders Belgian Poultry Destroyed  
</P>
<P>
	BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- The European Union called today for the  
destruction of Belgian chickens, eggs and any byproducts that could 
be laced with cancer-causing dioxin. The Belgian government issued 
a similar order for pigs, fearful that many of them have also been 
infected by the same contaminated animal feed. In Belgium, two 
officials from a major animal feed fat producer were arrested and 
accused of tampering with the fat that goes into animal feed, the 
likely cause how toxic dioxins entered the food chain. 

</P>
<P>
	9 Die in Ark. Plane Crash Landing  
</P>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- Nine people died in the crash landing  
of an American Airlines jet last night, a coroner confirmed today. 
Investigators want to know what the pilot, who died, was told about 
the violent weather before he attempted to land Flight 1420 at the 
Little Rock airport just before midnight. They said, however, that 
it was too early to say whether the rapidly moving storm caused or 
contributed to the crash. Hospitals said they treated 83 people for 
injuries, mostly cuts and burns. Another 51 people were unhurt. Two 
people are unaccounted for. 

</P>
<P>
	ACLU: Drug War Based on Race  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A report by the American Civil Liberties Union  
claims that the war on drugs has significantly increased the number 
of traffic stops based on race throughout the country. ACLU 
Executive Director Ira Glasser said ``skin color has become a 
substitute for evidence.'' Glasser said the Drug Enforcement 
Administration's ``Operation Pipeline'' has trained at least 27,000 
law enforcement officials on how to spot drug couriers on highways 
and has unfairly created a perception that blacks, Hispanics and 
other minorities are more likely to possess drugs. 

</P>
<P>
	Mexico, U.S. Discuss NAFTA Impact  
</P>
<P>
	TIJUANA, Mexico (AP) -- High-level U.S. and Mexican officials are  
meeting here to discuss negative aspects of the North America Free 
Trade Agreement and the business opportunities available for those 
willing to resolve them. NAFTA has been blamed for everything from 
sewage leaks to traffic-clogged roads to housing shortages. Energy 
Secretary Bill Richardson said NAFTA has brought jobs and progress 
to the border, but now there are problems involving ``traffic and 
the environment.'' NAFTA is credited with helping to double 
cross-border trade since 1993. 

</P>
<P>
	Texaco Calls Off Talks With Chevron  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A possible merger between oil giants Texaco and  
Chevron has been called off after Texaco said Chevron's proposal 
was ``unacceptable for several reasons.'' The deal between the 
nation's third and fourth-biggest energy companies would have been 
worth a reported $42 billion. Large oil companies have been rushing 
to unite because of falling oil prices and the need to cut costs. 
Shareholders of Exxon and Mobil, the nation's two biggest energy 
companies, plan to vote later this month on a possible merger. 

</P>
<P>
	'Home Improvement' Goes Out on Top  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The final episode of ``Home Improvement'' was  
easily the week's most-watched TV program, but it wasn't enough to 
help ABC win the weekly ratings battle. ``Home Improvement'' drew 
an estimated 35.5 million viewers, Nielsen Media Research said 
today, making it the fourth-highest rated series finale of the 
1990s behind ``Seinfeld,'' ``Cheers'' and ``The Cosby Show.'' 
Still, NBC scored a narrow victory for the week and won the May 
``sweeps'' period, when ratings are watched closely to set local 
advertising rates. NBC had a 7.8 rating and 14 share. ABC and CBS 
both had 7.5 ratings and 14 shares. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Sheds 25.65 to 10,570.61  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stock prices were mixed today as investors  
prepared themselves for a possible increase in interest rates but 
nonetheless went in search of bargains in the battered technology 
sector. The Dow industrials finished down 25.65 at 10,570.61. 
Decliners on the NYSE led advancers 1,705-1,231. The Nasdaq was up 
20.51 at 2,432.54. 

</P>
<P>
	Rangers 7, Royals 4  
</P>
<P>
	ARLINGTON, Texas (AP) -- The Texas Rangers used a six-run fifth  
inning to beat the Kansas City Royals 7-4 today for their ninth 
straight win. The Rangers' streak is the longest in the majors this 
season and their longest since winning 14 consecutive games in May 
1991. Rafael Palmeiro hit his 15th homer and drove in three runs. 
Kansas City completed a 1-8 road trip with five straight defeats. 

</P>
<P>
	Ewing Out for Playoffs  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The New York Knicks will have to continue their  
surprising playoff run without Patrick Ewing: The 36-year-old 
center will be sidelined for the rest of the postseason because of 
a partially torn Achilles' tendon. The injury was diagnosed this 
morning, just hours after Ewing missed a potential tying shot at 
the buzzer in Game 2 of the Eastern Conference finals against the 
Pacers in Indianapolis. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by VINCENT CINISOMO  

</P>
</TEXT>
