<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> China Communists Facing Discontent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FUCHENG, China (AP) -- A decade after crushing pro-democracy  
protests, China's communist leaders are facing seething discontent. 
</P>
<P>
	But unlike the student-led Tiananmen Square democracy movement  
that was bloodily quelled by the army on June 4, 1989, the biggest 
challenge to communist rule comes now from the unskilled, not the 
educated elite. 
</P>
<P>
	Legions of Chinese farmers struggling under heavy tax burdens  
and hordes of workers fired by failing state industries are feeling 
left behind by free-market reforms that have raised living 
standards for millions of Chinese. 
</P>
<P>
	``The taxes the government wants are too high, so we farmers  
have to protest,'' said Sun Junzheng, who is trying to feed his 
family of four from a sliver of an acre in this dusty patch of 
north China farm country. 
</P>
<P>
	When the tax collectors arrived at the village of King's Passing  
a few months ago, the poor residents turned them away. But the 
collectors came back, this time with police, and seized all the 
sacks of wheat, rice and peanuts they could find. 
</P>
<P>
	The confrontation left the farmers with barely enough grain to  
scrape through to the next harvest -- but the anger to fight again. 
</P>
<P>
	On the rise the past three years, protests by workers and  
farmers have swelled even more this year, according to a Communist 
Party directive to local leaders on handling the protests. 
</P>
<P>
	In the countryside, anger is directed at high taxes and land  
grabs by officials. In the cities, it's shoddy housing, investment 
scams, unpaid pensions and a lack of jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	Driving the grievances are falling incomes for many Chinese and,  
in an echo from the Tiananmen protests, complaints about rapacious 
corruption among local officials. 
</P>
<P>
	``In overcoming these problems, we cannot be optimistic,'' the  
party directive said. 
</P>
<P>
	Heirs to a peasant revolution, China's communist leaders are  
aware of the threat to their rule. They are studying an overhaul of 
the tax system to keep cash-starved local governments from fleecing 
farmers and have begun a nationwide retraining program for 
bureaucrats. 
</P>
<P>
	Headed by Vice President Hu Jintao and Zeng Qinghong, a  
confidant of party leader and President Jiang Zemin, the campaign 
aims to inculcate honesty and make officials more responsive to 
both Beijing's dictates and local complaints. 
</P>
<P>
	In the short term, officials have adopted more direct measures:  
repression or payoffs, anything to ensure peace in the months 
leading up to celebrations of the 50th anniversary of communist 
rule on Oct. 1. 
</P>
<P>
	Neither strategy has prevented confrontations this year.  
</P>
<P>
	Some 5,000 tax-protesting farmers reportedly fought with  
hundreds of riot police in southern Hunan province. One person 
died. 
</P>
<P>
	Bombs have been set off or planted in at least eight cities,  
many of them places where protests have occurred. 
</P>
<P>
	Most disputes have been less dramatic, with locals and officials  
left in a standoff of mutual suspicion. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors in the Sanchen Group futures company swarmed  
government offices in the northeastern city of Panjin and paralyzed 
intersections in March after the company president disappeared with 
$24 million. The protesters charged city politicians had been 
bought off. 
</P>
<P>
	After the Zichuan district government in eastern Shandong  
province closed a mismanaged agricultural fund in April, locals 
demonstrated to demand repayment and accuse officials of skimming 
money to build offices and pay for entertainment. 
</P>
<P>
	At King's Passing, 120 miles south of Beijing, farmers have been  
trying to fend off tax collectors for three years, Sun and fellow 
villagers said. Last year, police seized televisions and bicycles 
until the recalcitrant paid up. This winter, they took grain. 
</P>
<P>
	``Every year is worse than the last,'' said Sun, a farmer all  
his 35 years. ``It'll happen again in July.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sun and his fellow farmers are each obligated to hand over 330  
pounds of grain -- a fifth to a third of a typical farmer's harvest 
-- and pay a 5 percent income tax. 
</P>
<P>
	After paying up, Sun said, he has little money for school fees  
for his two children and for fertilizer and irrigation water for 
his farm plot, much less for clothes and other daily necessities. 
</P>
<P>
	National leaders are trying to keep local governments from  
increasing fees. A recent directive ordered a cap on local charges 
for schooling, marriage certificates and building permits. 
</P>
<P>
	Premier Zhu Rongji also warned provincial officials in March not  
to worsen tensions by resorting to ``crude or dictatorial 
methods.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The message has not been widely received. In Panjin, Zichuan and  
King's Passing, residents seeking redress complain of harassment by 
police and plainclothes agents -- charges the local governments 
deny. 
</P>
<P>
	``The common folk want to stir things up, but they are afraid  
to,'' said an angry Zichuan resident, who spoke anonymously in fear 
of retribution. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
