<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Star Watch: Joan Plowright </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Joan Plowright says it felt good to get out of  
her straitjacket. 
</P>
<P>
	Straitjacket?  
</P>
<P>
	``Yes, a straitjacket -- Lady Olivier,'' she answers, laughing.  
</P>
<P>
	Married for 28 years to Sir Laurence Olivier until his death in  
1989, Plowright is talking about how her film career has flourished 
over the past decade. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just think I hit a lucky streak, starting off with Lawrence  
Kasdan,'' her director in ``I Love You to Death.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kevin Kline had enjoyed her performances in two English films  
and suggested that Kasdan send her the script of the 1990 dark 
comedy. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just loved the opportunity to do something wild -- get out of  
my straitjacket,'' she says. 
</P>
<P>
	Then she took a role in Barry Levinson's ``Avalon'' and, as she  
puts it, ``then it kind of snowballed,'' with such varied films as 
``Enchanted April,'' for which she received an Academy Award 
nomination, and ``Last Action Hero.'' She even played Mrs. Wilson 
in ``Dennis the Menace'' and took a role in ``101 Dalmatians'' -- 
both as a ``treat'' to her grandchildren. 
</P>
<P>
	Now she's co-starring in a cinematic rarity -- a film dominated  
by powerhouse actresses, Oscar winners Judi Dench, Maggie Smith and 
Cher. Lily Tomlin also appears. In Franco Zeffirelli's 
autobiographical ``Tea With Mussolini,'' Plowright, Dench and Smith 
are the ``scorpioni,'' tart-tongued British expatriates who help 
raise a boy born out-of-wedlock in fascist, wartime Italy -- each in 
her own idiosyncratic way. 
</P>
<P>
	``The thought of being all together for the first time made us  
feel, `Gosh, this is an opportunity that is probably never going to 
happen again,''' Plowright said during a recent visit to New York 
from London. 
</P>
<P>
	And she's right.  
</P>
<P>
	It's overstating the obvious to talk about the paucity of roles  
for older women, the 69-year-old Plowright says. ``One has almost 
gotten tired of saying it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It's nothing new, as she points out. ``In the classical theater,  
there are probably 20 male parts to three female.'' 
</P>
<P>
	So she's grateful for parts that extend beyond ``maiden aunts,  
or battered wives, or decoration -- on the arms of a man.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Luck isn't enough, she says; versatility is essential.  
</P>
<P>
	``It is something that we are more trained to do in England. We  
are trained in drama school, and having the permanent companies ... 
you are contracted for two or three years. You have a development 
program. You play Lady Macbeth one night, and a Chekhov girl the 
next night who's dying of unrequited love, then you play a nice, 
saucy maid in a French classic ... and then you're doing `Guys and 
Dolls.''' 
</P>
<P>
	So once you get the opportunity to move into films, she says,  
you can draw upon ``that enormous background, of having created 
different characters in different styles, (written by) different 
authors, both classic, contemporary, and musical.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Because her mother ran a local amateur drama group, Plowright  
was involved in theater at age 3. Although her father, a newspaper 
editor, initially disapproved of her becoming an actress, she soon 
was spending school vacations at summer sessions of university 
drama schools. After high school, she studied at the Laban Art of 
Movement Studio in Manchester then won a two-year scholarship to 
the drama school at the Old Vic Theatre in London. 
</P>
<P>
	By 1956, she joined the English Stage Company, headquartered at  
London's Royal Court Theater, where she gained recognition in 
dramas written by the so-called Angry Young Men. 
</P>
<P>
	She fondly recalls that playwrights and performers alike enjoyed  
the anger they provoked -- cries of ``Rubbish!'' and seats being 
slammed as audience members walked out of the Royal Court. 
</P>
<P>
	And it was the unlikely meeting place for her, her fellow rebels  
and Olivier, considered by many to be the century's greatest actor. 
</P>
<P>
	``Larry appeared to be the epitome of the Establishment, an  
old-fashioned great success of the West End. Of course, he wasn't. 
... He came to the Royal Court to do John Osborne's `The 
Entertainer.' There we were all thinking, `Oh Lord, we're being 
invaded by this Sir','' says Plowright, who played his daughter in 
the stage and screen version. 
</P>
<P>
	But he took off his coat and started rehearsing with a power and  
passion that won them over. 
</P>
<P>
	``My goodness, I mean, he was just one of us! He was an actor.  
That's what he was. A great actor! But he was an ACTOR -- with 
ACTORS!'' 
</P>
<P>
	She and Olivier were more than impressed with each other's  
acting talents -- they were smitten. A year after Olivier divorced 
Vivien Leigh, they were married in Connecticut. Both were appearing 
on Broadway at the time -- he in ``Becket,'' she in ``A Taste of 
Honey,'' for which she won the 1961 best-actress Tony. 
</P>
<P>
	She soon felt the straitjacket.  
</P>
<P>
	She thought she couldn't be herself in public, and feared her  
opinions in interviews would be taken to be Olivier's. ``Which 
people would do in those days,'' she says. ``And that's why I got 
into a straitjacket. 
</P>
<P>
	``I had to be awfully careful of what I said. Because it would  
be somehow assumed, or they could use his name, because it was a 
bigger name than mine -- `Olivier thinks ...' because his wife said 
so.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Finally, she reckoned that she could say to the press and  
public: ``Don't think Larry thinks the same thing. If you want to 
know what he thinks, ask him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She and Olivier had three children, and she concentrated on  
their home life while he took over the National Theater Company -- 
with a lot of help from her there, too. 
</P>
<P>
	``Those choices were made because they were strongly felt and  
they are not regretted,'' she says firmly. 
</P>
<P>
	A major reason their marriage worked for nearly three decades  
was that they could talk to each other about anything. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was also to do with a passion for the job which was shared.  
... Understanding, compassion, and the fact that one person can put 
their career on hold now and again. And I think that is essential. 
I mean quite obviously if I'd gone off all over the place, it 
wouldn't have lasted. He'd have found somebody else,'' she says, 
chuckling ruefully, ``to have the talks with.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When she's not working, she spends most weekends at a country  
home in Sussex with all or part of her family. She dotes on her 
four grandchildren, ages 2 to 11. She has taken them to Disneyland 
and now wants to take them to Venice or Florence -- ``to give them 
alternatives to television and video games.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She finally intends to start an autobiography. Previously, she  
only reached the point of accepting an advance for a book, then 
gave it back. But now she says she wants to concentrate on writing, 
unless an irresistible part comes her way. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
