<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Analysts Not Fazed by Rite Aid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAMP HILL, Pa. (AP) -- A reduction in Rite Aid Corp. earnings for  
the past three years, prompted by a Securities and Exchange 
Commission review of Rite Aid's accounting practices, is no cause 
for alarm over the finances of the nation's third-largest drugstore 
chain, according to market analysts. 
</P>
<P>
	``No big deal,'' said analyst Eric Bosshard of Midwest Research.  
``There were some small issues that they were able to tidy up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``This doesn't reflect badly on the company. It's simply a  
result of an unusual period,'' said Sally H. Wallick, an analyst 
with Legg Mason Wood Walker in Baltimore. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors responded to Rite Aid's restatement of its earnings  
for fiscal 1997, 1998 and 1999 -- made in an SEC filing Tuesday -- by 
pushing shares down more than 8 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Shares of Rite Aid dropped $2.50 to $24.18 3/4 in trading on the  
New York Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the company's new, more conservative accounting methods,  
Rite Aid's income for the fiscal year that ended Feb. 27 was 
reduced by $14.3 million, or 5 cents a share. 
</P>
<P>
	The revised earnings amounted to a reduction of 4 cents a share  
for fiscal 1998, and an increase of 1 cent in net per-share 
earnings for fiscal 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	The revisions primarily affect how the company accounted for  
expenses related to recent acquisitions, store openings and the 
closing of smaller stores and distribution centers. 
</P>
<P>
	The company's stock has plummeted nearly 50 percent this year as  
a result of weaker-than-expected earnings during the fourth quarter 
of fiscal 1999. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
