<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 06:24:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Speedway Sued After Debris Kills Man </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHARLOTTE (AP) -- Lowe's Motor Speedway and the Indy Racing  
League have been sued by the family of a man killed by flying 
debris during a May 1 open-wheel auto race. 
</P>
<P>
	Attorneys representing Dexter Barry Mobley's three children, who  
live in Georgia, filed the lawsuit in Mecklenburg Superior Court, 
seeking unspecified monetary damages from the track owners, the IRL 
and the speedway's president, H.A. ``Humpy'' Wheeler. 
</P>
<P>
	Mobley, 41, of Statesville was one of three spectators at the  
IRL's Visionaire 500 who died after a wheel and other debris flew 
over safety fences and into the grandstand following a crash. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit claims IRL, Wheeler and Speedway Motorsports Inc.  
were negligent in protecting fans. The defendants ``knew or should 
have known'' that allowing the fast open-wheel cars to race at 
Lowe's Motor Speedway -- a track designed for heavier, slower stock 
cars -- was ``inherently dangerous and heightened the risk of a 
serious crash,'' the lawsuit said. 
</P>
<P>
	Robert Beauchamp of Albany, Ga., lead attorney for Mobley's  
estate, told the Atlanta Journal-Constitution on Sunday the 
lawsuit, filed Friday, was the first step toward ``putting the 
whole industry on trial'' for not adequately protecting spectators 
when mixing IRL-style cars with NASCAR-style tracks. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've talked to the attorneys in Michigan, and we've agreed to  
put the whole industry on trial,'' Beauchamp told the Atlanta 
newspaper. ``Between Michigan and the Visionaire 500 (at Lowe's 
Motor Speedway), why didn't they do anything to improve safety? Six 
people shouldn't have to die to change something.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ten months before the May 1 accident, three fans were killed  
during a similar open-wheel auto race at Michigan Speedway in 
Brooklyn, Mich. Both the Lowe's and Michigan speedways are 
banked-oval tracks with turns designed for the stock cars. 
Open-wheel cars generally race on flatter courses, such as the 
Indianapolis Motor Speedway. 
</P>
<P>
	Speedway officials declined to comment on the lawsuit. Lauri  
Wilks, vice president and general counsel for Speedway Motorsports 
Inc., said Wheeler and SMI officials had not yet received copies of 
the lawsuit. 
</P>
<P>
	``As far as we are concerned, we are continuing to work with the  
families, to see to all their needs and help them in whatever way 
we can,'' Wilks said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit claims Wheeler told reporters after the Michigan  
crash that the Charlotte-area track should consider increasing the 
fence height. Since the May 1 accident, Lowe's Motor Speedway has 
raised the fence on parts of the track to 21 feet. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
