<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Judge Skeptical of AOL E-Mails </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A judge expressed skepticism Wednesday that  
e-mails cited by Microsoft about the $10 billion alliance of two of 
its biggest rivals actually indicate they plan to threaten the 
software giant's dominance in the computer industry. 
</P>
<P>
	Internal documents disclosed about America Online Inc.'s  
purchase earlier this year of Netscape Communications Corp. 
appeared to contradict public statements by executives at both 
companies about the impetus for the deal. 
</P>
<P>
	But in a surprise move, U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield  
Jackson stopped Microsoft's attorney in mid-sentence to complain 
that the documents were ``ambiguous or cryptic'' about whether they 
suggested AOL had plans to compete more directly with Microsoft. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft contends that the alliance of AOL and Netscape, with a  
related agreement with Sun Microsystems Inc., demonstrates that the 
company faces healthy competition and is not the monopolist 
described by government lawyers. 
</P>
<P>
	The judge allowed that the e-mails raised doubts about testimony  
Wednesday from a government witness, economist Franklin Fisher, who 
said he doesn't believe AOL will choose to distribute its newly 
acquired Netscape Internet software to its more than 17 million 
subscribers. 
</P>
<P>
	An e-mail in July from Sun employee Woody Mewborn, after a  
meeting with AOL executives, said that AOL's most recent software 
``will be the last Microsoft WindowsInternet Explorer 4.0 
version.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mewborn added that a new version of AOL's software, which won't  
use Microsoft's Internet Explorer browser software, was 18 to 24 
months away, and was aimed at ``breaking (AOL's) deadly embrace 
with Microsoft.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``It does call into question the accuracy of (Fisher's) forecast  
into that question,'' the judge told Microsoft lawyer Michael 
Lacovara, adding: ``The point's been made. You don't have to go any 
further.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Jackson also said the documents weren't a clear indicator  
that AOL plans to compete with Microsoft as directly as the 
software giant maintains. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not sure what your strategy is here,'' Jackson told  
Lacovara. ``A number of these are ambiguous or cryptic.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jackson also complained separately that the AOL-related  
documents, including e-mails and slide presentations, were dated 
last fall or earlier. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of the documents appeared to contradict statements by AOL  
Chairman Steve Case and others, who maintained that AOL was more 
interested in buying Netscape's popular Web site than its popular 
Internet browser software. 
</P>
<P>
	Case told Microsoft lawyers last month that AOL ``did not buy  
Netscape because of the browser business. We bought Netscape in 
some ways despite the browser business.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But a slide presentation from AOL's investment bankers last  
November repeatedly describes the company's upcoming plans for the 
Netscape browser, including a proposal to ``extend browser to be a 
more comprehensive desktop application ... with the goal of 
becoming user's de facto environment.'' 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
