<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stocks End Slightly Higher / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The Tokyo stock market's main index climbed  
slightly today for the third straight day on expectations that the 
government may stimulate Japan's economy with a new set of 
measures. The dollar slipped against the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 120.54 yen at late afternoon, down 0.57 yen  
from late Tuesday in Tokyo and also lower than its late New York 
level of 120.56 yen overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained 9.49 points,  
or 0.06 percent, closing the day at 16,417.99. On Tuesday, the 
index rose 296.85 points, or 1.84 percent, on top of Monday's 
138.97 point gain. 
</P>
<P>
	For much of today's trading, stocks on the Tokyo Stock Exchange  
moved in a tight range in lackluster trading. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders said the Nikkei's upside was limited as investors locked  
in profits in reaction to Tuesday's rally and following a 
2.4-percent plunge in the technology rich U.S. Nasdaq Composite 
Index overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders said, however, that the market's downside was firmly  
supported by hopes that the government will come up with new 
measures to stimulate Japan's economy ahead of the June 19 meeting 
of the Group of Eight major industrialized nations in Germany. 
</P>
<P>
	``Fears of a sharp fall in the Nikkei have abated,'' said  
Hiroichi Nishi, general manager at Nikko Securities. 
</P>
<P>
	Investor sentiment improved somewhat following a report Tuesday  
in a small Japanese investment newspaper saying that Prime Minister 
Keizo Obuchi may decide later this month to suspend Japan's 
unpopular 5-percent national sales tax. Several government 
officials later strongly denied the report. 
</P>
<P>
	Volume on the exchange's first section was estimated at 434  
million shares, compared with Tuesday's turnover of 433 million 
shares. Advancers outnumbered 743 to 429, with 137 issues 
unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section finished up 9.29 points, or 0.71 percent, to 
1,326.77. The TOPIX rose 20.29 points, or 1.56 percent, the 
previous day. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency trading, the dollar mostly followed its overnight  
trend in New York, where it fell as inflation fears pushed down 
U.S. stock and bond markets. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar came under renewed selling pressure after a stronger  
than expected manufacturing report on Tuesday increased speculation 
the U.S. Federal Reserve will raise interest rates to cool the 
economy. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Association of Purchasing Management said its price  
index rose to 52.2 in May from 49.9 in April, leading analysts and 
investors to interpret that as an indication that inflation was 
revving up. 
</P>
<P>
	Although higher interest rates typically are supportive of a  
nation's currency, in this case they are felt to mean that 
businesses will have a harder time getting loans to conduct 
business. 
</P>
<P>
	Helping to cap the dollar's upside was euro selling against the  
Japanese currency, said Ryohei Muramatsu, treasury manager at 
Commerzbank in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro's problems, partly because of slowing economic growth  
in Europe, were exacerbated by a decision by the 11-member European 
Union last week to allow Italy to increase its budget deficit. 
</P>
<P>
	At late afternoon today, the euro was quoted at 124.78 yen, down  
from 126.28 yen late Tuesday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	In Tokyo, the yield on the benchmark No. 213 10-year Japanese  
government bond rose to 1.6750 percent from Tuesday's finish of 
1.6050 percent, driving its price down to 97.64 yen from 98.23 yen 
Tuesday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
