<HEADLINE> Ex-Illinois Player Pleads Guilty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	URBANA, Ill. (AP) -- Former Illinois basketball player Ervin  
Small pleaded guilty to possession with intent to distribute 
cocaine. 
</P>
<P>
	After the plea Tuesday, U.S. District Judge Michael McCuskey  
granted a request by assistant U.S. attorney Kevin Byrnes that 
Small, 31, be held pending sentencing Oct. 22. 
</P>
<P>
	``While he has been thoroughly cooperative and candid, and  
provided sworn statements as to his guilt ... it doesn't rebut the 
fact that he's committed a dangerous crime,'' Byrnes said. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal sentencing guidelines call for Small, of Champaign, to  
face a mandatory prison sentence of 10 years to life, but he could 
possibly get a lesser sentence for cooperating with authorities. 
</P>
<P>
	Small played at Illinois from 1988 through 1990 and was a member  
of the team that went to the NCAA tournament's Final Four in 1989. 
</P>
<P>
	He had worked for almost six years as a correctional officer at  
the Danville Correctional Center before resigning in February. 
Police said there was no indication that Small had tried to 
distribute cocaine at the medium-security prison. 
  	   	
