<HEADLINE> Stock Prices Decline in Japan / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The dollar moved higher against the yen Thursday  
morning amid expectations that U.S. interest rates will rise. Tokyo 
share prices slipped. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 121.71 yen in late morning, up 1.17 yen from  
late Wednesday in Tokyo and also above its late New York level of 
121.33 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average lost 177.32 points,  
or 1.08 percent, to 16,240.67 points at the end of the morning 
session. The index had gained 9.49 points, or 0.06 percent, on 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, the dollar gained ground on buying by  
Japanese institutional investors, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	The greenback's advance was partly based on a belief among  
investors that the U.S. Federal Reserve will raise interest rates 
to cool the economy, traders said. Higher interest rates make a 
currency more attractive to investors. 
</P>
<P>
	Also supporting the dollar was the currency's strength against  
the euro, which was partly a result of ongoing warfare in Kosovo, 
traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro was quoted at 126.14 yen, up from 124.78 yen late  
Wednesday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, prices dropped as investors took to the  
sidelines amid a lack of major market-moving news. 
</P>
<P>
	Kazunori Jinnai, deputy general manager of the equity department  
at Daiwa Securities SB Capital markets, said the market will likely 
remain near current levels until Friday, when key U.S. jobs data 
will be released in Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders said the upcoming employment data would provide clues on  
the future direction of U.S. interest rates and stock prices. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section was down 10.39 points, or 0.78 percent, to 1,316.38. 
The TOPIX finished up 9.29 points, or 0.71 percent, the day before. 
</P>
<P>
	In New York, the Dow Jones industrial average fell 18.37 points  
to close at 10,577.89. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond rose  
to 1.6750 percent from Wednesday's finish of 1.6700 percent, 
driving its price down to 97.64 yen from 97.68 yen. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
