<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Palestinians Protest Negotiations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RAMALLAH, West Bank (AP) -- Turning up the pressure on Israel's  
prime minister-elect, Palestinian leaders said Wednesday they will 
not resume peace talks unless Ehud Barak freezes Jewish settlement 
expansion in the West Bank and Gaza Strip. 
</P>
<P>
	The warning by Palestinian Parliament Speaker Ahmed Qureia came  
on the eve of what the Palestinians have designated as a ``day of 
rage'' -- a series of protest marches Thursday in the West Bank and 
Gaza Strip. 
</P>
<P>
	Referring to the burst of settlement expansion under outgoing  
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu, Qureia said: ``Reason dictates 
that there cannot be a resumption of negotiations without a clear 
message on cessation of settlement activity.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Barak has promised to revitalize the negotiations, but has also  
assured potential hawkish coalition partners he will not cut 
funding to settlements and will complete some of the construction 
authorized by Netanyahu. 
</P>
<P>
	Barak spokesman David Ziso said the prime minister-elect regards  
negotiations with the Palestinians as ``very important'' and plans 
to meet with President Clinton and Mideast leaders soon to move the 
talks forward. 
</P>
<P>
	The Palestinians have expressed concern that Barak will press  
ahead in negotiations with Syria and Lebanon and leave the 
Palestinian issue to last -- robbing the Palestinians of leverage in 
light of Syria's refusal to coordinate positions ahead of a 
resumption of peace talks. 
</P>
<P>
	Palestinian Information Minister Yasser Abed Rabbo said  
Thursday's marches were intended to send a message ``that the 
situation is on the brink of an irreversible explosion.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Abed Rabbo said he expected the protests to be peaceful, unless  
the marchers are provoked by Israeli troops. 
</P>
<P>
	However, Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat's Fatah faction called  
for confrontation with Israel. The protests will ``ignite the land 
under (the settlers') feet until they leave our land forever,'' 
said a Fatah statement distributed in Jerusalem. 
</P>
<P>
	The militant Islamic group Hamas said in a statement it would  
also participate in Thursday's protests. ``We reiterate that 
confrontation is the best way to obtain our rights,'' Hamas said. 
</P>
<P>
	Potential flashpoints are the Palestinian towns of Hebron,  
Bethlehem and Nablus, where Israel retains a military presence. 
</P>
<P>
	A scuffle broke out Wednesday in Hebron between Palestinians and  
Jewish settlers after the settlers attacked Palestinian Boy Scouts 
near a holy site there. 
</P>
<P>
	The Israeli army broke up the fight and briefly detained two  
Palestinians. 
</P>
<P>
	The Palestinians have been especially angered by a burst of  
settlement activity in the final days of the Netanyahu government. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, outgoing Defense Minister Moshe Arens expanded the  
West Bank settlement of Maale Adumim by four square miles, 
connecting it to Jerusalem. 
</P>
<P>
	With the expansion, Maale Adumim will further cut off east  
Jerusalem from its West Bank hinterland and make it more difficult 
for Israel and the Palestinians to reach a creative solution on the 
future of Jerusalem, the most explosive issue in their conflict. 
</P>
<P>
	Barak has not commented on the move and has been vague in  
general about his intentions regarding settlements. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990602.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 13:00:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Wheat Leads Corn, Soybeans Up / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Wheat futures advanced Wednesday on the Chicago  
Board of Trade, leading corn and soybeans higher, amid concern 
about planting delays in the northern Plains. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat reversed early losses tied to pressure from harvesting of  
the winter wheat crop as rain continued to delay planting of spring 
wheat. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. Agriculture Department reported late Tuesday that 85  
percent of the nation's spring wheat had been sown, but the window 
is rapidly closing for getting the remainder of the crop into the 
ground. 
</P>
<P>
	While spring wheat production is much smaller than winter wheat,  
the government reported earlier this year that plantings would be 
down sharply as farmers eye a weak world demand situation. Further 
delays could reduce production even more. 
</P>
<P>
	Corn gained on the strength in wheat despite the government's  
report that most of the crop is in the ground and in good 
condition. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybeans edged higher on the strength of the grains complex.  
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for July delivery rose 1 1/2 cents to $2.53 1/4 a bushel; July  
corn rose 1/2 cent to $2.16 3/4 a bushel; July oats rose 3/4 cent to 
$1.22 1/2 a bushel; July soybeans rose 3/4 cent to $4.58 3/4 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Live cattle and pork futures were mixed on the Chicago  
Mercantile Exchange, while feeder cattle retreated. 
</P>
<P>
	June live cattle rose .02 cent to 64.52 cents a pound; August  
feeder cattle fell .20 cent to 75.67 cents a pound; June lean hogs 
fell .82 cent to 50.65 cents a pound; July pork bellies rose .85 
cent to 53.55 cents a pound. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
