<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 15:20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> World Bank Estimates 200M New Poor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- In its first detailed look at the impact of  
the Asian financial crisis on global poverty, the World Bank 
estimates the world has 200 million ``newly poor'' and recommends 
urgent changes in financial rescue programs to protect people, not 
just economies. 
</P>
<P>
	``Countries that until recently believed they were turning the  
tide in the fight against poverty are witnessing its 
re-emergence,'' said bank President James D. Wolfensohn. ``We must 
now draw on the lessons of recent experience to help us reshape our 
strategies for the future.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Programs to avoid and deal with financial crises in all  
countries should boost social protections, referred to by 
economists as ``safety nets,'' the bank said in its annual update 
on global poverty. They include unemployment insurance, subsidized 
school fees, job creation, food subsidies and other programs aimed 
at keeping more people from slipping into poverty. 
</P>
<P>
	The bank is responding to data showing poverty rising again in  
India, continuing to go up in Africa and sharply worsening across 
Eastern Europe and Central Asia. Indonesia, hit early in the 
crisis, is among the worst hit, with 30 million more people earning 
less than $1 a day than it had before the financial collapse. 
</P>
<P>
	Worldwide, the number of people below that income, considered  
the benchmark for abject poverty, is estimated at 1.5 billion -- up 
200 million from 1993. Final figures for 1999 will not be available 
for several years, but the estimate is based on trends since 1.2 
billion poor were counted in 1987. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the gloomy outlook for global poverty, the report said  
there has been widespread progress in health and education. And an 
exception to the increase in poverty is China, where the number of 
poor is believed to have declined from 280 million in 1990 to 125 
million in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	The bank, in a report last week based on a survey of Asian  
companies, concluded that Asian economies are recovering more 
quickly than expected from the crises, which started in Thailand in 
1997 with plunging currency rates and spread through Asia and 
beyond. 
</P>
<P>
	The new report points to the lasting impact of the crisis on  
some of the world's poorest, diminishing hope of cutting worldwide 
poverty in half by 2020 -- a goal many experts had thought could be 
achieved. 
</P>
<P>
	The bank's underlying purpose always has been to cut poverty,  
but it has been criticized in recent years for lending programs 
that stress long-term development over dealing more directly with 
the suffering. 
</P>
<P>
	``The East Asia crisis and its spillover into other emerging  
markets offers the world an opportunity to devise a new approach to 
crisis, one that rightly puts concern for the poor and the 
vulnerable right at the center of its response,'' said World Bank 
economist Giovanna Prennushi, who authored the global report. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990602.0167 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 16:06:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  First Lady Won't Say Magic Words </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Looking more like a candidate than ever, Hillary  
Rodham Clinton worked the crowd at the City College commencement 
Wednesday and cautioned graduates against those who try to ``lift 
up our public schools and the students they serve by tearing them 
down.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton, who is edging closer to a Senate race, did not  
name names, but a potential Republican rival, New York Mayor 
Rudolph Giuliani has frequently criticized the city's public 
schools. 
</P>
<P>
	As she walked through the crowd of 3,000 graduates, Mrs. Clinton  
shook dozens and dozens of hands thrust out by cheering students, 
warming to the task as she went along. One man put his arms out for 
a hug, and she returned his embrace after a moment's hesitation. 
Later, students chanted, ``Run, Hillary, run!'' 
</P>
<P>
	As she has before, the first lady called for more resources for  
public schools, improved early childhood education and higher 
educational standards. Her every sentence was met with a roar from 
the students, most of them black, Hispanic and from working-class 
backgrounds. And like a candidate on the campaign trail, Mrs. 
Clinton's cadences grew stronger with every cheer. 
</P>
<P>
	Later, at a state Democratic Committee luncheon, Mrs. Clinton  
was asked if she had any news to report about a bid for the Senate 
seat being vacated by retiring Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan. 
</P>
<P>
	``I will have something to say later,'' she said.  
</P>
<P>
	Her spokeswoman, Marsha Berry, said Mrs. Clinton was not about  
to reveal her plans. ``She's still weighing the options,'' said Ms. 
Berry. 
</P>
<P>
	But close associates say they expect Mrs. Clinton to run,  
barring a sudden change of heart. They say that before making an 
announcement, she would notify New York Rep. Nita Lowey, a Democrat 
who was considering the race herself, of her plans. 
</P>
<P>
	A spokesman for the congresswoman said the two women had not  
talked as of Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Gov. George Pataki criticized Mrs. Clinton as a carpetbagger  
because she has never lived in New York. ``I don't think we need 
somebody from Washington or Arkansas moving to New York to 
represent us,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	But in remarks prepared for delivery at an evening event, Rep.  
Carolyn Maloney, D-N.Y., said, ``We New Yorkers don't care about 
where you're from. We New Yorkers care about what you can do to 
continue to build the greatest city, state and country in the 
world.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dressed in a purple graduation gown, Mrs. Clinton received the  
City College President's Medal honoring her work on behalf of 
women's rights, children's issues and education. 
</P>
<P>
	``We can never lift up our public schools and the students they  
serve by tearing them down,'' she told the graduates at the 
school's Harlem campus. ``We can never ensure the future of this 
city or state or our nation by undermining the public education 
system that is at the very foundation of the American dream.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton said education reform would work only ``if we stop  
pointing fingers.'' She cautioned against those who said they want 
to improve education ``to score political points.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Not all students agreed with her every point of view. When Mrs.  
Clinton described visiting ethnic Albanian refugees from Kosovo in 
Macedonia, a dozen graduates held up a large banner reading ``Stop 
war now!'' But their chants were not loud enough to disrupt her. 
</P>
<P>
	At the Democratic luncheon, Mrs. Clinton was given a Yankees  
baseball cap by United Federation of Teachers President Randi 
Weingarten, who was being honored by the state party. Afterward, 
the first lady shook hands with restaurant patrons and waved to a 
small cheering crowd of joggers and mothers with strollers waiting 
near her limousine. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton made no mention of a possible run for the Senate.  
Sen. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., said, ``There's no candidacy yet. But 
Hillary Clinton gets closer and closer and closer and we get more 
and more excited about the prospect.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990602.0168 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 16:06:00 </DATE_TIME>
