<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 5:10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Stocks End Mixed; Dow Down 18.37  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stock prices closed mixed today as investors  
prepared themselves for a possible increase in interest rates but 
nonetheless went in search of bargains in the battered technology 
sector. The Dow Jones industrial average was down 18.37 to close at 
10,577.89. Broader stock indicators were slightly higher after 
paring big losses. The technology-dominated Nasdaq rose 20.36 to 
2,432.39. An afternoon speech by Federal Reserve Chairman Alan 
Greenspan helped calm a jittery market. The influential 
policy-maker kept his remarks at an international business 
conference in Boston tightly focused on trade, and did not address 
interest rates. 

</P>
<P>
	Financial Figures  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Financial figures at the close:  
Dow Industrials:        10577.89  - 18.37
NYSE Issues:         Advances 1336  Declines 1615  Unchgd  588
NYSE Volume:         708,832,090
Most Active NYSE issue:        America Online110       - 3 1/8
S&AMP;P 500:         1294.81  +  .55
AMEX Mkt Value Index:          771.23  -  4.88
Nasdaq Composite Index        2432.39  + 20.36
Gold(final) -    $265.90    troy oz., NY Comex spot month Wed.

</P>
<P>
	Greenspan Warns Vs. Protectionism  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan said  
that the U.S. economy has reaped enormous benefits from lowering 
trade barriers and warned against any switch to protectionism. In a 
Boston speech to an international business conference, Greenspan 
expressed concern at what he sees as a weakening of support for 
free trade in the United States. ``Protecting markets from new 
technologies has never succeeded,'' Greenspan said. He stuck to 
trade matters, and did not discuss interest rates, in his speech. 

</P>
<P>
	Sales of New Homes Up 9.2 Percent  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- New home sales reached their second highest  
level on record in April as buyers, trying to stay ahead of rising 
mortgage rates, rushed to close deals. Sales of new single-family 
homes jumped 9.2 percent in April, following four straight months 
of declines, the Commerce Department said today. The surge pushed 
up sales of new homes to a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 
978,000 units in April. The all-time high was a sales rate of 
985,000 units set last November. 

</P>
<P>
	Philly Exchange Urges Trading Delay  
</P>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- The Philadelphia Stock Exchange's chairman  
today urged Security and Exchange Commission Chairman Arthur Levitt 
to delay plans for extended stock trading hours that would put 
massive demands on exchanges. The National Association of 
Securities Dealers, which governs Nasdaq, approved a plan last week 
to extend trading hours from the current 9:30 a.m. to 4 p.m. 
Eastern time schedule, with a second session that would likely 
start at 5:30 p.m. and end at 9 p.m. or later. The board of the New 
York Stock Exchange is expected to consider a proposal tomorrow to 
extend trading hours starting in July as the traditional markets 
try to respond to rising competition from overseas exchanges and 
alternative computer-based exchanges. 

</P>
<P>
	Teamsters, Haulers Reach Agreement  
</P>
<P>
	ARLINGTON, Va. (AP) -- The Teamsters union and companies that  
haul new cars to dealerships nationwide today announced tentative 
agreement on a four-year contract, averting a strike. Under the 
terms, drivers who choose to retire after 25 years of work would 
get better pension benefits, including health insurance for those 
age 55 and older, union officials said. Although the union did not 
agree to allow part-time drivers, Teamsters Union president James 
Hoffa said negotiators made a concession to scheduling adaptability 
that the companies had sought. 

</P>
<P>
	Barnes &AMP; Noble Halts Ingram Deal  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Barnes &AMP; Noble is walking away from its planned  
purchase of Ingram Book Group because of antitrust objections to 
the $600 million deal that would have united the world's largest 
bookstore chain and the No. 1 book wholesaler. Today's decision, 
which was mutually agreed to by both companies, follows recent 
reports that the Federal Trade Commission might delay or block the 
deal. Independent booksellers cheered the news. Barnes &AMP; Noble 
stock closed up 1 1/4 at 28 5/8. 

</P>
<P>
	Adobe Systems To Cut 250 Jobs  
</P>
<P>
	SAN JOSE, Calif. (AP) -- Some 250 employees will lose their jobs  
at Adobe Systems this year in a restructuring plan designed to 
increase revenue. That number represents 9 percent of Adobe 
employees worldwide. The desktop publishing software company said 
today that 40 percent of the job cuts will come from overseas 
operations, mainly in Edinburgh, Scotland. The savings will be used 
to increase investments in e-business and enhanced marketing 
programs. Adobe posted 1998 earnings of $105 million on revenue of 
$895 million. 

</P>
<P>
	Taiwan Shows Its Computer Skills  
</P>
<P>
	TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) -- Open any personal computer and chances are  
most of its insides were made in Taiwan -- even though the companies 
that produce this technology are relative unknowns. This week, 
however, they're trying to make a name for themselves at the annual 
Computex trade show in Taipei, one of the top three computer shows 
in the world. With output forecast to rise nearly 15 percent to 
more than $45 billion this year, Taiwan is entrenched as the 
world's third largest producer of information technology products, 
behind Japan and the United States. 

</P>
<P>
	Gates, Lawyers Tell Different Tales  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- As the government's antitrust case against  
Microsoft winds toward an end in federal court, it seems at times 
that company chairman Bill Gates and lawyers representing the 
software giant are reading from different scripts. This week, for 
the second time during the high-stakes trial, comments made by 
Gates have undercut the company's legal arguments. In the latest 
instance, while Microsoft argued in court that new devices might 
cut deeply into its business, Gates wrote in Newsweek that personal 
computers -- which depend almost exclusively on the company's 
Windows operating system -- would remain the industry standard for 
years. 

</P>
<P>
	Mazda Sets New Minivan Price  
</P>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Mazda will price its redesigned 2000 MPV -- its  
first new minivan in a decade -- at just under $20,000 for the base 
model. List prices will range from $19,995 for the base DX model to 
$25,550 for the luxury ES model. Those prices make the imported MPV 
competitive with minivans offered by domestic and foreign 
automakers. 

</P>
<P>
	US Airways Gives Some Raises  
</P>
<P>
	ARLINGTON, Va. (AP) -- US Airways plans to give pay raises of  
nearly 14 percent to 9,500 passenger-service workers who have gone 
seven years without a pay increase. US Airways said the raises are 
not only deserved but necessary and long overdue. The airline's 
action came four days after a federal Appeals Court overturned the 
1997 election giving the Communications Workers of America the 
right to represent the workers, but a CWA spokeswoman said the 
union negotiated most of the improvements. 

</P>
<P>
	Economic Numbers  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Economic numbers:  
</P>
<P>
	New home sales: up 9.2 percent  
</P>
<P>
	Tomorrow: Retail sales  
</P>
<P>
	Tomorrow: Jobless claims  
</P>
<P>
	Tomorrow: Factory orders  
</P>
<P>
	Friday: Unemployment  

  	   	
