<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Financial Issues in Elderly Divorce </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- Divorce, fortunately, is not common among older  
people, particularly those who have been married many years. 
</P>
<P>
	Marriages still are more apt to break up around the seven-year  
mark, not on a silver anniversary. But when divorce occurs later in 
life, it not only can be emotionally devastating, it can present 
far more complicated financial issues compared with early breakups, 
says an estate planning expert at the College for Financial 
Planning. 
</P>
<P>
	``One of the first things to do is to review your financial and  
estate planning documents,'' suggests Gregg Parish, an academic 
associate at the college. 
</P>
<P>
	For example, a spouse will likely be named as beneficiary in a  
will, a joint tenant in bank and brokerage accounts, as the agent 
in financial and health care powers of attorney, and as trustee of 
a trust. 
</P>
<P>
	Parish notes that while state divorce laws typically make some  
of these designations null and void upon divorce, ``that doesn't 
take care of the time during which you are getting divorced.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If during the divorce process you die or become incapacitated --  
always a greater risk the older you are -- the surviving spouse will 
retain complete control. ``You probably will want to remove them 
from these positions as soon as possible,'' Parish says. 
</P>
<P>
	A common situation, he says, is when a couple owns a home in  
joint tenancy with rights of survival. Thus, if one spouse dies, 
the other automatically inherits the home. 
</P>
<P>
	Parish says many divorce experts recommend that couples sever  
the joint tenancy, often by converting ownership to tenants in 
common, in which each party is considered to own half of the 
property. 
</P>
<P>
	Parish says this typically can be done simply by executing and  
recording a deed, but state laws vary, so it's important to check 
as soon as possible with an attorney to see what should be done. 
</P>
<P>
	In the case of bank accounts, money markets and some other cash  
equivalents held in joint tenancy, it's probably best if the couple 
divides up the accounts and deposits their half in separate 
accounts, says Parish. 
</P>
<P>
	You also may be able to transfer half of your jointly held  
brokerage accounts and mutual funds into separate accounts, though 
that will depend in part on how the account is titled and what 
restrictions the brokerage house or mutual fund may have on 
transfers. 
</P>
<P>
	However, it's usually best not to sell assets at this stage in  
order to divide the proceeds because the sale will likely trigger 
capital-gains taxes. 
</P>
<P>
	Parish cautions that moving a portion of a bank or brokerage  
account into solely your name ``doesn't mean you've converted it 
from marital property to separate property that you won't have to 
account for in the divorce proceedings.'' It merely prevents one 
spouse from arbitrarily spending more than his or her half of 
jointly held property. 
</P>
<P>
	Another area older people going through divorce should be  
especially cautious about is inheritances or gifts from their own 
parents. You may want to stop or delay distribution of their estate 
to you, says Parish, to reduce the chance that the property would 
become mixed into marital property. Or you might put any gifts or 
inheritances into a separate account or trust. 
</P>
<P>
	``One of the problems here,'' says Parish, ``is that like so  
many of divorce and estate planning laws, it is state law that 
determines what is and is not marital property. The area can be 
murky.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Older divorcing spouses also are more likely than younger  
couples to own interests in a small business, such as a partnership 
or corporation. Typically the partners or owners have an agreement 
stating what rights they have should one of the parties go through 
a divorce. So an early step would be to review the agreement with 
the other owners in order to take proper action. 
</P>
<P>
	The presence of minor children is typically less of an issue for  
older divorcing couples, but not unheard of for someone still in 
their late 50s or even early 60s. 
</P>
<P>
	If children are still around, it becomes particularly important  
that the person providing child support payments take precautions 
to ensure that payments continue in the event of his or her death, 
disability or unemployment. Life insurance or other assets could be 
put into an irrevocable trust from which support payments can be 
made in these circumstances. 
</P>
<P>
	Alimony payments are far less common today because women are  
more likely to be self-supporting than they once were. But among 
today's older couples it's still not uncommon to find a woman who 
may not have employable skills, and who must rely on her former 
spouse for support. 
</P>
<P>
	As in the case of child support payments, steps should be taken  
to ensure continuation of payments if the obligated party dies 
before the recipient. 
</P>
<P>
	Division of property, such as the home, retirement benefits and  
investment accounts, is crucial ``because a lot more in the way of 
assets are typically at stake among older divorcing couples than 
younger ones,'' Parish says. 
</P>
<P>
	The same caution can be said about older people who remarry.  
Because they may have accumulated a lifetime of assets, prenuptial 
agreements often should play a role in order to protect assets for 
themselves or their heirs. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
