<HEADLINE> Briggs-Botha Winner Wants Tyson </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Shannon Briggs grew up in the same Brooklyn  
neighborhood as Mike Tyson and has always wanted to fight the 
former world champion. 
</P>
<P>
	The only person who may stand in the way is Francois Botha.  
</P>
<P>
	Briggs (31-2, 25 KOs) and Botha (39-2, 24 KOs) will meet in a  
heavyweight bout on August 7 in Atlantic City. 
</P>
<P>
	Both are already talking about Tyson.  
</P>
<P>
	``My ultimate goal is to be the heavyweight champion, but I got  
into boxing because I wanted to fight Mike Tyson and now I feel I'm 
within one win of getting that chance,'' Briggs said at a New York 
news conference Wednesday. ``Fighting Tyson is like a title shot.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Botha, who beat Axel Schulz in 1995 for the IBF title and was  
stripped of it later after testing positive for steroids, knows all 
about Tyson. 
</P>
<P>
	He was leading Tyson on all three cards after four rounds in a  
bout this past January before being knocked out in the fifth round. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know I can easily beat Mike and I think I proved it in those  
rounds,'' Botha said. ``I beat myself in that fight, but this time 
I won't lose my concentration and won't get too cocky and 
arrogant.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The fight, Briggs' first appearance with Showtime, will be shown  
on the cable outlet's pay-per-view. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a new beginning for me,'' Briggs said. ``It's going to  
give my fans and some people who don't like me a chance to see me 
again. I haven't been very active with a hand injury, but I'm back 
again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Like Botha, Briggs has also had opportunities in big fights. He  
took advantage in 1997 when he won a decision over George Foreman. 
But Briggs was stopped in the fifth round of a title shot against 
Lennox Lewis in March of 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	``Botha is a guy I can really showcase my skills against,''  
Briggs said. ``I can really shine on this man and make him look 
bad.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
