<DOCNO> APW19990602.0184 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 00:30:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Study: Andro May Grow Breasts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- A new study finds that the dietary supplement  
used by slugger Mark McGwire may promote breast enlargement, heart 
disease and cancer instead of boosting men's strength. 
</P>
<P>
	The study published in today's Journal of the American Medical  
Association compared androstenedione with a dummy pill in 20 men 
ages 19 to 29 during an eight-week weightlifting program. 
</P>
<P>
	Researchers found the supplement had no effect on testosterone  
levels in the blood, and no difference in strength could be found 
between the two groups of men. 
</P>
<P>
	Androstenedione -- pronounced an-droh-STEEN-die-ohn -- is a  
naturally occurring hormone that the body uses in tiny amounts to 
make the male hormone testosterone, which promotes tissue growth. 
Supplements, touted as a testosterone booster and muscle builder, 
contain many times the amount found in the body naturally. 
</P>
<P>
	McGwire, the St. Louis Cardinals baseball player who hit a  
record 70 home runs last year, has said he uses the supplements to 
speed recovery from minor injuries. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would say there's absolutely no reason to think  
androstenedione had anything to do with his slugging,'' said lead 
author Douglas. King, an exercise biochemist at Iowa State 
University. 
</P>
<P>
	All the study subjects were new to weight training and made  
rapid strength gains during the study. 
</P>
<P>
	But the men who took the supplement -- 300 milligrams daily --  
showed significant declines in levels of ``good'' cholesterol, 
which protects against heart disease. 
</P>
<P>
	Androstenedione also raised the men's levels of the female  
hormone estrogen, King said. Elevated levels of estrogen in men are 
known to promote breast enlargement and are also associated with a 
higher risk of pancreatic and possibly other cancers. 
</P>
<P>
	The study did not measure breast size. King said such an effect  
probably would take longer to occur. 
</P>
<P>
	McGwire had no comment on the findings. A furor erupted last  
year when he acknowledged that he used androstenedione following a 
report by The Associated Press. 
</P>
<P>
	Major league baseball spokesman Pat Courtney said the league has  
``some of the leading people in the field, along with the players' 
association, looking at the issue.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``You just can't hurry,'' he said. ``I'm sure they will take  
everything into consideration in their findings. We're waiting to 
hear the results.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The hormonal effect of androstenedione in men is the opposite of  
what has been reported in women. In a paper 37 years ago, 
researchers reported that two women who each took 100 milligrams of 
androstenedione on a single occasion had four- to seven-fold 
increases in their blood levels of testosterone. 
</P>
<P>
	No other medical literature on the topic exists, the researchers  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Experts not involved in the new study praised it but said it  
leaves many questions unanswered. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's the most comprehensive study on androstenedione that's  
ever been done,'' said Dr. Joel Finkelstein, an endocrinologist at 
Massachusetts General Hospital. But ``what we really need are 
higher doses and larger groups of men studied.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Finkelstein and a colleague, Dr. Benjamin Leder, are conducting  
their own study with the support of major league baseball, which is 
looking at whether to ban the supplement. The National Football 
League, the Olympics and the National Collegiate Athletic 
Association already have banned it. 
</P>
<P>
	Both researchers said they are prohibited from discussing their  
study before it is published, under standard medical-journal rules. 
</P>
<P>
	Dr. Charles Yesalis III, a professor of health and human  
development at Pennsylvania State University, said testing the drug 
in athletes might reveal some slight benefit that would not emerge 
from the type of subjects King studied. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
