<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Officer Sues in Tailwind Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- A former Army officer quoted in a story  
that accused U.S. commandoes of using nerve gas to hunt down 
defectors during the Vietnam War sued three media groups Wednesday 
for more than $100 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Robert Van Buskirk, a former Special Forces lieutenant, filed  
suit against CNN, Time and Time Warner Inc. over the story that was 
later retracted. 
</P>
<P>
	Van Buskirk has been ``shunned by many persons with whom he  
previously had social or business relations, and by his former 
comrades in arms, and has suffered mental anguish by being accused 
of war crimes and murder,'' according to the lawsuit filed in 
federal court. 
</P>
<P>
	The lawsuit is based on a joint CNN-Time story telecast on June  
7, 1998, that claimed the military used sarin gas in Laos during 
Operation Tailwind, a mission to find defectors. Two U.S. defectors 
were supposedly killed in the attack, the report said. 
</P>
<P>
	The story was retracted after an internal investigation could  
not substantiate the allegations. Time and CNN, both owned by Time 
Warner, apologized for the story. 
</P>
<P>
	Van Buskirk's attorney, Elihu Berman, of Clearwater, Fla., said  
Van Buskirk's chief argument is that he was cited as the primary 
source for what was inaccurate information. 
</P>
<P>
	His defamation lawsuit seeks $75,000 in compensatory damages and  
$100 million in punitive damages. 
</P>
<P>
	A Time magazine spokeswoman said she could not comment on the  
lawsuit. A Time Warner spokeswoman referred phone calls to CNN; a 
CNN spokesman declined comment. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
