<HEADLINE> Europe: Dollar Mixed; Gold Lower </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- The dollar was mixed against other major  
currencies in European trading Wednesday, and the troubled euro 
slipped to a record low. Gold was lower. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro was quoted at $1.0371, down from $1.0449 Tuesday, as  
analysts painted a bleak picture for the recovery of the currency 
from the steep losses suffered against the dollar over the past few 
months. 
</P>
<P>
	In Frankfurt, Germany, European Central Bank officials met to  
discuss the currency, weakened by a decision to allow Italy to 
increase its budget deficit. 
</P>
<P>
	Other dollar rates compared with late Tuesday: 120.71 Japanese  
yen, down from 120.95; 1.5338 Swiss francs, up from 1.5230; and 
1.4798 Canadian dollars, down from 1.4800 
</P>
<P>
	The British pound was quoted at $1.6103, up from $1.6072.  
</P>
<P>
	In midday trading in New York, the dollar was worth 120.83 yen,  
while the euro was worth $1.0345 and the British pound was worth 
$1.6060. 
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately, though they remain in use. Based on euro 
rates, the dollar is worth: 1.8859 German marks, up from 1.8718; 
6.3249 French francs, up from 6.2777; 2.1249 Dutch guilders, up 
from 2.1090; 1,867.00 Italian lire, up from 1,853.07. 
</P>
<P>
	Gold closed in London at $266.20 bid per troy ounce, down from  
$266.90 on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	In Zurich the bid price was $265.95, down from $267.05.  
</P>
<P>
	Gold rose $1.10 in Hong Kong to close at $267.35.  
</P>
<P>
	Silver closed in London at $4.99 bid per troy ounce, up from  
$4.98. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
