<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Charge Reinstated Against Hubbell </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- A federal appeals court reinstated a criminal  
charge that Webster Hubbell engaged in a scheme to conceal legal 
work he and Hillary Rodham Clinton did on a fraudulent Arkansas 
land deal. 
</P>
<P>
	The three-judge panel unanimously rejected on Tuesday Hubbell's  
argument that one of 15 charges against him should be dismissed as 
too vague. His trial is to begin Aug. 9. 
</P>
<P>
	An 85-paragraph section of the indictment enumerates some 50  
alleged lies by Hubbell over a six-year span to regulators from the 
Resolution Trust Corp. and the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	``It cannot be the case that the more elaborate the scheme or  
the more numerous the acts of concealment, the less able the 
government is to charge a crime,'' said the court decision. The 
judges were Stephen Williams and Laurence Silberman, Republican 
appointees, and David Tatel, a Clinton appointee. 
</P>
<P>
	``Hubbell's ... argument that the indictment fails to give  
sufficient notice because it provides too much detail is, to be 
charitable, unconvincing,'' the court added. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge James Robertson had ruled that the  
allegations against Hubbell were not specific enough. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal regulators say the land development involved, a  
1,050-acre tract south of Little Rock called Castle Grande, was 
riddled with insider dealing and fictitious sales. 
</P>
<P>
	The project was owned by Mrs. Clinton's former Whitewater  
partner, Jim McDougal, and Hubbell's father-in-law, Seth Ward. Mrs. 
Clinton has testified repeatedly that she remembers almost nothing 
of her work on Castle Grande in 1985-86. Her work on the project 
was disclosed when her missing law firm billing records turned up 
in the White House family residence in 1996 under still-unexplained 
circumstances. 
</P>
<P>
	Castle Grande cost McDougal's savings and loan close to $4  
million. The government eventually took over the failing 
institution at a cost to taxpayers of $65 million. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
