<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks End Mixed; Dow Down 18.37 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stock prices closed mixed today as investors  
prepared themselves for a possible increase in interest rates but 
nonetheless went in search of bargains in the battered technology 
sector. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones industrial average was down 18.37 to close at  
10,577.89. The index fell as much as 131.40 points earlier in the 
session before erasing most of the losses in the final hour of 
trading. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators were slightly higher after paring big  
losses. 
</P>
<P>
	The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 rose 0.55 to 1,294.81, and the  
technology-dominated Nasdaq composite index rose 20.36 to 2,432.39. 
</P>
<P>
	Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 6-to-5 margin on the  
New York Stock Exchange, with 1,635 down, 1,358 up and 570 
unchanged. 
</P>
<P>
	NYSE volume totaled 726.14 million shares as of 4 p.m., vs.  
681.99 million in the previous session. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index fell 0.78 to 620.50, and the American  
Stock Exchange composite index fell 4.88 to 771.23. 
</P>
<P>
	The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 0.72 to 436.74.  
</P>
<P>
	An afternoon speech by Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan  
helped calm a jittery market. The influential policy-maker kept his 
remarks at an international business conference in Boston tightly 
focused on trade, and did not address interest rates. 
</P>
<P>
	The market has been rattled for more than two weeks by  
persistent fears that the Fed will soon raise rates to cool off the 
booming economy. 
</P>
<P>
	``The biggest bull market in history has been aided and abetted  
by a friendly Fed,'' said Larry Wachtel, a market analyst at 
Prudential Securities. ``Everyone is afraid of what will happen if 
the Fed turns unfriendly.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While the Dow remained in a narrow trading range throughout  
Greenspan's speech, market watchers still strained to catch any 
hints he might offer about the Fed's future course. Alan Skrainka, 
chief market strategist at Edward Jones of St. Louis, said many 
expect the Fed to raise interest rates when its Open Market 
Committee meets June 29. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Fed doesn't want to shock the system, so Greenspan's  
lieutenants have been warming us up for a while,'' he said. 
``People are selling on the rumor of a rate hike, so they may buy 
when the news hits.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wachtel said the market is likely to remain off-balance at least  
until Friday, when the Labor Department will report May's 
unemployment figures. 
</P>
<P>
	``Given the emotional component of that report, there won't be  
any real direction until then,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bond prices continued their tumble after a robust report on new  
home sales. The price of the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond 
recovered slightly by this afternoon, yielding 5.93 percent, but 
the yield had soared to 5.97 in earlier trading. 
</P>
<P>
	A yield of 6 percent is viewed as a critical point for stocks,  
because at that level, yields make bonds a more attractive 
investment. 
</P>
<P>
	Interest rate worries depressed bank and financial stocks today,  
with J.P. Morgan leading decliners. The financial sector is 
especially vulnerable to higher interest rates because lending 
volume shrinks when it becomes more expensive to borrow. 
</P>
<P>
	Internet companies began the day by tumbling yet again, but  
their weakened prices enticed some buyers. America Online dropped 
sharply in early trading, but turned higher late in the session. 
Yahoo posted a strong gain after Sprint Corp.'s PCS Group agreed to 
offer Yahoo content to users of its wireless phones. 
</P>
<P>
	Online brokerages mirrored their more conventional rivals and  
were mostly lower. 
</P>
<P>
	Bookseller Barnes &AMP; Noble rose slightly after it called off its  
planned acquisition of book distributor Ingram Book Group. The 
company's online wing, barnesandnoble.com, fell. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
