<DOCNO> APW19990602.0193 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 16:00:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Belmont Stakes Notebook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- With dozens of photographers and cameramen  
recording his every move, Triple Crown hopeful Charismatic arrived 
at Belmont Park late Wednesday morning after a delayed trip from 
Kentucky. 
</P>
<P>
	The flight carrying the Kentucky Derby and Preakness winner,  
potential spoilers Prime Directive, Pineaff and the filly 
Silverbulletday, along with several other racehorses, was delayed 
90 minutes in Louisville due to bad weather, but had a smooth trip 
after takeoff. 
</P>
<P>
	``At 6 a.m. as we were getting ready to leave the barn, it got  
black and started lightning and pouring,'' trainer D. Wayne Lukas 
said after the chestnut colt was safely unloaded, bathed and 
settled into his stall at barn 10. ``I was concerned with getting 
to the airport, let alone getting into the air. We waited about an 
hour and a half and then loaded in a light rain. 
</P>
<P>
	``As soon as we took off and got above the storm everything was  
smooth. But the delay didn't bother Charismatic. The lightning was 
crackling, but he loaded well, he wasn't worried. He takes 
everything in stride.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Silverbulletday, looking to become the third filly to win the  
1 1/2-mile Belmont, was transported to the racetrack from the airport 
in a separate horse van, arriving at barn 50 a half-hour after 
Charismatic. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to find out if she fits -- I think she fits,''  
trainer Bob Baffert said. ``The mile and half? We don't know. I 
just hope when they come to the quarter pole, that she's still 
kicking in and by then we'll know what's going to happen.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *TRIPLE SURVIVORS:* Nineteen horses ran in the Kentucky Derby,  
but just four will complete the Triple Crown series in Saturday's 
Belmont Stakes. 
</P>
<P>
	They are: Charismatic, the Derby and Preakness winner; Menifee,  
the Derby and Preakness runner-up; and Adonis and Stephen Got Even, 
both trained by Nick Zito. Stephen Got Even was 14th in the Derby 
and fourth in the Preakness, while Adonis was 17th in the Derby and 
sixth in the Preakness. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *TRIPLE TIME:* For the third straight year, there's a chance for  
a Triple Crown champion. 
</P>
<P>
	Trainer D. Wayne Lukas, whose Charismatic has a shot at becoming  
racing's 12th Triple Crown winner if he can win Saturday's Belmont 
Stakes, says the time is right for racing hero. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the public likes to see it, I think we're in the  
crossroads of racing,'' he said Wednesday during the draw for post 
positions at Belmont Park. ``The tracks are changing ownership, the 
NTRA (National Thoroughbred Racing Association) has done a great 
job marketing, and I think the timing is right to show the American 
public that we're not always on page 14 of the sports section, that 
we can move up a few pages.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *ANTLEY TIPS:* As Chris Antley gears up for his Triple Crown  
shot aboard Charismatic, the jockey with the on-line stock market 
newsletter also has a Triple Crown tip for investors: 
</P>
<P>
	``Yahoo!, MCI and AOL,'' he said, ``that's my Triple Crown.''  
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *BAFFERT LOGIC:* Trainer Bob Baffert said his star filly  
Silverbulletday wasn't really ready to run in the Kentucky Derby 
and an outside post position kept her out of the Preakness. 
</P>
<P>
	The Belmont, though, seems to be the right fit for  
Silverbulletday, who has won 11 of 12 career starts against her own 
sex. 
</P>
<P>
	``Now we feel good about it, this is the time (to run her),''  
Baffert said. ``Winning the Triple Crown is either meant to be or 
not meant to be. I lost the last two. If Charismatic wins, it's a 
great story. If my filly wins, it's a great story, too.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The last Triple Crown winner was Affirmed in 1978; the last  
filly to win the Belmont was Tanya in 1905. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *LONG SHOT:* Teletable, the longest shot in the Belmont at 99-1  
on the morning line, went for a 1 1/2-mile gallop Wednesday morning, a 
routine he will follow until Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Belmont will be his first race since Feb. 15, when he broke  
his maiden at Gulfstream in his fourth career start. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's a good horse and he's doing real well so we decided to  
run him in the Belmont,'' trainer Alfredo Callejas said. 
</P>
<P>
	Callejas has saddled four horses in past runnings of the  
Belmont, the most recent being Mr. Energizer, who was seventh in 
1997. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *GOOD LUCK:* Peter Pan winner Best of Luck is scheduled to have  
his final work for the Belmont Thursday morning, said New 
York-based trainer Allen Jerkens, nicknamed ``the Giant Killer'' 
for his knack at pulling off huge upsets in major races. 
</P>
<P>
	``We think he has a great chance in here,'' Best of Luck's  
jockey, Jean-Luc Samyn, said. ``He ran great in the Peter Pan. But 
he will have to step up to win.'' 
  	   	
</P>
