<DOCNO> APW19990602.0200 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 17:00:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> National Spelling Bee Under Way </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Megan McFall took a deep breath, wished away  
the hiccup attacks that often appear when she's nervous and 
successfully spelled ``c-h-r-y-s-a-n-t-h-e-m-u-m.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``There was no hiccup. That was just a blank,'' Megan, a  
13-year-old home-schooler from West Farmington, Ohio, said of her 
noticeable hesitation Wednesday before starting to spell in the 
72nd annual Scripps Howard National Spelling Bee. Nevertheless, at 
the end of the first of two days of spelling by the 249 
contestants, Megan was still in the running -- with 104 other 
spellers. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of the 9- to 15-year-olds spelled with their hands stuffed  
deep in their pockets. Others gazed at the ceiling for inspiration 
and hoped they wouldn't hear the elimination bell. The bee got off 
to a swift start because of a new policy that gives judges more 
guidance in disqualifying contestants who spell as slow as 
m-o-l-a-s-s-e-s. 
</P>
<P>
	Kristina Rodriguez, a 14-year-old from Brownsville, Texas, was  
one of three spellers who almost succumbed to the policy. On 
Kristina's third word, she asked several times for the definition, 
pronunciation and origins of ``glycolytic,'' which refers to the 
chemical breakdown of glucose. 
</P>
<P>
	After three minutes and seven seconds, twice as long as the 90  
seconds officials generally allowed on the first day, judges 
insisted Kristina spell the word, which she did correctly to stay 
in the contest. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't study this hard to be disqualified,'' she said during  
a break. Under the guidelines, adequate times to spell words are 90 
seconds for easier words from the first day, and two minutes for 
the harder words in the final rounds Thursday, but the judges have 
leeway. 
</P>
<P>
	Suspense also came when judges asked to hear a tape of Kristen  
Davis' spelling of ``pomeridian,'' meaning blossoming after noon. 
The 12-year-old from Stuart, Va., however, spelled it 
``poneridian.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dozens of parents, siblings and sponsors cheered the spellers --  
even when they missed -- in the ballroom of a downtown Washington 
hotel. 
</P>
<P>
	While some weathered tongue-twisters like ``prestidigitator,''  
``meistersinger'' and ``xerostomia,'' others were stumped by the 
likes of ``sousaphone,'' ``rapport'' and ``suffocate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kyle Trujillo, one of two 9-year-olds in the contest and,  
ironically, from Tuba City, Ariz., missed ``sousaphone.'' He 
spelled it ``suziphone.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The other 9-year-old and the youngest contestant, fourth-grader  
Shante Lewis from Plainfield, N.J., also was eliminated in the 
first round. 
</P>
<P>
	Without hesitation, Elise West, 13, of Memphis, Tenn., correctly  
spelled ``tentativeness.'' Sarah Sinnett of Powellsville, N.C., 
kept her cool while acing ``discombobulate.'' And the audience 
applauded and chuckled when Angela Arenivar, 14, of Perryton, 
Texas, pumped her fists and jumped up and down after squeaking out 
the spelling of ``wheedle.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Zachary Holland Baker, 13, of Parsons, Tenn., ended his  
first-time appearance by misspelling his first word -- 
``siphonapterology,'' a branch of entomology concerned with fleas. 
He was tripped up by the previous speller's word, ``psychedelic.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I had the p-s-y thing still in my mind,'' he said. ``I hoped I  
would get past the first round. That's the hardest round. I wanted 
a chance at $10,000.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The contestants, most sponsored by their local newspapers, all  
won regional bees to qualify. The winner Thursday will receive 
$10,000, a choice of encyclopedias and other prizes. 
</P>
<P>
	Scripps Howard announced Wednesday that Jamaica, home of last  
year's champ, will return to the competition next year after being 
banned this year for holding its local qualifying contest too 
early. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm very happy that Jamaica has found a way back into the  
competition,'' said Karin Daley of the Daily Gleaner, the newspaper 
that will sponsor Jamaican contenders for the national bee. 
</P>
<P>
	Scripps Howard, the newspaper group based in Cincinnati,  
coordinates the national finals and produces the word lists and 
study materials. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
