<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Women's Open Golf Notebook  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WEST POINT, Miss. (AP) -- By winning the year's first major and  
ending a nearly three-year stretch without a victory, Dottie Pepper 
moved within single digits of the LPGA Hall of Fame. 
</P>
<P>
	Unlike many halls, the LPGA's is based solely on performance.  
Under requirements revamped this year, 27 points are needed for 
induction. 
</P>
<P>
	``Before this season started, I felt if I could get my number  
down to single digits it would be considered a successful year,'' 
said Pepper, who has 19 points toward the Hall of Fame. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you win the first major, you start thinking a little  
bigger. If the world is a perfect place, we would be sitting here 
Sunday afternoon with only six points to go.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. Women's Open, the season's second major, begins  
Thursday at Old Waverly Golf Club. 
</P>
<P>
	As for the LPGA scoring system, players get one point for each  
career victory, scoring title and player of the year award. A 
victory in one of the LPGA's four majors is worth two points. 
</P>
<P>
	Pepper has 15 victories, including two Dinah Shore titles, in a  
13-year career. Before this year's Dinah Shore, her last victory 
was the LPGA Championship in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	Before the criteria changes, players had to win 40 tournaments,  
35 with one major or 30 with two majors for induction into the 
hall. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *PARK A PRO:* Get ready for another amateur to join the  
professional ranks. 
</P>
<P>
	Grace Park, the U.S. Amateur and NCAA champion, said Wednesday  
that she plans to turn pro after the U.S. Women's Open. She could 
not turn pro before the Open because her exemption is based on her 
winning the Amateur. 
</P>
<P>
	``I feel I'm ready now,'' Park said.  
</P>
<P>
	That doesn't mean the 20-year-old South Korean, who moved to the  
United States when she was 12, is ready to act like a pro. 
</P>
<P>
	While IMG and Cornerstone Sports are the two agencies battling  
to sign Park, family associates say a decision likely will not be 
made until later this summer -- and any endorsements would not be 
sought until after she gets an LPGA Tour card. 
</P>
<P>
	Unlike Tiger Woods on the PGA Tour and Jenny Chuasiriporn, the  
Open runnerup who turned pro last week, Park does not plan to take 
any sponsor's exemptions into LPGA Tour events with hopes of 
getting her card. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, she plans to play the remaining eight events on the  
Futures Tour. She can earn her card by finishing in the top three 
on the Futures money list. If she finishes from fourth to 10th on 
the money list, she would be exempt to the finals of Q-school. 
</P>
<P>
	A two-time All-American at Arizona State, Park has been the  
top-ranked women's amateur and female college player the past two 
years. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *JENNY'S JOURNEY:* After making her professional debut in the  
U.S. Women's Open, Chuasiriporn will use sponsor's exemptions to 
play in three straight LPGA events in July. 
</P>
<P>
	``I took the first ones that came to me early,'' said  
Chuasiriporn, who needs the exemptions to play because she does not 
yet have an LPGA card. 
</P>
<P>
	Chuasiriporn, the 1998 U.S. Open runnerup as an amateur after  
her 40-foot birdie putt forced a 20-hole playoff, finished her 
college career last month as Duke won the national championship. 
</P>
<P>
	Her plans are to play in the Jamie Farr Kroger Classic, the  
Michelob Light Classic and the Big Apple Classic the first three 
weeks of July. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *FUTURE SITE:* Sticking with a recent trend of taking its  
premiere women's event to rural America, the USGA said Wednesday 
that the 2002 Open will be played at Prairie Dunes Golf Club in 
Hutchinson, Kan. 
</P>
<P>
	This year's event is at Old Waverly Golf Club in West Point,  
Miss., after a stop last year in Kohler, Wisc., an hour from Green 
Bay and Milwaukee. 
</P>
<P>
	Next year's Open will be played outside of Chicago, but will  
also be played opposite the British Open. 
</P>
<P>
	In 2001, the rural tour continues at Southern Pines in North  
Carolina. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *OWENS FUND:* The LPGA Foundation has established a fund for  
research and education in the name of DeDe Owens, a former 
president of the LPGA's teaching and club professional division. 
</P>
<P>
	The DeDe Owens LPGA Golf Education and Research Fund will  
support LPGA golf education and research projects with which Owens 
was involved. 
</P>
<P>
	Owens, who died May 16 of a heart attack, played four years on  
the LPGA Tour before joining the teaching and club pro division in 
1974. She was a teaching professional at Cog Hill Golf and Country 
Club in Chicago when she died. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
