<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> British Supermarket Chain To Cut Jobs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Britain's second-largest supermarket chain, J.  
Sainsbury, is cutting 1,100 jobs as part of an overhaul of its 
struggling business. 
</P>
<P>
	A 3 percent decline in last year's operating profit to 714  
million British pounds ($1.1 billion) was ``not acceptable,'' 
Sainsbury said Wednesday. The losses came despite a 5 percent 
increase in sales after the company opened 20 new supermarkets and 
expanded 22 others. 
</P>
<P>
	Chief executive Dino Adriano said the layoffs are part of the  
company's plan to save 160 million pounds ($256 million) over the 
next three years. 
</P>
<P>
	Sainsbury employs 130,000 people in 415 stores. Long identified  
with middle-class British shoppers, its has recently lost market 
share to more innovative rivals like Tesco. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have radically reassessed our current position and  
prospects,'' Adriano said. 
</P>
<P>
	The company said its five-year plan will focus on enlarging its  
stores, shortening the time customers must wait in check-out lines, 
introducing new products and expanding its lower-priced range of 
goods. 
</P>
<P>
	Strong growth at its Homebase chain of do-it-yourself hardware  
centers and the U.S.-based Shaw's supermarket chain helped offset 
weakness in the British food retailing business, Sainsbury said. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
