<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Auto Sales Exceed Expectations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Automakers posted one of their strongest U.S.  
sales months ever in May, exceeding the industry's own expectations 
as demand for new cars and light trucks showed no sign of slowing. 
</P>
<P>
	``A record year is within reach,'' Ford Motor Co. marketing  
chief Bob Rewey said Wednesday as the automakers released their 
sales figures for the month. ``May was a blockbuster sales month 
for Ford and the industry -- stronger than we expected.'' 
</P>
<P>
	May's year-to-year gains were expected to be muted because of  
the comparison to a particularly robust May 1998, when sales were 
boosted by a discount coupon war between General Motors Corp., Ford 
and what was then Chrysler Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	But a burst of sales over the long Memorial Day weekend helped  
most automakers end the month with impressive gains. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's one of the two or three strongest months ever; maybe the  
strongest month that wasn't influenced by changes in the tax law or 
other artificial stuff,'' said analyst David Healy of Burnham 
Securities Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	Ford posted one of the biggest increases -- up 10 percent  
compared with a year ago. It had a surprising 18 percent increase 
in car sales, excluding its Jaguar and Volvo models. Ford's light 
trucks -- pickups, sport utility vehicles, vans and minivans -- were 
up 6 percent for a May record. 
</P>
<P>
	The Chrysler half of DaimlerChrysler AG was up 6 percent for its  
best month ever, led by an 8 percent increase in truck sales. James 
P. Holden, vice president of marketing and sales, said the 
company's economists keep expecting the market to soften, but so 
far there's no evidence of it. 
</P>
<P>
	``The market feels mighty strong, and I don't see that  
changing,'' Holden said. 
</P>
<P>
	GM was the biggest disappointment in May's sales contest. Its  
sales were off 5 percent. Despite its hot-selling full-size 
pickups, overall sales of GM's light trucks declined 2 percent; its 
full-size SUVs took the biggest hit. 
</P>
<P>
	``All year long they've been giving away market share to the  
foreign brands while Ford and DaimlerChrysler have held their 
own,'' Healy said. ``May was just another example of that 
intensified.'' 
</P>
<P>
	European automakers once again had the greatest percentage  
gains. Although European companies sell far fewer vehicles in the 
United States than either the domestic or Asian automakers, they 
have been steadily gaining market share over the past two years, 
mostly at the expense of GM. 
</P>
<P>
	In fact, the Europeans have had double-digit, year-over-year  
percentage gains for the past 21 months. In May, Volkswagen AG 
posted a 56 percent increase for its best May in 20 years; Saab 
Automobile AB, half-owned by GM, more than doubled its sales from a 
year ago; Ford's Volvo Cars unit was up 21 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Asian automakers also did well last month. Honda Motor Co. was  
up 6 percent for its best May, and Nissan Motor Corp. posted a 10 
percent gain 
</P>
<P>
	Ford announced Wednesday it would boost its second-quarter  
production by another 20,000 vehicles to a total of 1.282 million 
vehicles -- up 8 percent from the same quarter of 1998. It was 
Ford's third increase since its second-quarter production schedule 
was announced in March. 
</P>
<P>
	Wednesday's reports came as the industry dodged a potential  
threat to its profits, as the Teamsters union and trucking 
companies that transport new vehicles to dealers reached agreement 
on a new contract and averted a threatened strike. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
