<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 11 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	U.N. Trying to Bring Aid to Kosovo  
</P>
<P>
	UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- The United Nations is trying to arrange  
regular land convoys to deliver food and other aid to help ethnic 
Albanians still in Kosovo, the top U.N. humanitarian coordinator 
said today. Yugoslavia has already indicated it would allow such 
convoys. Time is running out for the estimated 600,000 people still 
living in the province without sufficient food, medicine or water, 
said Sergio Vieira de Mello, the U.N. official. The U.N. agencies 
are trying to determine what must be done to allow for the return 
of 850,000 refugees to the province. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Orders Gov't Energy Cuts  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Aides say President Clinton will issue an  
executive order calling on the government to use less energy and 
cut greenhouse gas emissions by 30 percent. Environmentalists have 
chided the administration for not doing enough to address climate 
change. The federal government is the world's largest user of 
energy, more than $8 billion worth a year. Government agencies will 
be required to increase efforts to cut energy use for lighting, 
heating and cooling to achieve a 35 percent reduction by 2010, 
compared to 1985 levels. 

</P>
<P>
	National Spelling Bee Under Way  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The 72nd annual Scripps Howard National  
Spelling Bee is under way, and the first contestant eliminated was 
``irascible'' over his fate. The 12-year-old boy from Nevada 
misspelled it with a double ``r,'' and was the first casualty of 
the tournament. Still, more than 100 competitors remained, and 
those who survived today's three rounds will return to spell again 
tomorrow. The contestants, most sponsored by their local 
newspapers, all won regional bees to qualify. The winner Thursday 
will receive $10,000, a choice of encyclopedias and other prizes. 

</P>
<P>
	Antigay Slur Carved on Student  
</P>
<P>
	GREENFIELD, Mass. (AP) -- Two prep school students were charged  
with a hate crime today for allegedly carving an antigay slur into 
another student's back because he liked to listen to the British 
rock band Queen. Jonathan Shapiro, 18, and Matthew Rogers, 20, 
allegedly used a pocket knife to cut the word into the back of a 
17-year-old student at the Northfield Mount Hermon School. The 
student has left the school. Shapiro and Rogers face a maximum 
sentence of 25 years in prison if convicted. 

</P>
<P>
	Gates and Wife Donate $5 Bil. More  
</P>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- Microsoft founder Bill Gates and his wife,  
Melinda, have donated $5 billion to one of their philanthropic 
foundations, making it the third largest in the United States. The 
$5 billion gift of Microsoft stock to the William H. Gates 
Foundation gives it an asset base of $10 billion. The Lilly 
Endowment is listed as the largest foundation with assets of more 
than $15 billion, followed by the Ford Foundation at $10.7 billion. 
Gates and his wife are estimated to be worth more than $80 billion. 

</P>
<P>
	Taco Bell Marketing Chief Leaving  
</P>
<P>
	IRVINE, Calif. (AP) -- The advertising executive considered  
largely responsible for Taco Bell's popular Chihuahua commercials 
is leaving the company to take a top marketing job with the Federal 
National Mortgage Association. Vada Hill, 39, has been Taco Bell's 
chief marketing officer since 1997. Sales increased 3 percent in 
1998 after the appearance of the big-eyed pup saying, ``Yo Quiero 
Taco Bell.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Japan Stock Slip; Nikkei Sheds 58.87  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks slipped in early trading Thursday  
as investors took a wait-and-see stance in the absence of fresh 
market-affecting news. The Nikkei fell 58.87 to 16,359.12 in the 
first 30 minutes of trading. On Wall Street, the Dow industrials 
fell 18.37 to 10,577.89. 

</P>
<P>
	Diamondbacks 15, Expos 2  
</P>
<P>
	MONTREAL (AP) -- Matt Williams hit his 16th homer and Steve  
Finley had four extra-base hits and four RBIs to help the Arizona 
Diamondbacks pound the Montreal Expos 15-2 tonight. Arizona tied a 
team record for runs in a game and set a new record for hits with 
20. Finley has driven in 15 runs in his last four games. 

</P>
<P>
	Tigers 4, Red Sox 2  
</P>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Justin Thompson continued his dominance against  
the Boston Red Sox with eight strong innings as the Detroit Tigers 
salvaged the finale of a three-game series with a 4-2 win tonight. 
Thompson improved to 4-1 against Boston in his career. He lost his 
shutout in the ninth when Mike Stanley hit a two-run homer. Todd 
Jones got the final three outs for his ninth save. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by VINCENT CINISOMO  

  	   	
</P>
