<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lawyer Denies Agent Paid Florida LB </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GAINESVILLE, Fla. (AP) -- Sports agent Tank Black denies that he  
gave money to former Florida linebacker Johnny Rutledge, insisting 
police forced the player to lie about accepting payments, the 
agent's lawyer said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Leonard Mungo, the lawyer, said he planned to ask the U.S.  
Attorney's office to investigate the way university police handled 
the case. 
</P>
<P>
	Among other things, Mungo wants to know whether Rutledge and  
former linebacker Jevon Kearse were threatened with perjury if they 
didn't change testimony that exonerated Black of wrongdoing. 
</P>
<P>
	``I talked with two of the Keystone Kops down there and they  
intimated to me that they were not happy with statements those 
players had given under oath'' in April, Mungo said. ``They weren't 
pleased with the statements because those statements completely 
exonerated Tank.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rutledge, a second-round draft pick of the Arizona Cardinals,  
told Florida Today in Tuesday's edition that he had taken $500 per 
month over the span of a year from Black in exchange for an 
agreement to sign with Black's agency after the 1998 season. 
</P>
<P>
	``My friends know the story,'' Rutledge said. ``I've sat down  
and I've told them the story. I just mainly want to come clean with 
the people that have remained closest to me. It's just something I 
did. Now, I'm learning from it. I just hope I can move on and put 
all of this in the past.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Reached by The Associated Press on Wednesday, Rutledge refused  
to confirm the newspaper report. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't want to talk about it at all,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Rutledge told the newspaper that he, Kearse and McGrew admitted  
taking money when questioned by police last month. Mungo said 
McGrew didn't make the admission, but Kearse and Rutledge did. 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, Kearse told Florida Today he hadn't been paid  
illegally. 
</P>
<P>
	Soon after questioning from police, the three dropped Black and  
hired Leigh Steinberg to represent them. A fourth player, Mike 
Peterson, also was interviewed by police. He remains a Black 
client. 
</P>
<P>
	Mungo said the players originally told campus police that they  
had not taken money from Black or anyone associated with his 
company, Professional Management Inc., of Columbia, S.C. The lawyer 
says a few weeks later, Kearse and Rutledge were coerced into 
changing their stories. 
</P>
<P>
	``The first time, they were harassed, no doubt, but they were  
not intimidated,'' Mungo said. ``The second time, they were 
intimidated. And I don't know why you would think you would get a 
trustworthy statement when an ax is hanging over your head.'' 
</P>
<P>
	University police spokeswoman Stacy Badics said the department  
had no additional comment. 
</P>
<P>
	Last month, the NFL Players Association filed a disciplinary  
complaint, accusing Black of illegally recruiting former Florida 
players to his company. 
</P>
<P>
	Mungo said he has asked the U.S. Attorney's office to  
investigate whether the NFLPA convinced university police to start 
the investigation and whether the NFLPA illegally used the police 
findings to further their own investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	Black has until next month to answer the NFLPA's complaint.  
Mungo said he is working on a lawsuit asking federal court to take 
jurisdiction over the complaint. 
</P>
<P>
	If Black is found guilty of violating Florida's agent law, he  
could receive a five-year prison sentence and up to $5,000 in 
fines. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials at the Florida athletic department have said they  
don't anticipate problems with the NCAA or Southeastern Conference 
because they reported the violations immediately upon hearing of 
them. 
</P>
<P>
	An official with the SEC agreed.  
</P>
<P>
	``They've been trying for years to not let something like that  
happen,'' said Jim McCullough, the SEC's compliance officer. ``The 
fact that they turned it over to (university police) immediately 
after they knew about it shows me they're handling it the best they 
can.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
