<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bond Prices Are Mixed / Bonds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Bond prices were mixed Wednesday after plunging  
the day before amid mounting inflation worries. 
</P>
<P>
	The price of the benchmark 30-year Treasury fell 1/32 point, or  
$0.31 per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which moves in the 
opposite direction, settled at 5.94 percent, barely higher from 
Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Short-term issues were unchanged, while intermediate-term issues  
ranged from 1/16 point lower to 1/32 point higher, according to 
Bridge Telerate, a financial information service. 
</P>
<P>
	The market struggled in the morning after the government  
reported that sales of new homes unexpectedly rose during April, 
aggravating worries the economy may be growing at an inflationary 
pace. 
</P>
<P>
	Bonds tumbled on Tuesday after a manufacturing group reported  
that factory activity jumped during May to the highest level since 
October 1997. The report also showed that prices paid for factory 
supplies also rose in the month. Inflation makes fixed-income 
investments like bonds less appealing. 
</P>
<P>
	In other trading Wednesday, yields on three-month Treasury bills  
fell to 4.71 percent from 4.75 percent in Tuesday's auction, while 
the discount fell 0.4 percentage point to 4.59 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Six-month yields fell to 4.93 percent compared with 4.94 percent  
in Tuesday's auction, while the discount fell 0.02 percentage point 
to 4.74 percent. One-year yields fell to 5.03 percent from late 
Tuesday's 5.04 percent, as the discount fell 0.02 percentage point 
to 4.78 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the  
discount is the interest at which they are sold. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between  
banks, fell to 4.69 percent from 5.06 1/4 percent late Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively  
traded municipal bonds fell 1/32 to 121 7/32. The average yield to 
maturity rose held steady at late Tuesday's 5.42 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
