<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                           *Vaclav Benda    	
</P>
<P>
	PRAGUE, Czech Republic (AP) -- Vaclav Benda, a Czech senator,  
mathematician, philosopher and former anti-communist dissident, 
died today, the news agency CTK reported. He was 52. 
</P>
<P>
	Benda had been hospitalized recently with serious pulmonary  
problems. Benda was a member of Klaus's Civic Democratic Party. 
</P>
<P>
	Benda, a signatory of the Charter 77 human rights movement,  
spent four years in communist jails. 
</P>
<P>
	After the 1989 peaceful revolution that toppled the communist  
regime, Benda became a deputy in the then-Czechoslovak parliament 
and later headed a newly established institute investigating crimes 
of the former communist officials. 
</P>
<P>
	He was elected to the upper chamber of the Czech parliament, the  
Senate, in 1996. 

</P>
<P>
                      *Dr. L. Joseph Butterfield    	
</P>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- Dr. L. Joseph Butterfield, known as the father of  
neonatology, died Tuesday at his home in Denver. He was 72. 
</P>
<P>
	Butterfield was known worldwide for his ideas about the care of  
newborn babies. His medical career spanned five decades and 
included a career-long affiliation with The Children's Hospital in 
Denver. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1965, he was recruited as the medical director to create  
Children's Newborn Center, among the first of its kind in the 
nation. His program, ``Newborn Country USA,'' became recognized as 
a national model for regional perinatal care. 

</P>
<P>
                       *Leonard Edward Howard    	
</P>
<P>
	LAWTON, Okla. (AP) -- Leonard Edward ``Ed'' Howard, city/county  
reporter for the Lawton Constitution, died Monday after a brief 
illness. He was 44. 
</P>
<P>
	Howard began his career in January 1979 as a staff writer for  
The Lawton Constitution and Morning Press. He went on to work at 
the Miami (Okla.) News Record, The Georgetown (Texas) Weekly and 
The El Reno Tribune before returning to the Constitution in October 
1993. 

</P>
<P>
                           *Everett LaFon    	
</P>
<P>
	TRENTON, Tenn. (AP) -- Everett LaFon, an uncle of Vice President  
Al Gore, died Tuesday. He was 78. 
</P>
<P>
	LaFon was the brother of the vice president's 86-year-old  
mother, Pauline Gore of Carthage. Jackson was the LaFon family's 
home town when Mrs. Gore was growing up. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Harvey Puckett    	
</P>
<P>
	PARIS, Ky. (AP) -- Harvey Puckett, a jockey at tracks in southern  
Ohio and northern Kentucky, died Sunday of kidney failure. He was 
41. 
</P>
<P>
	Puckett had some of his best years in the mid-1980s at River  
Downs in Cincinnati, where he won six stakes races. He rode Tall 
Grass Walker to the 1984 Spartacus Stakes victory and set a course 
record aboard the horse on June 10, 1984, when they covered 7 1/2 
furlongs on the turf course in 1:29 3/5. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Crocker Snow Sr.    	
</P>
<P>
	IPSWICH, Mass. (AP) -- Crocker Snow Sr., a pioneering aviator and  
director of the Massachusetts Aeronautic Commission, died Tuesday. 
He was 94. 
</P>
<P>
	Snow was a founder of Skyways Aviation, the first commercial  
flight operation at Logan International Airport in Boston. Amelia 
Earhart was one of his students. 
</P>
<P>
	Snow became the state's first aviation director in 1939 shortly  
after the forming of the commission, which he helped create by 
writing the first comprehensive aeronautical law for Massachusetts. 
</P>
<P>
	His only absence from the commission in nearly 40 years was a  
tour of duty during World War II in the Army Air Force. He became a 
colonel by 1944. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1970, President Nixon appointed him chairman of the Aviation  
Advisory Commission, created by Congress to report on the 
long-range needs of commercial and private aviation. 
</P>
<P>
	He made his last solo flight in 1998.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
