<DOCNO> APW19990602.0218 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 19:40:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Truck Carrying Explosives Overturns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SPRINGFIELD, Va. (AP) -- A tractor-trailer carrying 20 tons of  
explosive black powder for fireworks overturned on the Washington 
area's busiest highway interchange Wednesday, backing up traffic 
for 20 miles and forcing rush-hour commuters to sit and stew for 
hours. 
</P>
<P>
	The flatbed truck crashed at about 4 a.m. on an off-ramp in an  
interchange called the ``mixing bowl,'' where 370,000 drivers 
converge daily at the intersections of I-395, I-495 -- the 
Washington Beltway -- and I-95, the major highway from Maine to 
Florida. 
</P>
<P>
	The interchange reopened about 8:30 p.m. after the powder  
containers were doused with water, inspected and loaded onto 
another vehicle for removal, state police said. 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities cleared a 2,000-foot safety zone around the wreck,  
evacuating 200 people from 50 homes and sending many to a high 
school. 
</P>
<P>
	``They didn't even want us to get out of our pajamas,'' said  
Emmanuel Edim, 45, of Springfield. 
</P>
<P>
	None of the black powder spilled out of its cargo container,  
which had been sitting on the flatbed trailer. Hazardous-waste 
workers treated it gingerly to prevent an explosion. 
</P>
<P>
	The driver, Juanita Kirk, 41, and her boyfriend were not  
injured. Ms. Kirk was charged with reckless driving. 
</P>
<P>
	The cause of the crash was under investigation.  
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Kirk told police she heard a popping sound just before the  
rig overturned. 
</P>
<P>
	Accidents are common in the mixing bowl, one of the busiest  
interchanges on the East Coast. Construction has begun on an 
eight-year, $350 million improvement project. 
</P>
<P>
	The ramp where the accident occurred has had numerous truck  
crashes over the years, said Lucy Caldwell, Virginia State Police 
spokeswoman. Loads shift when the ramp is taken at high speed, 
causing trucks to roll over, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	After the wreck, local roads were clogged for miles as commuters  
fled the highways. Angry drivers honked their horns and ran red 
lights while talking on cell phones. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everywhere I turned, it was a traffic jam,'' said Jenny Pena,  
20, of Springfield, after spending four hours in her car. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990602.0219 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 10:00:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ben Fine Looks Almost Any Part </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- You might swear you've seen him before. An  
ailing patient in a hospital? A kindly grandfather sure to offer a 
Hershey bar? Or that upper middle-class New Yorker? 
</P>
<P>
	Ben Fine has been all of these, sort of. For almost three  
decades, Fine has been a model for magazine ads -- even if he isn't 
ailing, doesn't really like chocolate and never lived in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	``They might want a disheveled old man. They might want a  
successful CEO,'' he says. ``There's a picture for everyone.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fine darts around his apartment, tossing aside papers, digging  
through drawers, searching for some particular shots he posed for 
years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	It's not just his All-American looks, though one friend  
describes him as ``one of those guys who looks like everyone's 
grandfather.'' His energy and versatility have landed him in about 
75 ads placed in major publications across the country. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can't sit around and just watch television all day,'' Fine  
says. ``Once people hit their 50s and 60s they often lose their 
ambition, and they're fearful and afraid of dying. But as you get 
older, life is not over.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As a child Fine loved to dance, but his mother steered him away  
from the arts. He ultimately became a wholesaler of costume 
jewelry. 
</P>
<P>
	But when he hit 50, he decided to chase his childhood dream. He  
concentrated on acting, then modeling. 
</P>
<P>
	He moved from home in the suburbs to downtown, where he shares  
bachelor quarters with his cats, Boo-Boo and Little One. Even 
triple-bypass surgery didn't stop him. 
</P>
<P>
	His acting career took him to regional theater with small roles  
in shows such as ``The Fantastiks'' and ``Fiddler on the Roof.'' He 
was a TV extra on soaps such as ``All My Children'' and ``One Life 
to Live.'' Recently, he had a bit part as a doctor taking a pulse 
in ``Law &AMP; Order.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But modeling delights him, whether he's portraying someone down  
on his luck or a successful CEO. Then there's Fine as ship captain, 
gardener with a wrenched back, orchestra conductor, waiter in a 
European cafe. 
</P>
<P>
	When the phone rings. Fine jumps. ``I don't know whether I'll be  
doctor, a patient or someone's grandfather,'' he says, before 
answering. ``I'll have to ask my agent what clothes to bring.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His wardrobe includes 150 neckties, 20 suits and 60 shirts --  
plus a couple of detachable mustaches. Unlike high-profile models 
who display the clothes that designers provide, print models pull 
from their personal wardrobes for everyday looks. 
</P>
<P>
	Why does this work for Fine? He credits his innate ability to  
act. ``See, look at that face of anguish,'' he says, recreating 
that gardener with a strained back. ``To be a good print model you 
have to know how to act. 
</P>
<P>
	``Here in this ad, I'm smoking, and I don't smoke. It took four  
hours to get that shot. I thought I was going to die.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As a carpenter: ``I can't even saw a piece of wood.''  
</P>
<P>
	As the pope: ``And I'm so Jewish.''  
</P>
<P>
	He also is full of optimism, something you can't sell in an ad.  
</P>
<P>
	``You can't get into a fit of depression,'' he says.  
``Depression is the worst thing you can have. It makes you get sick 
and it ages you. ... If the phone doesn't ring, you can't let it 
bother you.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``What I tell people is that all they need is courage,'' he  
says. ``... Anyone can do it. All you need is an 8x10 glossy and a 
good attitude.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fine's knack for self-promotion helps, too. He is still  
shuffling papers, in pursuit of his favorite photos. Finally: 
``Found it!'' 
</P>
<P>
	One is a full-page magazine ad for a shipping company. Fine is  
posing as Mikhail Gorbachev, a slice of pizza in one hand and a 
flag with the company logo in the other. 
</P>
<P>
	``See, they painted his birthmark on my forehead,'' he says,  
pointing to the ``strawberry'' that was so distinctive on the 
former Soviet leader. ``I got a real kick out of it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Another is a 1995 cover of New York magazine. As a dapper New  
Yorker, this lifetime Philadelphian stretches his 6-foot frame into 
an upper-middle-class citizen, perhaps in his 60s. 
</P>
<P>
	Fine was 75 at the time, but he confides that even today  
``people can never guess my age.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Go ahead, guess, he urges, for the third time, just one hour  
after disclosing: 79. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990602.0220 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 13:50:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jury Deadlocks in University Suit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- A federal court jury deadlocked Wednesday  
on accusations by the University of California that Genentech Corp. 
violated a university patent to develop the company's lucrative 
human growth hormone. 
</P>
<P>
	Jurors voted 8-1 in the university's favor, but were unable to  
resolve the impasse during six days of deliberations, two jurors 
told reporters. 
</P>
<P>
	The jury resolved another issue in the university's favor,  
rejecting Genentech's claim the 1982 patent was invalid. That 
verdict will be binding in a retrial of the infringement issue, 
said U.S. District Judge Charles Legge. 
</P>
<P>
	The university accused Genentech, a leading biotechnology firm,  
of using stolen DNA covered by a UC patent to develop the 
top-selling hormone Protropin. 
</P>
<P>
	Genentech denied that genetic material taken from a UC San  
Francisco lab in 1978 was used to develop the treatment. 
</P>
<P>
	The suit sought $400 million in damages, which could have been  
tripled for willful patent infringement. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990602.0221 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 20:46:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  LSU Women Botch NCAA Track Bid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOISE, Idaho (AP) -- For the want of a baton, the chance of LSU  
regaining the women's NCAA outdoor track and field championship 
went tumbling Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The first exchange between Joyce Bates and Chenelle Marshall in  
the 400-meter relay semifinals went awry and so did the Tigers' 
hope of taking back the title from Texas. The Longhorns, who ended 
LSU's 11-year reign last year, had no difficulty with their 
handoffs and won their heat in 43.20 seconds, a record for Boise 
State's Bronco Stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	In breaking LSU's 1994 record of 43.26, Texas, the defending  
champion in the relay, led the way into Friday's final. 
</P>
<P>
	While the relay turned out to be the pivotal event of the  
competition, four finals also were contested. 
</P>
<P>
	Stanford, which went 1-2-3 in the men's 10,000 last year,  
repeated again, with Nathan Nutter winning at 29:11.96, followed by 
Jason Balkman at 29:12.91 and Brent Hauser at 29:14.07. 
</P>
<P>
	Pittsburgh's Trecia Smith, the 1997 long jump champion and 1998  
triple jump winner, earned her second outdoor long jump title, 
leaping 21 feet, 8 1/4 inches. Freshman Gabor Mate from Hungary became 
Auburn's first men's throwing champion since 1951, winning the 
discus at 202-1, and SMU sophomore Florence Ezeh took the women's 
hammer throw at 207-2. 
</P>
<P>
	Tennessee's Tom Pappas, the collegiate record-holder in the  
decathlon, led after the first five events with 4,265 points -- 78 
ahead of runner-up Attila Zsivoczky of Kansas State. Pappas 
finished first in the shot put at 50-5 1/2 and in the high jump at 
7-0 1/4. 
</P>
<P>
	The final five events -- the 110 hurdles, discus, pole vault,  
javelin and 1,500 meters -- will be contested Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Both Marshall and Bates were puzzled as to how they misconnected  
on the handoff. 
</P>
<P>
	``I felt it (the baton),'' said the disheartened and tearful  
Marshall, running the second leg for the first time this year. ``It 
just brushed my hand. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am very disappointed. It's my only event. We've just got to  
put this behind us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Said Bates, ``I have no idea why it happened. I just couldn't  
believe it. I didn't think we would come out here and drop it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stanford's unprecedented sweep of the first three places in the  
10,000 for the second straight year capped a tactical race. 
</P>
<P>
	Arizona's Abdi Abdirahman set most of the pace for the first  
9,800 meters, with the Stanford trio hanging in close pursuit. 
Then, with about 200 meters left, the three Cardinal runners surged 
to the front, and Nutter, third last year, outkicked his teammates. 
</P>
<P>
	Balkman, the newcomer in the group, also outran Hauser to the  
tape. Hauser had finished second last year to his brother Brad. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was just hanging off the pace ...'' Nutter said. ``That was  
the plan.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Smith, winning her seventh NCAA title indoors and outdoors, will  
try to repeat as triple jump champion Friday and will compete in 
the heptathlon Friday and Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's my last year, so I'm trying to do everything I can before  
I go out,'' the senior said. 
</P>
<P>
	The 6-foot-6 Mate missed his season's best by only six inches in  
winning for the seventh time in eight meets. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm the happiest man in the world,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Ezeh couldn't stay around long enough to get her medal because  
she had to quickly return to Dallas for a final exam in 
organizational behavior on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm crying because I want to stay and support my teammates and  
say, `Go Mustangs!''' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Her teammates supported her loudly during the competition Bronco  
Stadium at Boise State, and she was anxious to return the favor. 
</P>
<P>
	``The team support, I loved it,'' said Ezeh, the 1997 French  
junior champion and national record-holder. 
</P>
<P>
	Ezeh nearly gave up the hammer throw last year after a  
discouraging 14th place in the European Championships. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I went home, I started to think, `What am I going to  
do?''' she said. ``Everyone was waiting for me. I thought about the 
hammer throw and I thought about life. 
</P>
<P>
	``I decided I wanted to be good. I had gone down ... touched the  
bottom. Now, I would go up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While the 400 relay semifinals proved disastrous for LSU's  
women, they also were dreadful for defending men's champion TCU. 
The Horned Frogs finished fifth in their heat and failed to qualify 
for Friday's final. 
</P>
<P>
	Florida freshman John Capel, the fastest American this year in  
the men's 200 at 19.99 in winning the Southeastern Conference 
title, won his preliminary heat at 20.71 in advancing to Friday's 
semifinals. Auburn's Coby Miller, the runner-up to Capel in the SEC 
championships, had the fastest prelim time, 20.39. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990602.0222 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 20:46:59 </DATE_TIME>
