<HEADLINE> Injured Indy Crew Member Gets Award </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Some people get flowers in the hospital.  
Steve Fried probably is the only one with an Indianapolis 500 
rookie of the year trophy at his bedside. 
</P>
<P>
	Fried, the chief mechanic for rookie driver Robby McGehee, was  
critically injured in a freak pit accident during Sunday's race. 
His condition has been upgraded to serious, although it may take 
another few days to determine the extent of his injuries, a team 
spokesman said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``A bunch of us were up there yesterday, and Robby presented him  
with the rookie of the year award,'' said Greg Hoover, spokesman 
for Energizer Motorsports. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's conscious and alert. He has the ventilator tube in, so he  
can't talk, but he communicates by spelling out words on his right 
leg with his index finger, as if he were writing them on his leg.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It's difficult for him to use a pen or pencil and paper because  
of his horizontal position in the bed at Methodist Hospital, Hoover 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Fried was working in McGehee's pit early in the race when he was  
struck from behind by Jimmy Kite's car, which had been hit by 
another car whose brakes had failed. Fried landed on his face and 
injured his head and chest. 
</P>
<P>
	McGehee wound up fifth, the best finish among four rookie  
starters, and at the Victory Celebration Monday night he dedicated 
his award to his injured crew chief. 
</P>
<P>
	``Having stood there and seen the whole thing, I've got to tell  
you, I was just amazed how alert he is and responsive,'' Hoover 
said. ``He knows everybody around him, knows what's going on. ... 
His wife, Jennifer, is with him at the hospital. His mother, 
Natalie, flew in from California. 
</P>
<P>
	``But he's doing good. He was kind of giving the doctors a  
little grief yesterday. That's Steve, good old Steve. So we're all 
pretty heartened by that,'' the team spokesman said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The doctors said that because he had an internal brain injury,  
it's sort of a 3- to 5-day evaluation period. They just kind of 
want to see how that comes along, but everything we've heard is 
positive.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
