<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bristol-Microsoft Trial Set To Open </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRIDGEPORT, Conn. (AP) -- Bristol Technology Inc. likes to  
describe its lawsuit against Microsoft Corp. as a battle of David 
versus Goliath. 
</P>
<P>
	But as a trial opens Thursday in Bristol's antitrust lawsuit  
against Microsoft, both companies will be using the David v. 
Goliath image for all it's worth. 
</P>
<P>
	Bristol is a small Danbury-based software maker with just 70  
employees and $8.7 million in revenues. Microsoft, the maker of 
Windows, has 26,000 employees and $14.48 billion in revenues. 
</P>
<P>
	At the trial, Bristol will claim Microsoft is using its market  
muscle to improperly withhold a software code Bristol needs to 
survive. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft, however, will claim that Bristol is playing on its  
status as an underdog to try to win a large financial judgment 
against Microsoft. 
</P>
<P>
	The two companies once worked together amicably. Bristol makes a  
product called Wind/U, which allows programs written specifically 
for Windows to be converted to run on computers with different 
operating systems such as Unix. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1994, Microsoft signed a licensing agreement with Bristol for  
Windows NT 3.0, but that agreement expired in 1997. Bristol filed 
suit after the two companies could not reach a new agreement. 
</P>
<P>
	Microsoft claims Bristol's lawsuit was meant to force Microsoft  
to agree to more favorable licensing terms. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've been very reasonable and fair,'' said Microsoft  
spokesman Tom Pilla. 
</P>
<P>
	``Before, during and after they sued us, we offered the same  
reasonable terms that would have allowed us to avoid litigation,'' 
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	At the trial, Microsoft plans to introduce a ``strategic  
communications game plan'' developed by a New York public relations 
firm for Bristol. The plan, developed about a month before Bristol 
filed its lawsuit against Microsoft, recommended that Bristol 
position itself as ``David ... a reluctant, yet courageous 
plaintiff defending its small, successful and growing 
entrepreneurial company and Goliath as a predatory, deep-pocketed, 
unethical behemoth.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bristol Chief Executive Keith Blackwell, who founded the company  
in the basement of his home in 1991, does not deny that Bristol 
developed elaborate plans to fight Microsoft. But he says it is 
Microsoft that refused to negotiate reasonable terms for the new 
contract. 
</P>
<P>
	He said he believes Microsoft hastily signed a similar licensing  
deal with Mainsoft, one of its competitors, a week after Bristol 
filed its lawsuit, merely so it could use the agreement to defend 
itself against the antitrust claims. 
</P>
<P>
	The trial, to be heard by a 10-member jury in U.S. District  
Court in Bridgeport, is expected to last about six weeks. As one of 
its first bits of testimony, Bristol plans to play parts of a 
videotaped deposition by Microsoft Chairman Bill Gates. 
</P>
<P>
	The trial had been scheduled to start Wednesday, but was  
postponed a day after Judge Janet Hall met with lawyers from both 
companies for several hours Tuesday and said there were procedural 
issues that still needed to be resolved. 
</P>
<P>
	The Bristol case begins this week as testimony resumes in a  
larger antitrust case brought by the U.S. Justice Department and 19 
states. In that case, the government contends that Microsoft 
illegally wielded the monopoly power from its dominant Windows 
product to expand into new markets, such as Internet software, and 
thus crush competitors. 
</P>
<P>
	Caldera Inc., a small Orem company, also is suing Microsoft for  
alleged antitrust law violations. A jury trial is scheduled for 
January. 




  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
