<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 14:00:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 5 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	9 Die in Ark. Plane Crash Landing  
</P>
<P>
	LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- A coroner has confirmed that nine  
people were killed when an American Airlines jetliner skidded off a 
runway while landing during a storm last night. The deaths are the 
first on a major U.S. airline in nearly 1 1/2 years. The dead were not 
immediately identified, except for Flight 1420's pilot, Capt. 
Richard Buschmann, the airline's chief pilot in Chicago. The jet 
was headed to Arkansas from Dallas and crashed amid rough weather 
at the Little Rock airport just before midnight. More than 80 
others on board were treated for injuries at hospitals. There were 
also about 50 others who didn't require treatment. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S. Seeks Normal Trade With China  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton plans to extend normal trade  
relations with China for another year, White House officials said 
today, despite opposition from Congress. The annual recommendation 
for ``most-favored nation'' status comes at a time when allegations 
that China stole sensitive nuclear secrets from U.S. research 
facilities and NATO's mistaken bombing of the Chinese Embassy in 
Belgrade have strained U.S. relations with Beijing. But aides say 
Clinton is convinced that continued engagement with China is key to 
improving relations. 

</P>
<P>
	U.S. To Review Kosovo Options  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton will meet with U.S. military  
leaders tomorrow to assess the conflict in Yugoslavia, including 
the possibility of using ground troops to battle Serb forces. 
Defense Secretary William Cohen said there are currently no plans 
to use troops as anything other than peacekeepers, but the leaders 
will discuss a range of issues including whether ground force is an 
option. Clinton, meanwhile, said that the United States would 
contribute 7,000 of the approximately 50,000 troops that would form 
a peacekeeping force for Kosovo once the Serbs agree to NATO's 
demands for an end to the fighting. 

</P>
<P>
	Killing Halts Paris Transportation  
</P>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- A strike by transport workers angry about the  
killing of a co-worker paralyzed public transportation in Paris and 
its suburbs today. The deadly attack against Eric Douet was only 
the latest in a rising number of assaults against French transport 
workers. Douet was beaten to death by a peddler he had confronted. 
The government responded to the rising violence by deploying police 
on trains and buses, but the transport union said the measures 
weren't enough. Meanwhile, thousands of French commuters walked 
through the muggy weather to work. 

</P>
<P>
	World Bank Estimates 200M New Poor  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The World Bank in its annual update on global  
poverty estimates there are millions of ``newly poor'' people, and 
recommends urgent changes in financial rescue programs. The bank 
said programs, including unemployment insurance and subsidized 
school fees, are needed to avoid and deal with financial crises. 
The bank responded to data showing poverty rising again in India, 
continuing to go up in Africa and sharply worsening across Eastern 
Europe and Central Asia. The bank said the number of people 
classified as living in abject poverty rose 200 million in 1993 to 
1.5 billion. 

</P>
<P>
	Truck Carrying Explosives Overturns  
</P>
<P>
	SPRINGFIELD, Va. (AP) -- A tractor-trailer loaded with 20 tons of  
explosive firework powder overturned at a major highway interchange 
early today, prompting the evacuation of dozens of homes and 
clogging rush-hour traffic in the Washington area. The flatbed 
truck ran off a ramp at the interchange of I-495, I-395 and I-95, 
the major north-south highway linking New York and Florida. The 
explosive powder, the type used to make fireworks, was inside a 
cargo container atop a flatbed trailer. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Sheds 25.65 to 10,570.61  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks closed down today as investors prepared  
for a possible increase in interest rates when the Federal Reserve 
meets later this month. The Dow industrials finished down 25.65 at 
10,570.61. Decliners on the NYSE lead advancers 1,705-1,231. The 
Nasdaq was up 20.51 at 2,432.54. 

</P>
<P>
	Ewing Out for Playoffs  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- New York Knicks center Patrick Ewing will miss  
the rest of the playoffs because of a partially torn Achilles' 
tendon. Ewing underwent tests this morning that confirmed the 
injury, just hours after he missed a potential tying shot at the 
buzzer in Game 2 of the Eastern Conference finals against the 
Pacers in Indianapolis. The 36-year-old center will be in a cast 
for six weeks. The 14-year veteran has been slowed all season by 
his sore Achilles, and also has struggled with sore knees. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by VINCENT CINISOMO  

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
