<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Transplants Cure Cases of Blindness </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	People blinded by fire, chemical burns or illness could have  
enough of their sight restored to do daily chores -- maybe even 
drive -- through innovative transplant surgery that uses special 
tissue-making cells, researchers reported today. 
</P>
<P>
	The procedure, pioneered a decade ago and refined since then,  
would not help people who were born blind or lost their sight 
because of nerve or retina damage. It is only for patients who are 
legally blind but can still sense light. 
</P>
<P>
	Japanese researchers restored sight to half of the eyes on which  
they performed surgery, though some needed as many as four 
operations. Their work, the first long-term study of the procedure, 
was reported in today's New England Journal of Medicine. 
</P>
<P>
	The 39 patients had become legally blind in one or both eyes,  
meaning they could, at best, count fingers held up in front of 
them. 
</P>
<P>
	``The best patient recovered from a finger count to almost  
20/20'' and was able to drive again, said Dr. Kazuo Tsubota, 
chairman of ophthalmology at Tokyo Dental College, where students 
also study medicine. 
</P>
<P>
	The patients' blindness was caused by heat or chemical burns,  
blistering from a severe reaction to medication or an eye-attacking 
immune disorder that afflicts the elderly. Tens of thousands of 
Americans are legally blind for these reasons. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's so many people out there that don't know they can be  
helped,'' said Dr. Edward Holland, director of the Cornea Service 
in the Department of Ophthalmology at the University of Minnesota. 
</P>
<P>
	After a Harvard researcher 10 years ago successfully  
transplanted the special cells from a patient's healthy eye to a 
damaged one, scientists tried the same procedure using eye tissue 
from cadavers, refining the approach as they gained experience. 
</P>
<P>
	From 1992 through 1996, the Japanese doctors did 70 transplant  
operations on 43 eyes in 39 patients. Surgeons removed the damaged 
eye surface, then sewed on tissue from an eye bank, a new cornea, 
if necessary, and tissue called the limbus that rings the cornea. 
</P>
<P>
	The limbus contains stem cells, ``factories'' that produce  
various types of cells -- in this case, the epithelial cells that 
cover the eyeball. Normally the body replaces epithelial cells 
every few months as they slough off like skin. 
</P>
<P>
	Because illness or injury had killed the stem cells of these  
patients, when their epithelium wore away, scar tissue formed over 
the cornea, destroying vision. Thus a cornea transplant would have 
failed within a few months. 
</P>
<P>
	With this procedure, the patients get a new epithelium factory.  
</P>
<P>
	After an average of 39 months, the transplanted tissue was still  
generating epithelium in 51 percent of the patients. Their vision 
improved, on average, from only being able to distinguish motion or 
count fingers to being able to read the top letter on an eye chart, 
without eyeglasses, from about 3 feet away. 
</P>
<P>
	``Even though the success rate at first glance doesn't seem that  
high, you're comparing it with zero,'' Holland said. 
</P>
<P>
	Holland, who co-wrote an editorial accompanying the study, has  
done about 60 such operations with a similar success rate. He said 
the study shows how two key improvements are increasing doctors' 
success: transplanting more limbus tissue so patients get more stem 
cells and giving patients immune-suppressing drugs to prevent 
transplant rejection. 
</P>
<P>
	Tsubota's team is working on other refinements. Those include  
determining the optimal dosage and duration for the 
immune-suppressing medications; making special eye drops from the 
patient's own tears to provide key proteins and combat the dry eyes 
common with such injuries; and putting the donor stem cells in 
nutrients so they multiply and yield more stem cells for 
transplant. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
