<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  SMU's Ezeh Wins NCAA Hammer Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOISE, Idaho (AP) -- SMU sophomore Florence Ezeh became the first  
winner in the NCAA Outdoor Track and Field Championships on 
Wednesday, and couldn't stay around long enough to get her medal. 
</P>
<P>
	After winning the women's hammer throw at 207 feet, 2 inches,  
Ezeh had to quickly return to Dallas for a final exam in 
organizational behavior on Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm crying because I want to stay and support my teammates and  
say, `Go Mustangs!''' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Her teammates supported her loudly during the competition at  
rain-soaked Bronco Stadium at Boise State, and she was anxious to 
return the favor. 
</P>
<P>
	``The team support, I loved it,'' said Ezeh, the 1997 French  
junior champion and national record-holder. 
</P>
<P>
	One of Ezeh's biggest concerns Wednesday was getting to the  
track on time. In last year's NCAA Championships at Buffalo, N.Y., 
she arrived late after her coach got lost and took 90 minutes for a 
drive that should have been much shorter. 
</P>
<P>
	That unnerved Ezeh and her best throw was only 186-6, just 15th  
place. 
</P>
<P>
	``I lost all my power,'' she said. ``I was too tense.''  
</P>
<P>
	This time, the ride took only about 10 minutes and Ezeh was  
``confident and focused.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Michelle Fournier of South Carolina finished second at 206-5 and  
Renetta Seiler of Kansas State was third at 203-4. 
</P>
<P>
	``I never threw in a ring with two inches of rain in it,''  
Seiler said. 
</P>
<P>
	Ezeh nearly gave up the hammer throw last year after a  
discouraging 14th place in the European Championships. 
</P>
<P>
	``When I went home, I started to think, `What am I going to  
do?''' she said. ``Everyone was waiting for me. I thought about the 
hammer throw and I thought about life. 
</P>
<P>
	``I decided I wanted to be good. I had gone down ... touched the  
bottom. Now, I would go up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ezeh, coached by former world-class hammer thrower Walter  
Ciofani, reached her peak Wednesday. It was her ninth victory in 11 
meets this season. 
</P>
<P>
	The hammer was one of four finals on the opening day's program.  
The others were the women's long jump and the men's discus and 
10,000 meters. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
