<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Northwest Rapped on Storm Handling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ROMULUS, Mich. (AP) -- A federal report released Wednesday  
criticized Northwest Airlines for being poorly prepared for a 
January blizzard that stranded thousands of passengers on runways 
at Detroit Metropolitan Airport. 
</P>
<P>
	The report from the U.S. Department of Transportation found that  
Northwest did not violate any federal regulations during the storm, 
which dumped nearly 2 feet of snow at the airport. But it said 
conditions at the aircraft, including overflowing bathrooms and a 
lack of food and water, were ``severe enough to have jeopardized 
passengers' well-being.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Northwest challenged the implication that the airline does not  
care about its customers, and said changes have been made to 
prevent future tie-ups. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nobody doubts the passengers caught in that snowstorm were in  
a horrible, uncomfortable, inconvenient position,'' said Northwest 
spokesman Jon Austin. ``But our goal throughout the whole event was 
to ensure their safety.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Federal officials investigated the snowstorm at the request of  
U.S. Rep. John Dingell of Michigan, the ranking Democrat on the 
House Commerce Committee. He used the report to push for his 
``passenger bill of rights'' legislation and more competition among 
airlines. 
</P>
<P>
	An airplane passenger ``has less rights than anyone in our  
society except someone on death row,'' Dingell said at a news 
conference at the airport Wednesday. ``We cannot continue to exist 
in a situation where we have so little competition here that the 
rights of passengers are ignored.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Austin said that competition already exists in Detroit, however.  
Despite Northwest's marketing prowess and dominance of the region, 
more than 40 percent of passengers at Detroit area airports choose 
to fly on other carriers, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	During the storm on Jan. 2-3, Northwest planes stacked up on the  
tarmac, unable to take off or pull into a gate. Some passengers 
were stuck for up to eight hours in planes; some have since filed 
lawsuits. 
</P>
<P>
	The report said Northwest officials in Minneapolis continued to  
send planes to Detroit as the blizzard began, even after other 
airlines had canceled all flights. Detroit is Northwest's 
second-largest hub, with about 500 flights a day -- about 80 percent 
of the airport's traffic. 
</P>
<P>
	The report also criticized Northwest for not having a snow  
emergency plan for Detroit, and said Detroit workers did not tell 
Minneapolis planners how severe the storm was. 
</P>
<P>
	At a congressional hearing in March, Northwest executives said  
weather conditions were unprecedented. Wind chill reached 30 below 
zero on the first day of the storm, and snow fell as fast as two 
inches per hour. 
</P>
<P>
	Richard Hirst, Northwest's senior vice president of corporate  
affairs, said at the March hearing that passengers were forced to 
wait on airplanes for gates to open because it was unsafe to bring 
them down the metal airline steps used by mechanics. The steps were 
frozen and slippery, he said, and passengers without proper winter 
clothing could have suffered from frostbite within minutes. 
</P>
<P>
	But the federal report said Northwest did not consider some  
other options, such as borrowing the right kind of stairs from 
other airlines. Austin said all available options were considered. 
</P>
<P>
	In February, Northwest apologized for the delays and announced  
changes in how it handles snow emergencies. Northwest will send 
employees to Detroit when bad weather is likely, and improve 
employee communications. The company said weather-related costs 
totaled about $20 million in the first three months of 1999. 
</P>
<P>
	However, the report cites some Northwest officials as saying  
that changes made since the storm would not necessarily prevent ``a 
recurrence of lengthy passenger strandings.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Other federal lawmakers have introduced bills similar to  
Dingell's that would require airlines to provide their customers 
more information about delays, bumping and pricing. Northwest is 
against any such bill, Austin said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We think it's a bad idea when government proposes to insert  
itself between a customer and a business,'' he said. ``Customers 
speak eloquently about what they need from business.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
