<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Rallies Swamp Indonesia's Capital </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) -- More than 100,000 people paraded  
through Jakarta on Wednesday, snarling traffic with political 
rallies in the final days of Indonesia's unexpectedly peaceful 
election campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	Waves of supporters from different parties danced through a  
downtown pond, loudly prayed in Arabic and listened to a singer 
perform through a makeshift sound system as the two-week campaign 
entered the homestretch before Monday's national election. 
</P>
<P>
	The vote is expected to be the freest in decades. President  
Suharto, who ruled the country for 32 years, left office last year 
after violent pro-democracy protests. 
</P>
<P>
	Campaigning will go on for two more days, followed by a two-day  
cooling-off period before the vote for 48 political parties. 
Hundreds of foreign electoral monitors are to watch over the poll, 
including a group of 100 led by former U.S. President Jimmy Carter. 
</P>
<P>
	The rallies Wednesday took on the feel of a peaceful street  
carnival, complete with food vendors. Troops and police looked on. 
</P>
<P>
	Traffic ground to a halt in the capital's center as masses of  
people, some wearing the Justice Party's white Islamic headdresses 
and others the Star and Moon party's green T-shirts, took part in 
the daily convoys down the main boulevard, closing all but one of 
the eight lanes through the heart of the city. 
</P>
<P>
	Dozens of people jumped into a pond surrounding a statue in a  
major traffic circle. Others prayed loudly in Arabic to the beat of 
a drummer. Several climbed the 125-foot statue to hang their 
parties' flags. One man fell and was pulled from the shallow water 
unconscious. 
</P>
<P>
	After the crowd dispersed, Republic Party supporters in orange  
and National Mandate Party backers in blue took its place. 
</P>
<P>
	The congestion cleared after dark before the Indonesian People's  
Party, one of 10 parties authorized to have rallies Thursday, began 
its last campaign appearance at 11 p.m. 
</P>
<P>
	Supporters of Megawati Sukarnoputri's Indonesian Democratic  
Party for Struggle added to the growing crowd after midnight, 
waving their signature bright red flags with a black bull's head. 
</P>
<P>
	Buses parked in a circle around the pool as workers set up  
portable lights and a sound system that a singer used to keep 
hundreds of people entertained. The crowd dispersed at 1 a.m. 
</P>
<P>
	In a Cabinet meeting Wednesday, Information Minister Yunus  
Yosfiah said the government plans to go ahead with voting in Aceh 
province despite attacks by separatist rebels that now are being 
classified as a rebellion. 
</P>
<P>
	He quoted military commander Gen. Wiranto as telling a Cabinet  
meeting that 59 people, including 45 civilians, have been killed in 
the last month by the rebels. Another 96 civilians and 15 
security-force members were injured. 
</P>
<P>
	The Parliament that is elected Monday will choose a president in  
November. Megawati, 52, the daughter of Indonesia's founding 
president, Sukarno, is considered the frontrunner. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990602.0248 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 14:20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Duval, Woods Return to Golf World  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) -- David Duval and Tiger Woods are together  
again, playing in the same tournament for the first time since the 
Masters almost two months ago. 
</P>
<P>
	They are ranked Nos. 1 and 2 in the world and among the 105  
players in this week's Memorial Tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	``They can't do it every week,'' defending champion Fred Couples  
said Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Lately, they haven't done it at all. Duval has taken the last  
three weeks off since missing the cut in New Orleans, while Woods 
skipped the Colonial and Kemper the past two weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet both believe the time away hasn't taken the edge off their  
games. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am coming off some time off,'' said Duval, who has already  
won four times this year and won almost $3 million on the PGA 
grind. ``But in the same sense, I expect to play well or I wouldn't 
have come.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Duval spent his time fishing and doing ``nothing exciting.'' He  
said he practiced for maybe six days, less than he expected to work 
on his game. 
</P>
<P>
	``I intended to, but I didn't do a whole lot,'' he said with a  
grin. 
</P>
<P>
	Woods, third on the money list and with a win at the Buick  
Invitational on Valentine's Day, tied for seventh at the Byron 
Nelson his last time out. He feels he's ready for a breakthrough 
win at Muirfield Village Golf Club. 
</P>
<P>
	``The golf course has suited my game even though the scores  
don't reflect it,'' Woods said. ``I do like this golf course. It's 
just a matter of time before I get it going.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Woods tied for 51st and 67th in his two previous Memorial  
starts. 
</P>
<P>
	``The golf course is always in great shape,'' he said.  
``Unfortunately, I haven't been able to put the scores together 
here. I don't know why. It's just one of those weeks where it just 
doesn't happen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Three of the last four years, Duval has been near the lead at  
the turn on Sunday. He's finished second twice and third once. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked if he looked forward to a potential showdown with Woods,  
he said, ``Oh, absolutely. I look forward to it being with anybody, 
as long as I'm a part of it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Seven of the top 10 on the PGA money list are on hand, as are 14  
of the top 20 players in the world rankings. Ernie Els, Justin 
Leonard, Greg Norman, Mark O'Meara and Spanish phenom Sergio 
Garcia, among others, all hope to use the Memorial as a springboard 
to the U.S. Open at Pinehurst in two weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	``Good players have won here because this is an extraordinary  
field,'' Couples said. ``In a 156-man field, you get everyone that 
plays. Here it's 105 players, a lot of foreigners and other great 
players and it's a very strong field.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tournament founder Jack Nicklaus will test his hip replacement  
in his former hometown on a course he designed. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would be just delighted if I can play four days,'' he said.  
``And I would be even more delighted if I were a contender. But, 
you know, I don't expect that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Couples feels the same way. Since getting married in the last  
year, he has spent less time practicing and more time going to the 
zoo, soccer and softball games with his wife's two children. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a good shot that I'll play well, but there's a great  
shot that I won't,'' he said. ``And that's not very good odds.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
