<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Automakers, Aluminum Industry Ally </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- General Motors Corp., Ford Motor Co.,  
DaimlerChrysler AG and major aluminum makers plan to jointly 
research and develop ways to reduce the weight of tomorrow's cars 
and trucks. 
</P>
<P>
	The automakers and aluminum companies announced formation of the  
Auto Aluminum Alliance today. The move stems from the car 
companies' cooperative research consortium, known as the U.S. 
Council for Automotive Research. 
</P>
<P>
	Through the council, GM, Ford and DaimlerChrysler have been  
working toward a goal of reducing the weight of today's typical 
midsize sedan by 40 percent. New uses of lightweight metals are 
seen as a key to reaching that goal, which in turn will help 
increase fuel mileage and lower emissions. 
</P>
<P>
	Automakers and their suppliers also are studying plastics and  
composites, as well as thinner, lighter-weight steel products. 
Their effort to reduce vehicle weight comes as U.S. consumers 
increasingly favor larger trucks and sport utility vehicles and 
government regulators pursue tougher pollution standards. 
</P>
<P>
	``Through the alliance, the aluminum industry will come together  
and work more collaboratively with the auto industry to help them 
meet their future materials and customer needs,'' said Rick Milner, 
president of Alcoa Automotive. 
</P>
<P>
	The aluminum makers involved in the project are Alcoa Inc.,  
Alcan Aluminum Corp., Kaiser Aluminum and Chemical Corp., Reynolds 
Metals Co., Aluminum Precision Products, ARCO Aluminum Inc., Hydro 
Raufoss Automotive, Nichols Aluminum, VAW of America Inc., and 
Wabash Alloys. 
</P>
<P>
	Though the use of aluminum in the average vehicle has doubled  
since 1991, wider use in high-volume vehicles has been held back by 
costs and the need for different manufacturing and repair 
techniques. Aluminum costs three to five times more than automotive 
steel, pound for pound. The alliance will look at how aluminum's 
costs can be reduced and those areas where its use makes the most 
sense. 
</P>
<P>
	The group also will study ways to cost-effectively recover used  
aluminum from scrapped vehicles, develop standardized test methods 
for sheet aluminum and performance data for use by designers, and 
work to distribute information on repair of aluminum body parts. 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990602.0253 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 13:50:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Orange County Wants Tobacco Money </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SANTA ANA, Calif. (AP) -- Orange County could pay off about $600  
million in debt stemming from its 1994 bankruptcy by using money 
from the national tobacco industry settlement, the county's chief 
financial officer said. 
</P>
<P>
	Under a complex plan that involves purchasing bonds, the county  
would also use some of the money for jails, Chief Financial Officer 
Gary Burton told the Board of Supervisors Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Burton's plan would establish a nonprofit organization that  
would issue bonds based on the settlement revenue. The county would 
then use proceeds from the bonds sale, along with other savings, to 
pay off debts incurred when it emerged from bankruptcy in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	The county will have immediate access to a much larger pool of  
money by selling bonds than if it simply accepted the settlement 
payments, which are estimated at $30 million to $38 million a year 
over 25 years. The nonprofit organization is necessary so the 
county can keep the new bond debt off its balance sheets, Burton 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Paying off bankruptcy debt ahead of schedule allows the county  
to avoid hefty interest payments, county officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We got out of bankruptcy essentially on a credit card, and  
that's why one of (the) priorities is (eliminating) the debt,'' 
said county Chief Executive Officer Jan Mittermeier. 
</P>
<P>
	The county has $1.3 billion in outstanding debt related to the  
bankruptcy. The debt not paid through tobacco settlement funds 
would be paid off using other restricted funds, such as gas taxes, 
flood control funds and redevelopment money. 
</P>
<P>
	The plan also allows for about $150 million for other county  
departments such as jails or juvenile detention facilities. 
</P>
<P>
	Meantime, the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals on Friday ruled  
the county will have to show that Standard &AMP; Poor Inc., which gave 
the county's bonds top ratings before the crash, acted with 
``actual malice.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Orange County has settled its lawsuits with other firms. S&AMP;P is  
the major remaining holdout of firms sued by the county. 
</P>
<P>
	The county claims the high ratings contributed to a borrowing  
binge that forced its bankruptcy. S&AMP;P, which publishes a variety of 
financial analyses, has argued that its services for Orange County 
were covered by First Amendment guarantees of freedom of speech and 
press, and that it couldn't be liable. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
