<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Feds Probe Texas AG on Tobacco Fees </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AUSTIN, Texas (AP) -- Federal prosecutors have subpoenaed records  
from the Texas attorney general's office on a private lawyer's 
claim to millions of dollars in fees for the state's tobacco 
settlement. 
</P>
<P>
	The subpoena is the first confirmation that federal officials  
are investigating efforts by former Attorney General Dan Morales to 
have attorney Marc D. Murr, his former law partner, paid for his 
role in Texas' $17.3 billion settlement with the tobacco industry. 
</P>
<P>
	The subpoena was issued May 20 and obtained today by The  
Associated Press. 
</P>
<P>
	Murr has now waived all claims to fees in the case, his lawyer  
said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Morales led Texas' effort to sue eight tobacco companies and  
three trade groups in 1996 seeking reimbursement for public funds 
spent on Texans' smoking-related illnesses. The case was settled 
before trial. 
</P>
<P>
	Five private attorneys who helped represent the state were  
awarded $3.3 billion in fees. In December 1997, Murr asked for $520 
million, saying he advised Morales. 
</P>
<P>
	A state arbitration panel approved $260 million for him even  
though the other attorneys said Murr did little or no work on the 
case. 
</P>
<P>
	The subpoena orders current state Attorney General John Cornyn  
to provide correspondence, computer and phone records, and other 
information to a grand jury meeting June 15 in Austin. 
</P>
<P>
	``They are not telling us what they are doing, but they are  
obviously trying to determine whether the evidence we uncovered and 
believe amounts to civil fraud rises to the level of criminal 
fraud,'' Cornyn said. He succeeded Morales in January. 
</P>
<P>
	Last month, sources speaking on condition of anonymity told The  
Associated Press that the FBI had been comparing computer data to 
paper records to determine whether Morales backdated four contracts 
and letters to make it appear Murr was involved in the case longer 
than he really was. 
</P>
<P>
	In early May, Murr agreed to drop his claim to the $260 million  
agreed to the state panel and accept only $1 million recommended by 
a federal arbitration panel. That decision came just before a 
federal court hearing on whether the three members of the state 
panel were illegally selected because they were chosen by Murr and 
Morales. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, tobacco industry officials said they received an  
$82,000 check from Murr, reimbursing the companies for money paid 
so far as part of the $1 million award. 
</P>
<P>
	Murr has ended all efforts to seek payment for his role in the  
tobacco case and will not ask for any additional money, said his 
lawyer, Roy Minton. 
</P>
<P>
	Minton would not comment on the subpoena.  
</P>
<P>
	Morales did not immediately return a call for comment. In the  
past, he has denied all allegations of wrongdoing and said the 
accusations are politically calculated to prevent him from running 
for governor as a Democrat. Cornyn is a Republican. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
