<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Astronauts leaving space station </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla. (AP) -- Discovery's astronauts are leaving  
the new international space station a little cozier and quieter for 
those who will follow in the year ahead. 
</P>
<P>
	The space shuttle will pull away nearly 2 tons lighter Thursday  
evening after six days of linked flight. The seven astronauts began 
closing the station's hatches early Thursday after they finished 
carrying gear inside. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the more than 100 items they stowed aboard the two-room  
space station: laptop computers, water, clothes, trash bags and 
spare parts. 
</P>
<P>
	The astronauts got the place ready for its first permanent  
occupants, who are scheduled to move in next March. 
</P>
<P>
	``We spent a lot of this mission stowing supplies for them, so  
it should be pretty comfortable,'' said Ellen Ochoa, the astronaut 
in charge of all the moving. 
</P>
<P>
	Because no one will be back until December, one of the crew's  
last chores was to photograph every inch of the interior to help 
engineers on the ground solve any problems that might crop up. The 
astronauts also did a photo survey of the exterior one last time. 
</P>
<P>
	Astronaut Daniel Barry said Wednesday it was less noisy back in  
the Russian-made section of the space station than when the crew 
entered Sunday night, thanks to the mufflers he and others placed 
over clattering fans, ducts and outlets. Before the repairs, the 
noise level was equivalent to that of a busy street corner. 
</P>
<P>
	Barry said he measured the noise level at 65 to 69 decibels  
before the foam mufflers were installed. Afterward, it was about 3 
decibels lower. 
</P>
<P>
	Zarya is still noisier than the American-made section, called  
Unity, Barry said. ``But it certainly isn't a problem to be able to 
converse or do work in terms of the sorts of things we've been 
doing,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	NASA is far more concerned about the effects of noise on the  
astronauts who will spend months living aboard the space station. 
</P>
<P>
	The NASA engineer in charge of space station acoustics, Jerry  
Goodman, said before the mission that he wanted the noise level 
down to 60 decibels, which is what the specifications call for, or 
at least the low 60s. ``If you go much above that,'' he said, 
``you'll have to wear hearing protection.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Space shuttle Atlantis is supposed to carry up more supplies in  
December, but only if the Russians launch the station's living 
quarters in November as planned. Russia's economic crisis has 
stalled work on that piece, and the arrival of the first permanent 
crew is already almost two years behind schedule. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
