<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Brew Sets Sights on Breaking Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOISE, Idaho (AP) -- Each year since he was a junior in high  
school, Derrick Brew has clipped about one second per year off his 
400-meter time. 
</P>
<P>
	Should Brew do it again this season and dip under 44 seconds, he  
would move into some heady company. Only seven Americans have 
broken the 44-second barrier, led by world record-holder and 1988 
Olympic silver medalist Butch Reynolds' 43.29. 
</P>
<P>
	The others are 1996 Olympic gold medalist Michael Johnson, 1992  
Olympic champion Quincy Watts, 1992 Olympic trials winner Danny 
Everett, former world record-holder and 1968 Olympic winner Lee 
Evans, 1988 Olympic gold medalist Steve Lewis and 1968 Olympic 
silver medalist Larry James. 
</P>
<P>
	Brew had his sights set on Watts' NCAA meet record of 44.00 set  
in 1992, when he was competing for Southern California, in the 
national collegiate championships, which began today at Boise 
State's Bronco Field. The 400 final is Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	``If I go in with the same mindset as in the SEC championships  
... and if I get a good push and hold my line, I think I have a 
good shot at Watts' record,'' Brew said. 
</P>
<P>
	Although Brew is a junior at LSU, this is his first NCAA outdoor  
championship meet. He spent the past two years at Barton County 
Community College in Kansas. There, he won the 1998 national junior 
college outdoor championship in a record 44.53, a time that was 
eighth-best in the world last year. He also was the JUCO indoor 
champion and was ranked eighth in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1997, as a college freshman, he ran 45.21 and was the JUCO  
runner-up in the 400. In his final two scholastic years at Klein 
Forest High in Houston, he ran 47.40 and 46.63. As a senior, he won 
the Texas state championship and the national scholastic title. 
</P>
<P>
	This year, he owns the second-fastest time in the world, a  
career-best 44.29, in winning the Southeastern Conference title at 
Athens, Ga. He also won the SEC indoor championship and finished 
third at the NCAA indoors. 
</P>
<P>
	The overpowering performance outdoors -- he won by .80 seconds --  
added to Brew's confidence that he could become NCAA champion and 
LSU's first All-American in the 400 since Greg Hill in 1979. 
Earlier in the season, he got a big psychological boost by 
defeating defending NCAA champion Jerome Davis of Southern 
California in a U.S. Collegiate Track and Field Series meet at 
Baton Rouge, La. 
</P>
<P>
	He's not going into the NCAA meet overconfident, however.  
</P>
<P>
	``The 400 is hot this year,'' Brew said. ``In the SEC meet,  
there was one 44 (clocking) and five in the 45s.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Brew calls Johnson not only his idol, ``but the idol of all 400  
runners.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I like his style,'' Brew said. ``He impresses me. His 400,  
he's strong and he has lots of speed. He kills people in the final 
200. He goes out the first 200 in 21.1 and it doesn't look like 
he's running hard because he's run 19.32 for the 200. 
</P>
<P>
	``He runs upright, he has those short legs and he has lots of  
turnover.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Brew's aim is to run 21.3 for the opening 200, then turn on the  
speed in the second half of the race. 
</P>
<P>
	``The strongest part of my race is coming off the curve ... the  
final 150 meters,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't want to run faster than 21.1 for the first half. If I  
do, I could have problems the rest of the race.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Tigers haven't had an NCAA quarter-mile champion since 1934,  
when Glen Hardin won his second consecutive 440-yard title. 
</P>
<P>
	LSU is not favored to win the men's title, but with Brew's help  
could finish in the top five. Last year, the Tigers tied for fourth 
with Arizona, behind Arkansas, Stanford and TCU. 
</P>
<P>
	Arkansas is heavily favored to win its eighth consecutive  
championship. The women's title is expected to be a battle among 
defending champion Texas; LSU, which won 11 straight years before 
the Longhorns broke the streak last season; and UCLA. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990602.0259 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 13:20:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Olympic Official Blames U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAUSANNE, Switzerland (AP) -- A Chinese Olympic leader sent a  
blunt message Wednesday to Congress: Mind your own business. 
</P>
<P>
	He Zhenliang, China's senior delegate on the International  
Olympic Committee, accused Sen. John McCain of meddling in Olympic 
affairs to advance his White House ambitions. 
</P>
<P>
	``He knows nothing about Olympic Games,'' the official said of  
McCain. ``He used this for his own political purpose. This is 
political interference. Let the IOC deal with our own affairs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	As the IOC's new reform commission wrapped up its first round of  
meetings with moves toward democratic change, a backlash against 
U.S. politicians came to the fore. 
</P>
<P>
	McCain, an Arizona Republican and presidential contender, has  
been harshly critical of the IOC for its role in the vote-buying 
scheme stemming from Salt Lake's successful bid for the 2002 Winter 
Games. He chaired Senate hearings into the scandal in April. 
</P>
<P>
	The House Commerce Committee, meanwhile, is investigating  
Atlanta's winning bid for the 1996 Summer Games, while pressuring 
the White House to place the IOC under international anti-bribery 
laws. 
</P>
<P>
	And Congress has threatened to enact legislation that would  
cripple the IOC financially unless significant reforms are enacted. 
</P>
<P>
	In an interview with The Associated Press, He said it was ``very  
sad'' that U.S. politicians were involved in the Salt Lake 
scandal's aftermath ``because America has contributed so much to 
the Olympic movement.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``But if they interfere with sports for their own purpose, for  
their election campaigns, it will damage very seriously the image 
of American sports,'' He said. 
</P>
<P>
	In Washington, McCain dismissed He's criticism.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'll continue to be guided by the recommendations not of  
Chinese Olympics officials, but by (former) Sen. (George) Mitchell 
and his commission, whose considered views are respected in America 
and around the world,'' McCain said, referring to an inquiry on 
Olympic ethics headed by Mitchell, the former Senate majority 
leader. 
</P>
<P>
	He's comments, which echoed those of Olympic officials from  
Europe and Australia, came as Beijing pursues a bid for the 2008 
Summer Games. The Senate passed a resolution opposing Beijing's 
failed bid for the 2000 Games on human-rights grounds. 
</P>
<P>
	The issue of political interference emerged at the end of a  
two-day meeting that produced wide-ranging debate on ways of 
restructuring the IOC and changing the Olympic bidding and 
selection process. 
</P>
<P>
	IOC 2000, the reform commission, said the discussions  
underscored the need to ``move swiftly towards important reforms in 
areas such as democratization, ethics, representation and 
transparency.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The panel said athletes -- elected by active Olympic competitors  
-- should be on the IOC, and promised to quickly implement a new 
bidding system for the 2008 Summer Games. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the most important result of this meeting is that we  
realize that we need to change the structure of the IOC,'' 
president Juan Antonio Samaranch said. He said the change would be 
made by the end of 1999. 
</P>
<P>
	The commission, which is divided into three working groups, will  
submit a preliminary report June 20 at an IOC general assembly in 
Seoul, South Korea. Final recommendations are scheduled to be 
adopted in December. 
</P>
<P>
	Former Secretary of State Henry Kissinger, one of 36 outside  
members on the 80-member reform panel, said the IOC was moving in 
the right direction. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think it's a legitimate forum and I think serious efforts  
have been made,'' he said. ``And there are enough outsiders so you 
get a certain perspective. I think there will be significant 
progress made.'' 
</P>
<P>
	John MacAloon, an Olympic scholar at the University of Chicago  
and a member of the IOC 2000 panel, said he was amazed by the 
openness of the meetings. 
</P>
<P>
	``There hasn't been any taboo subject, including quite direct  
criticism by insiders as well as outsiders,'' he said. ``As far as 
having everything on the table, it's exceeded my expectations.'' 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. Olympic Committee president William Hybl said the most  
significant outcome was the commitment to bring 
democratically-elected athletes into the IOC ranks. 
</P>
<P>
	``They are a voice that will be a catalyst for change in years  
to come,'' Hybl said. 
</P>
<P>
	Delegates also pushed for greater representation on the IOC of  
women and leaders of international sports federations and national 
Olympic committees. 
</P>
<P>
	With as many as 10 cities preparing to run for the 2008 games,  
the working group on site selection backed a preselection process 
to weed out candidates failing to meet minimum technical 
requirements. 
</P>
<P>
	There was also discussion of possible continental rotation of  
the games and even a proposal to select two host cities, with one 
on standby in case of problems with the No. 1 choice. 
</P>
<P>
	In other developments:  
</P>
<P>
	-- Atlanta Olympic bidders revealed more details of the gifts and  
favors they used to win the 1996 Games, including $45,000 requested 
by disgraced African delegate Jean-Claude Ganga and a used bus that 
went to Peru. 
</P>
<P>
	Atlanta Olympic chief Billy Payne said he hoped the report to  
the House Commerce Committee will show the city won the games 
without resorting to the kinds of cash payments and extravagant 
gifts that sparked the Salt Lake scandal. 
</P>
<P>
	-- In Lausanne, Australian IOC member Phil Coles appeared for  
more than 2 1/2 hours before a special inquiry into alleged ethical 
misconduct. He expressed confidence that he had presented 
sufficient evidence to clear his name and avoid expulsion. 
</P>
<P>
	The three-member panel said it will report its findings to the  
IOC executive board in Seoul on June 14. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
