<HEADLINE> Bears Cut Veteran Andy Heck </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAKE FOREST, Ill. (AP) -- Tackle Andy Heck, the linchpin in the  
Bears offensive line for four years, was released Tuesday by the 
team. 
</P>
<P>
	The move, which was expected, saves the Bears Heck's base salary  
of $2.2 million under this year's salary cap and frees up money for 
rookie quarterback Cade McNown, the Bears first-round draft pick. 
</P>
<P>
	Heck, 32, has been a 10-year NFL starter since leaving Notre  
Dame. He was signed by Chicago as a free agent from the Seattle 
Seahawks in 1994. Troubled by back pain, his effectiveness declined 
last year and the Bears have tried unsuccessfully to trade him. 
</P>
<P>
	Chicago signed free agent Blake Brockermeyer from the Carolina  
Panthers to start at left tackle. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
