<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 06:24:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Sabres Focused on Stanley Cup Win </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) -- The Buffalo Sabres have the best record in  
the NHL playoffs. They have Dominik Hasek, the best goalie in the 
world, and they have speed and depth. 
</P>
<P>
	What they want is their names on the Stanley Cup.  
</P>
<P>
	The Sabres didn't celebrate after eliminating the Toronto Maple  
Leafs from the playoffs with a 4-2 win in Game 5 of the Eastern 
Conference finals on Monday night. 
</P>
<P>
	They couldn't get excited about the Prince of Wales Trophy. They  
didn't even want to touch it. 
</P>
<P>
	``It wasn't the Stanley Cup,'' Sabres captain Michael Peca  
explained. 
</P>
<P>
	The biggest series will be the Sabres against the winner of the  
Western Conference finals between Dallas and Colorado, now headed 
for a seventh game. 
</P>
<P>
	The Sabres have never won a Stanley Cup since they joined the  
NHL in 1970. 
</P>
<P>
	Buffalo players and fans are constantly reminded of the fact by  
three banners hanging in Marine Midland Arena for retired jersey 
numbers worn by the fabled French Connection line of Rene Robert, 
Rick Martin and Gilbert Perreault. 
</P>
<P>
	The three French Canadians teamed to give the Sabres 738 goals  
and 1,681 points from 1972 to 1979. 
</P>
<P>
	The finesse line led Buffalo to six playoff appearances and its  
only trip to the Stanley Cup finals in 1975. Their vulnerability 
was exposed when the Sabres lost in six games to Philadelphia's 
Broad Street Bullies. 
</P>
<P>
	Concluding that other teams lost to the Sabres by failing to  
keep up with the French Connection, Flyers coach Fred Shero sent 
out Bill Clement, Orest Kindrachuk and Bob Kelly to rough up the 
Buffalo stars and wear them down. 
</P>
<P>
	These Sabres have too much depth and muscle to be worn down.  
They soared through the playoffs without their leading scorer, 
Miroslav Satan. Buffalo also split the first two games in Toronto 
with backup Dwayne Roloson in net. 
</P>
<P>
	``The only reason we're still here is because of our depth,''  
said Sabres wing Dixon Ward, who finished the Maple Leafs with an 
empty-net goal in the closing seconds. 
</P>
<P>
	``Over the past few years, we've learned one or two lines and  
four or five defensemen won't win the Cup. We have 20 guys all 
going in the same direction.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Sabres are a blend of speed and toughness. Peca, one of the  
top checkers in the league, has made a career out of smothering 
opponents' top scorers. The list includes Ottawa's Alexei Yashin 
and Boston's Jason Allison. 
</P>
<P>
	Add to the list Maple Leafs center Mats Sundin, who had just one  
assist and one shot in Game 5. The Sabres also zoomed in on 
high-scoring veteran Steve Thomas and held him to no points in the 
deciding game. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was no secret that Thomas had a sore shoulder,'' Peca said.  
``You want to punish people and take away their effectiveness.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I thought we were capable of beating Buffalo, but we hit a  
bump in the road,'' Thomas said. 
</P>
<P>
	Rhett Warrener, who arrived in a March 23 trade with Florida for  
Mike Wilson, added some pop to the defense. 
</P>
<P>
	Former Washington Capitals forward Joe Juneau, who scored a goal  
to sink the Sabres and send Washington to the Stanley Cup finals 
last year, added finesse. 
</P>
<P>
	Power-play sniper Stu Barnes, acquired in a trade that sent  
disgruntled Matthew Barnaby to Pittsburgh, has come out of a slump. 
So has speedy Geoff Sanderson. 
</P>
<P>
	Everybody works. Everybody contributes something. Coach Lindy  
Ruff, a former blue-collar Sabres captain, demands it. 
</P>
<P>
	``Look at that team now; they made some changes,'' Toronto coach  
Pat Quinn said. ``They added talented players, and now they are 
doing things they didn't do before. They finish a lot of checks 
now. The Joe Juneaus, the Geoff Sandersons, they never finished any 
checks in their life, but they're doing it right now.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990602.0267 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 13:40:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Miller Takes His Shots at Ewing  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- About an hour after Reggie Miller hit the  
two free throws that won Game 2, he sat at the podium for his news 
conference and spotted Patrick Ewing entering in the room. 
</P>
<P>
	``As long as you make the last (shot), that's all that  
matters,'' Miller said. ``Right, Pat?'' 
</P>
<P>
	The jab was too easy for Miller to resist, coming after Ewing's  
last-gasp jumper hit the back of the rim. 
</P>
<P>
	After restraining himself for more than a week and not saying  
anything even remotely controversial, Miller struck with his first 
dig. And the remark figures to only fuel the animosity that makes 
the Pacers-Knicks rivalry such a great one. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's going to be a war,'' Ewing said.  
</P>
<P>
	Both teams took the day off Wednesday since the series, tied  
1-1, will not resume until Saturday at Madison Square Garden. 
</P>
<P>
	By then, the hostility will shift the other way -- most of it  
aimed squarely at the No. 1 Knick killer of the decade, Miller. 
</P>
<P>
	At Market Square Arena, the Knicks had to put up with taunting  
Indiana fans. Some of them behind the New York bench unleashed a 
stream of insults. Others showered the players with beer and hurled 
coins as they left the court. 
</P>
<P>
	During the game, the jeering of Ewing became so intense that he  
waved his arms in an emphatic ``bring it on'' gesture completely 
out of character for the 14-year veteran. At another point, Ewing 
mixed it up in a friendly manner with four Pacers fans sitting 
alongside the players' seats. 
</P>
<P>
	``They don't like me here,'' Ewing said.  
</P>
<P>
	Ewing's animated Rileyesque gesture, coming as it did when the  
Knicks were falling behind by 17 points, was somehow indicative of 
the confidence he and his team are playing with this postseason. 
</P>
<P>
	A month and a half ago, a 17-point deficit would have spelled  
certain doom for a team struggling to incorporate so many new 
additions and uncertain if it would make the playoffs -- or whether 
its coach would survive to see another day on the bench. 
</P>
<P>
	These days, however, there is a fearlessness and cockiness to  
the Knicks that has surprised the Pacers. 
</P>
<P>
	``We won, and it was not a pretty win, but a win is a win,''  
Antonio Davis said. ``New York will not go away. We must get ready 
to get in their house and go to work. We're looking forward to 
it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Most irritating to both teams was the way Game 2 was officiated  
by the veteran crew of Dick Bavetta, Hue Hollins and Joe Forte. New 
York was whistled for 40 fouls, including five on its point guards 
in the first nine minutes of the game. Miller hit the winning free 
throws with 2 seconds left after Chris Childs was whistled for his 
sixth foul. 
</P>
<P>
	``We let the officiating overwhelm us at first,'' Allan Houston  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Indiana's Rik Smits was limited to 13 minutes because of foul  
trouble, with a couple of the calls that went against him among the 
most questionable of the night. 
</P>
<P>
	After Miller made his free throws, New York had one last chance.  
Charlie Ward, a former Heisman-winning quarterback at Florida 
State, whipped a court-length pass to Ewing near the opposing free 
throw line. 
</P>
<P>
	Ewing wheeled and tossed up a high-arching shot that caromed off  
the rim. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a good look -- just missed,'' said coach Jeff Van Gundy,  
who contained himself when asked to comment on the officiating. 
</P>
<P>
	Larry Johnson, Childs and Chris Dudley fouled out, Kurt Thomas,  
Ewing and Ward had four apiece and Marcus Camby had five -- the last 
of which was a blocking foul with 31 seconds left that the Knicks 
strongly felt should have gone the other way. 
</P>
<P>
	``When your best players are sitting next to you,'' Van Gundy  
said, ``it's not a great feeling.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Said Childs: ``We took their best shot, and I'm pretty sure  
there's going to be more shots taken, but I'm telling you, this is 
a special, special group of guys. We have so much fight and 
determination in us. We're going to play to the end.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
