<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gant Keeps Spot in Phillies Lineup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Philadelphia Phillies manager Terry Francona  
confronted the hard facts: Ron Gant is batting .233, 100 points 
lower than Mike Lieberthal. Why not switch them in the batting 
order? 
</P>
<P>
	Not yet, says Francona, who is counting on Gant to come out of  
his season-long slump and become the No. 5 hitter the Phillies 
thought they were getting from St. Louis. 
</P>
<P>
	``Instead of trying to move Gant, I think we should try to get  
him to hit,'' Francona said Wednesday. ``I don't think we want him 
to hit .228 all season, but he still does things to help this 
ballclub.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Gant found himself in the middle of a firestorm during spring  
training, when he exchanged long-distance insults with Tony La 
Russa. The Cardinals manager, miffed that Gant claimed he'd been 
mistreated in St. Louis, said, ``All he ever did for us was whiff, 
whiff, whiff. I really hope he goes to Philly and whiffs for them 
like he whiffed for us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For a while, it seemed as though La Russa was right.  
</P>
<P>
	But despite his poor average, seven homers and 19 RBIs, Gant has  
shown signs of coming out of it lately. He battled back from an 0-2 
count and delivered a clutch RBI single in the Phillies' 6-5 
extra-inning loss to San Francisco on Tuesday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Gant also has showed himself to be a vastly improved outfielder,  
throwing out two runners in two innings Monday night and receiving 
an ovation when he got to the dugout. The small but vocal crowds at 
the Vet have been tough on Gant, but not unfair. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're not stupid,'' Gant said. ``They know I've been  
contributing, and they appreciate that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Gant went into Wednesday night's game against the Giants  
with 41 strikeouts in 159 at-bats. He seems to have an 0-2 count on 
him every time up. While it's worth wondering if Gant's days as a 
middle-of-the-order hitter are over, Francona said he's not giving 
up yet. 
</P>
<P>
	``If there's talk about moving me down, I don't know where that  
comes from,'' Gant said. ``I know what I can do. I just need to 
stay positive and keep progressing like I think I have.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lieberthal, a budding star with a .333 average and 10 homers, is  
the natural choice to take Gant's place behind cleanup hitter Rico 
Brogna. He currently bats seventh, but Francona said he doesn't 
want to put pressure on his catcher to produce at the plate. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you flip-flop them and Gant's still not hitting,'' Francona  
said, ``what kind of pitches is Lieberthal going to get to hit?'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
