<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> On Show: Homeless Treasures </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAIRO, Egypt (AP) -- Like orphans shuttling between relatives,  
Islamic treasures have traveled from one leading museum to another 
across Europe and America for nearly a decade. 
</P>
<P>
	The Egyptian perfume sprinkler, the Koranic manuscripts, the  
Ottoman rug and other priceless artworks owned by a royal Kuwaiti 
couple have nowhere to settle. Their home, the Kuwait National 
Museum, was burned down by Iraq's invading army in 1990. 
</P>
<P>
	Much of Kuwait has been reconstructed to its former glitz and  
chrome, but the four-building museum remains a charred wreck. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is a shame and an embarrassment. It seems culture is at the  
bottom of the government's priority,'' said Sheika Hussa al-Sabah, 
who owns the artifacts with her husband and had loaned them to the 
museum. Kuwait's emir is the couple's uncle, and they have an 
international real estate empire. 
</P>
<P>
	Fahad al-Wohaibi, director of the National Museum, told The  
Associated Press the government plans to rebuild part of the museum 
as soon as it can allocate the necessary $9.83 million. Kuwait has 
been dealing with unprecedented budget deficits because of low oil 
prices, the seven-month Iraqi occupation and the 1991 Gulf War. 
</P>
<P>
	After winning admiration on both sides of the Atlantic, the  
al-Sabah exhibition opened in Cairo last month, its debut in an 
Islamic country outside Kuwait. 
</P>
<P>
	On show until July 6 at Cairo's Mr. and Mrs. Mohammed Khalil  
Museum are some of the rarest and most beautiful artifacts spanning 
11 centuries -- 622-1800 -- of Islamic artistry culled from Spain to 
India. 
</P>
<P>
	Each object tells a historic tale:  
</P>
<P>
	--The jade pendant inscribed with gold was made for the  
17th-century Indian emperor Shah Jahan, who built the Taj Mahal. 
</P>
<P>
	--Two miniature paintings depict Persian king Bahram Gur's  
romance with seven princesses. He is shown visiting the princess of 
Maghrib in the turquoise pavilion on Wednesdays, and cavorting with 
the princess of Iran in the white pavilion on Fridays. 
</P>
<P>
	--A 1,000-year-old glass jug is thought to have adorned an  
Egyptian nobleman's buffet. Stunning in its simplicity, the jar's 
only decoration is on the neck where vertically stamped 
inscriptions repeat the words, ``enjoyable drinking.'' 
</P>
<P>
	--A unique illustration of a water clock design is from a 1315  
Syrian treatise on the construction of mechanical devices. Sheika 
Hussa and her husband had to sell two London apartments to buy it 
in an auction, outbidding several other institutions. 
</P>
<P>
	The varied pieces, separated by time and place, also have a  
collective tale to tell: A more poignant modern story of escape 
from Saddam Hussein's invaders. 
</P>
<P>
	During their seven-month occupation, the Iraqis looted the  
emirate of Kuwait of nearly everything that could be moved -- 
appliances, furniture, clothes, jewelry, food, even bathroom 
fixtures. 
</P>
<P>
	All the Kuwait National Museum's antiquities were carted to  
Baghdad and the building set on fire. 
</P>
<P>
	But just one week before the August 1990 invasion, 107 choice  
pieces from the al-Sabah collection were sent to Russia's State 
Hermitage Museum. 
</P>
<P>
	Since Iraq was forced to retreat, all but 59 of the 20,000  
pieces that were looted were retrieved through U.N. efforts. Twenty 
percent were partially or completely damaged. 
</P>
<P>
	With no place for display, many of the artifacts are being  
exhibited informally in Sheika Hussa's palatial home. Others are in 
storage or being restored. 
</P>
<P>
	Experts have hailed the exhibition as unique in presenting an  
overview of art since the inception of Islam. 
</P>
<P>
	``It gives you an idea of the mastery of craft in different  
material that was produced during all the centuries,'' said Lieve 
Vandenbulcke, a UNESCO conservator. She spoke from Kuwait, where 
she is working on damaged artworks. 
</P>
<P>
	Every artifact in the collection was bought by Sheika Hussa and  
her husband, Sheik Nasser Sabah al-Ahmed, from auction houses, 
dealers and the Thieves' Bazaar in Bombay, India. They began in 
1975 with a 14th-century Egyptian glass bottle from the Mameluke 
period. 
</P>
<P>
	``Ever since, it has been an obsession,'' Sheika Hussa said.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
