<HEADLINE> Clinton Pledges Help in Ark. Crash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COLORADO SPRINGS, Colo. (AP) -- President Clinton expressed the  
nation's sympathies today to the victims of the American Airlines 
crash near Little Rock, Ark. ``Our government is doing everything 
possible to aid the victims and help determine the cause of this 
tragedy,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	While flying to Colorado to deliver a commencement address,  
Clinton phoned Little Rock Mayor Jim Dailey for an update on the 
crash, said White House spokesman Joe Lockhart. 
</P>
<P>
	He said Dailey told Clinton that the crash scene gave him ``an  
awesome sense of the fragileness of life,'' adding, ``It was a 
miracle there weren't more deaths.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton replied, ``If there's anything we can do, just let us  
know. We're thinking about you and praying for you.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lockhart said Clinton learned that a friend, Nancy Wood, was on  
board the flight with her husband. Both survived. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton also issued a statement saying he and first lady Hillary  
Rodham Clinton were saddened by news of the crash. He said family 
assistance counselors and others were helping the National 
Transportation Safety Board and Federal Aviation Administration 
inspectors at the scene. 
</P>
<P>
	``We join the American people in extending our deepest  
sympathies to the families of those who died or were injured,'' 
Clinton said. ``I ask all Americans to remember in their prayers 
the passengers and their families.'' 


  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
