<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stonecutter Mills Closing 2 Plants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SPINDALE, N.C. (AP) -- Stonecutter Mills Inc. plans to close its  
plants in Rutherford and Polk counties and its office in New York 
on July 12, eliminating about 800 jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a death of a family,'' Jim Cowan, the Spindale-based  
company's chief executive, said yesterday. ``People who have worked 
together for nearly 80 years. It is hard. No one expected this. Not 
even me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stonecutter officials blame the North American Free Trade  
Agreement and a sharp downturn in new orders for the closings. 
NAFTA was established more than two years ago to eliminate trade 
barriers among the United States, Mexico and Canada. 
</P>
<P>
	The Rutherford County and Polk County manufacturing jobs are  
going to Mexico, Cowan said. 
</P>
<P>
	Stonecutter Mills' other businesses will continue to operate,  
Cowan said. The other operations, which employ 174 people, include 
Henson Timber, Mitchell Fabrics, Stonecutter Trucking and an 
engineering division. 
</P>
<P>
	Stonecutter is the third major textile plant owner to close  
mills since January. Dan River Inc. closed its doors in January, 
followed by the shutdown of Burlington Industries' J.C. Cowan plant 
in March. 
</P>
<P>
	In February, Cone Mills announced the layoff of 438 salaried and  
hourly employees. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
