<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Penguins Look To Up Season Tix Sales </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- Step right up, hockey fans, and lay down money  
for tickets for games that might not even happen. 
</P>
<P>
	The Pittsburgh Penguins, now operating with protection from  
creditors, could be moved to another city before the summer. Even 
so, the team is making a push to sell 12,000 season tickets and 
trying to capitalize on civic pride. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a very ambitious goal,'' David Andrews, the Penguins'  
chief operating officer, said Tuesday. ``But we hope to create a 
groundswell to demonstrate to the National Hockey League and to 
potential buyers Mario Lemieux and SMG-Fox that there is tremendous 
fan support for the Pens.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Fans who buy the tickets won't lose their money if the team  
moves. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Bernard Markovitz last week allowed the  
team to set up an escrow account to protect the money from 
creditors. If the Penguins move to another city, ticket buyers will 
get their money back. 
</P>
<P>
	The 1999-2000 season opens in October, but the team wants to  
sell as many season tickets as possible by June 24, a date 
Markovitz has set for deciding who will buy the team. 
</P>
<P>
	That way ``all fans, not just the creditors, will get a chance  
to vote, demonstrating the community is behind the team and the new 
ownership,'' Andrews wrote in a letter to city officials last week. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, 8,300 season tickets were sold. If fans buy 12,000  
season tickets this year, the team will have an easier time selling 
out the 17,000-seat Civic Arena for every home game. 
</P>
<P>
	Team managers settled on 12,000 because that is the number of  
season-ticket commitments required by the NHL from a city that 
wants an expansion franchise. 
</P>
<P>
	The team, which has hired a public relations firm to help in the  
ticket-selling effort, will allow fans to reserve a season-ticket 
plan for $25, then send in at least 10 percent of the cost within a 
month, said Penguins spokesman Tom McMillan. 
</P>
<P>
	Three plans to buy the team have been submitted to the judge.  
Two plans, one from former star center Lemieux and one from arena 
landlord SMG Inc. and broadcaster Fox Sports Net Pittsburgh, would 
keep the team in Pittsburgh. 
</P>
<P>
	Another from the NHL would either dissolve the team and auction  
player contracts or sell the team to one buyer -- reportedly Seattle 
billionaire Paul Allen -- who would move it to another city. 
</P>
<P>
	``As a community, we must take a stand against the NHL and their  
efforts to move or dissolve the Penguins,'' Andrews wrote. ``There 
is no more demonstrable way of doing so than by undertaking a 
measurable show of support, one that even the NHL will be forced to 
acknowledge.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
