<HEADLINE> Grains, Soybeans Mostly Lower / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Grain and soybean futures prices were mostly  
lower today on the Chicago Board of Trade after the government 
reported spring crops are in excellent condition. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. Agriculture Department reported corn crops were nearly  
completely planted, and 75 percent were in good to excellent 
condition. Losses were limited, however, amid heavy rainfall in the 
Midwest. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybean futures found support amid forecasts for warmer weather  
in growing areas next week that could stress young crops. But 
prices were pressured by speedy planting of what is expected to be 
record acreage. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat fell from harvesting pressure.  
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for July delivery fell 1/4 cent to $2.51 1/2 a bushel; July  
corn rose 1/4 cent to $2.16 1/2 a bushel; July oats fell 1/2 cent to 
$1.21 1/4 a bushel; July soybeans fell 1 1/4 cents to $4.56 3/4 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Live cattle and lean hog futures were mixed on the Chicago  
Mercantile Exchange. Feeder cattle retreated, while pork bellies 
rose. 
</P>
<P>
	June live cattle rose .07 cent to 64.57 cents a pound; August  
feeder cattle fell .22 cent to 75.65 cents a pound; June lean hogs 
fell .52 cent to 50.95 cents a pound; July pork bellies rose .35 
cent to 53.05 cents a pound. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
