<HEADLINE> Stocks Mostly Down; Dow Off 50.98 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mostly lower today as investors,  
increasingly worried about inflation, began preparing for a 
possible rise in interest rates when the Federal Reserve meets 
later this month. 
</P>
<P>
	At 3 p.m. on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was  
down 50.98 at 10,545.28. The index fell as much as 131.40 points 
earlier in the session, but regained some ground as investors 
sought bargains in the battered market. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators were mixed after spending much of the  
session in negative territory. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was 
down 1.73 at 1,292.53, and the Nasdaq composite index was up 6.18 
at 2,418.21. 
</P>
<P>
	Stocks began their decline this morning as traders awaited a  
speech by Fed Chairman Alan Greenspan at an international business 
conference in Boston. The market has been rattled for more than two 
weeks by persistent fears that the Fed will soon raise interest 
rates to cool off the booming economy. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, the Dow closed up 36.52 at 10,596.26 after falling  
as much as 150 points earlier in the session. 
</P>
<P>
	As Greenspan kept his remarks focused on trade, the Dow remained  
in a fairly narrow range. Market watchers, however, strained to 
catch any hints he might offer about the Fed's future course. 
</P>
<P>
	Alan Skrainka, chief market strategist at Edward Jones of St.  
Louis, said the market expects the Fed to raise interest rates when 
its Open Market Committee meets June 29. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Fed doesn't want to shock the system, so Greenspan's  
lieutenants have been warming us up for a while,'' he said. 
``People are selling on the rumor of a rate hike, so they may buy 
when the news hits.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bond prices continued their tumble, although the price of the  
benchmark 30-year Treasury bond recovered slightly by early 
afternoon. The 30-year bond was yielding 5.94 percent, down from 
5.97 in earlier trading. A yield of 6 percent is viewed as a 
critical point for stocks, because at that level, yields make bonds 
a more attractive investment. 
</P>
<P>
	Interest rate worries depressed bank and financial stocks today,  
with J.P. Morgan falling 3 1/2 at 130. The financial sector is 
especially vulnerable to higher interest rates because lending 
volume shrinks when it becomes more expensive to borrow. 
</P>
<P>
	Internet companies also tumbled until their weakened prices  
enticed some buyers. America Online dropped sharply in early 
trading, but is now up 1 1/2 at 114 5/8. 
</P>
<P>
	Online brokerages, however, mirrored their more conventional  
rivals and were mostly lower. DLJ Direct fell 3 3/4 to 35. 
</P>
<P>
	Bookseller Barnes &AMP; Noble rose 11/16 to 28 1/16 after it called  
off its planned acquisition of book distributor Ingram Book Group. 
The company's online wing, barnesandnoble.com, fell 3 to 17. 
</P>
<P>
	Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 3-to-2 margin on the  
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 581.7 million shares, 
ahead of Tuesday's quiet pace. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index was down 1.62 at 619.66, and the  
American Stock Exchange composite index was down 6.65 at 769.46. 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
