<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 21:20:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Calif. Reviews Internet Phone Rates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- State regulators may want more time to  
decide on a rate shift in Internet telephone charges, a proposal 
that could lead to higher fees for some Internet users in 
California. 
</P>
<P>
	A plan pushed by Pacific Bell to shift connection fees for such  
calls to a smaller phone company, which could pass them along to 
Internet service providers, had been scheduled for a vote at 
today's Public Utilities Commission meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	But the sponsor, Josiah Neeper, changed his proposal before the  
meeting so that it would require a full review and public comment 
before final PUC action, said Pacific Bell spokesman Bill Mashek. 
</P>
<P>
	Some legislators have urged the commission to postpone action  
and allow more time for a full debate on the effects on Internet 
charges and access. 
</P>
<P>
	A delay would also give Gov. Gray Davis more time to fill two  
vacancies on the five-member PUC, whose three current members were 
appointed by former Gov. Pete Wilson. 
</P>
<P>
	The commission voted 3-2 last October to maintain its current  
system, which treats Internet calls as local calls and requires 
Pacific Bell to pay a fee for their completion under its contracts 
with small phone companies. 
</P>
<P>
	But the terms of two commissioners, also Wilson appointees, have  
since expired. Both voted with the majority in October. 
</P>
<P>
	The eventual decision could set a precedent for other carriers  
that serve 600 Internet service providers in California. 
</P>
<P>
	The dispute involves Internet calls that start with the caller's  
local carrier, a field dominated by Pacific Bell. The call is 
passed along to the Internet service provider's carrier, typically 
a smaller company like Pac-West Telcomm, whose case was before the 
PUC today. 
</P>
<P>
	For handling the remainder of the call, Pacific Bell has been  
required, under past agreements, to pay a fee to Pac-West. 
</P>
<P>
	That arrangement was designed for the expected increase in  
competition among local carriers. When Internet traffic flourished 
among small phone companies, Pacific Bell protested that the fees 
were an improper subsidy and that the calls, often destined for 
remote Web sites, were long-distance calls for which no fee was 
required. 
</P>
<P>
	Pacific Bell started withholding its fee from Pac-West two years  
ago and has built up $50 million in an escrow account while the PUC 
considers its appeal. 
</P>
<P>
	Rick Bryson, chief financial officer of Stockton-based Pac-West,  
has said his company would have to increase rates to Internet 
service providers if it lost the Pacific Bell fees. 
</P>
<P>
	After last October's PUC vote to leave the interconnection fees  
intact, the Federal Communications Commission weighed in by 
declaring in January that Internet calls were long-distance. 
</P>
<P>
	However, the FCC specified that Internet callers would not have  
to pay long-distance rates and that state regulatory agencies 
remained free to allocate costs between the companies. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990602.0290 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-06-02 12:40:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Murder Mystery Shocks R.I. Town </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LITTLE COMPTON, R.I. (AP) -- Angela Spence-Shaw was struck on the  
head. Then the 66-year-old grandmother, clad in her nightgown, was 
dumped into her full bathtub. A plugged-in hair dryer was dropped 
into the water to electrocute her in case she had survived the 
beating. 
</P>
<P>
	The killer didn't bother to turn off the faucet, and by the time  
a friend found Mrs. Spence-Shaw's corpse the next morning, water 
was streaming down her dirt driveway. She apparently was killed 
Saturday night. 
</P>
<P>
	For a peaceful place that hadn't seen a murder in 34 years, a  
classic New England fishing and farming town with one general store 
and an inn, it's like an Agatha Christie novel or an episode of 
``Murder She Wrote.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators are trying to determine whether Mrs. Spence-Shaw,  
a widow who lived alone, died from the beating, drowned or was 
electrocuted. They said they have not been able to determine a 
motive. 
</P>
<P>
	Maj. Harold Watson, No. 2 official of the state police, said  
there were no obvious signs of robbery. He said relatives will be 
asked to see if anything is missing. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators are not saying whether a weapon was used in the  
beating or whether there was a struggle. The woman's two golden 
retrievers were unharmed. 
</P>
<P>
	The bucolic, seaside town is considered one of the safest  
communities in Rhode Island. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have maybe eight to 10 break-ins a year and a few domestic  
assaults,'' said Police Chief Egbert D. Hawes Jr. 
</P>
<P>
	Some residents don't even bother to lock their doors at night.  
Now, ``they're crazy if they don't,'' said Town Council President 
Jane Cabot. 
</P>
<P>
	Little Compton, established in 1674 by settlers from Plymouth  
Colony, is relatively isolated in the state's southeastern corner. 
The grassy Town Common is surrounded by houses, a Town Hall, a 
150-year-old church and a cemetery with 17th-century graves. 
</P>
<P>
	The year-round population of fewer than 3,400 doubles in summer,  
but mostly with people who own their own homes, not casual 
visitors. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Spence-Shaw and her husband, Peter VanCleve Shaw, moved  
here several years ago from Norton, Mass., where he had operated a 
store. He was active in local government; she was an avid gardener 
and got a job at a greenhouse. He died in 1991. 
</P>
<P>
	The couple's son, daughter-in-law and twin grandchildren live in  
nearby Bristol, and Mrs. Spence-Shaw baby-sat for her grandchildren 
on Tuesdays. 
</P>
<P>
	Last Saturday, Mrs. Spence-Shaw drove to Bristol for dinner with  
her son and his family. The next morning, a co-worker became 
concerned when Mrs. Spence-Shaw didn't show up as scheduled. The 
co-worker drove to her house and discovered the body. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everybody is very upset, very concerned about who would have  
done it,'' Cabot said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
